{"title_page": "Such Pretty Forks in the Road", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Such Pretty Forks in the Road\n| type         = studio\n| cover        = Alanis Morissette - Such Pretty Forks in the Road.png\n| alt          =\n| artist       = [[Alanis Morissette]]\n| released     =  2020\n| recorded     = <!-- Please source recording dates/years -->\n| studio       =\n| genre        = \n| length     =\n| label        =\n* Epiphany\n* [[Thirty Tigers]] (USA); Epiphany/[[RCA]] Records Germany GmbH (Europe)\n| producer    = [[Alex Hope (songwriter)|Alex Hope]], [[Catherine Marks]]\n| prev_title   = [[Live at Montreux 2012]]\n| prev_year    = 2013\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Such Pretty Forks in the Road\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Reasons I Drink]]\n | single1date = December 2, 2019\n | single2     = [[Smiling (song)|Smiling]]\n | single2date = February 21, 2020\n }}\n}}\n'''''Such Pretty Forks in the Road''''' is the upcoming ninth (and seventh international) studio album by Canadian-American singer-songwriter [[Alanis Morissette]], set to be released through Epiphany Music and [[Thirty Tigers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://store.alanis.com/|title=Alanis Morissette|first=Alanis|last=Morissette|website=Alanis Morissette}}</ref> It is Morissette's first studio album in eight years, following 2012's ''[[Havoc and Bright Lights]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6243209/alanis-morissette-jagged-little-pill-anniversary-tour-2020/|title=Alanis Morissette announces 'Jagged Little Pill' tour, 1 Canadian date|work=[[Global News]]|last=Wallis|first=Adam|date=December 2, 2019|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> The album was preceded by the singles \"[[Reasons I Drink]]\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/music/alanis-morissette-announces-new-album-hear-lead-single-reasons-i-drink-1.5380694|title=Alanis Morissette announces new album, hear lead single 'Reasons I Drink'|website=[[CBC.ca]]|last=Lau|first=Melody|date=December 2, 2019|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> and \"[[Smiling (song)|Smiling]]\", the latter being a new song written for the ''[[Jagged Little Pill (musical)|Jagged Little Pill]]'' stage musical.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereoboard.com/content/view/227436/9|title=Alanis Morissette Announces 'Jagged Little Pill' UK And European Arenas Shows \u2013 How To Buy Tickets|website=Stereoboard|last=Johnson|first=Laura|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nMorissette had been working on the album since at least Mid-2017. In August of 2017 on [[Anna Faris]]' podcast [[Unqualified (podcast)|Unqualified]], Morissette revealed the name of a new song called \"Reckoning.\" She described this song as \"patriarchy falling down,\" and said it was in reference to her day in court in regards to her embezzlement trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://unqualified.com/episodes/ep-87-alanis-morissette-jMGb3avH |title=Episode 87 |publisher=unqualified.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-cdca/pr/cpa-sentenced-6-years-federal-prison-embezzling-72-million-alanis-morissette-and-other|title=CPA Sentenced to 6 years in Federal Prison for Embezzling $7.2 Million from Alanis Morissette and Other Celebrities|date=May 4, 2017|website=www.justice.gov}}</ref> In early October of 2017, on her own podcast Conversation with Alanis Morissette, she detailed a new song called \"Diagnosis,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hi8qdTg1nyA |title=Episode 10: Conversation with Alanis Morissette & Karen Kleiman |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> in which she describes [[Postpartum depression]] and how she felt better when she knew what was going on with herself.  Later that month at [[Linkin Park and Friends: Celebrate Life in Honor of Chester Bennington]], Morissette was invited as a guest to perform [[Castle of Glass]] and a new song of hers called \"Rest.\" She detailed that she had been working with [[Michael Farrell (musician)|Mike Farrell]] and writing new demos.\n\nIn March of 2018, Morissette previewed another new song from the album called \"Ablaze,\" dedicated to her children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xOi3uY0XAz0 |title=Alanis Morissette - Ablaze (Acoustic) - New Song - Shawnee OK 3/16/2018 |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> In August of 2018 on [[Laura Whitmore]]'s Sunday Session on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], she detailed that the new album would be a \"piano record,\" and that \"Rest\" would make the final cut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p06gcfks|title=BBC Radio 5 live - Laura Whitmore, Alanis Morissette|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn August of 2019, Morissette revealed that she is working with [[Alex Hope (songwriter)|Alex Hope]] and [[Catherine Marks]] on her as-of-then untitled record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B06R937Hypq/|title=Alanis Morissette\u2019s Instagram photo: \u201cjugular and soul deep into new record. produced by @alexhopemusic and @cjmarks #deepdivingtogether \u2764\ufe0f #notitleyet \u2728\u2728\u2728\u201d|website=Instagram}}</ref> Morissette officially announced the album in December 2019, also debuting \"Reasons I Drink\" and the song \"Smiling\" during a performance at the [[Apollo Theater]] in [[New York City]] on December 2, the latter of which was called \"sanguine\" by Suzy Exposito of ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/alanis-morissette-jagged-little-pill-apollo-theater-920863/|title=A Buoyant Alanis Morissette Performs 'Jagged Little Pill,' Debuts New Songs at Apollo Theater|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|date=December 3, 2019|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nMorissette will embark on a world tour for the 25th anniversary of her 1995 album ''[[Jagged Little Pill]]'' in June 2020, during which she will perform songs from the rest of her career, including songs from ''Such Pretty Forks in the Road''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/12/alanis-morissette-jagged-little-pill-tour/|title=Alanis Morissette announces Jagged Little Pill 25th anniversary tour|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Young|first=Alex|date=December 3, 2019|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Such Pretty Forks in the Road'' track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1 = [[Smiling (song)|Smiling]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Alanis Morissette]]|[[Michael Farrell (musician)|Michael Farrell]]}}\n| extra1 = [[Alex Hope (songwriter)|Alex Hope]]\n| length1 = 4:17\n\n| title2 = Ablaze\n| length2 = 3:57\n\n| title3 = [[Reasons I Drink]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Morissette|Farrell}}\n| extra3 = Hope\n| length3 = 3:36\n\n| title4 = Diagnosis\n| length4 = 4:49\n\n| title5 = Missing the Miracle\n| length5 = 3:33\n\n| title6 = Losing the Plot\n| length6 = 3:57\n\n| title7 = Reckoning\n| length7 = 3:30\n\n| title8 = Sandbox Love\n| length8 = 4:12\n\n| title9 = Her\n| length9 = 4:10\n\n| title10 = Nemesis\n| length10 = 5:56\n\n| title11 = Pedestal\n| length11 = 4:08\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Alanis Morissette}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Alanis Morissette albums]]\n[[Category:Upcoming albums]]\n[[Category:Thirty Tigers albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Alex Hope (songwriter)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Catherine Marks]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n\n{{2020s-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = Such Pretty Forks in the Road\n| type         = studio\n| cover        = Alanis Morissette - Such Pretty Forks in the Road.png\n| alt          =\n| artist       = [[Alanis Morissette]]\n| released     =  2020\n| recorded     = <!-- Please source recording dates/years -->\n| studio       =\n| genre        = \n| length     =\n| label        =\n* Epiphany\n* [[Thirty Tigers]] (USA); Epiphany/[[RCA]] Records Germany GmbH (Europe)\n| producer    = [[Alex Hope (songwriter)|Alex Hope]], [[Catherine Marks]]\n| prev_title   = [[Live at Montreux 2012]]\n| prev_year    = 2013\n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = Such Pretty Forks in the Road\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Reasons I Drink]]\n | single1date = December 2, 2019\n | single2     = [[Smiling (song)|Smiling]]\n | single2date = February 21, 2020\n }}\n}}\n'''''Such Pretty Forks in the Road''''' is the upcoming ninth (and seventh international) studio album by Canadian-American singer-songwriter [[Alanis Morissette]], set to be released through Epiphany Music and [[Thirty Tigers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://store.alanis.com/|title=Alanis Morissette|first=Alanis|last=Morissette|website=Alanis Morissette}}</ref> It is Morissette's first studio album in eight years, following 2012's ''[[Havoc and Bright Lights]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6243209/alanis-morissette-jagged-little-pill-anniversary-tour-2020/|title=Alanis Morissette announces 'Jagged Little Pill' tour, 1 Canadian date|work=[[Global News]]|last=Wallis|first=Adam|date=December 2, 2019|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> The album was preceded by the singles \"[[Reasons I Drink]]\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/music/alanis-morissette-announces-new-album-hear-lead-single-reasons-i-drink-1.5380694|title=Alanis Morissette announces new album, hear lead single 'Reasons I Drink'|website=[[CBC.ca]]|last=Lau|first=Melody|date=December 2, 2019|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> and \"[[Smiling (song)|Smiling]]\", the latter being a new song written for the ''[[Jagged Little Pill (musical)|Jagged Little Pill]]'' stage musical.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stereoboard.com/content/view/227436/9|title=Alanis Morisette Announces 'Jagged Little Pill' UK And European Arenas Shows \u2013 How To Buy Tickets|website=Stereoboard|last=Johnson|first=Laura|date=February 21, 2020|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nMorissette had been working on the album since at least Mid-2017. In August of 2017 on [[Anna Faris]]' podcast [[Unqualified (podcast)|Unqualified]], Morissette revealed the name of a new song called \"Reckoning.\" She described this song as \"patriarchy falling down,\" and said it was in reference to her day in court in regards to her embezzlement trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://unqualified.com/episodes/ep-87-alanis-morissette-jMGb3avH |title=Episode 87 |publisher=unqualified.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-cdca/pr/cpa-sentenced-6-years-federal-prison-embezzling-72-million-alanis-morissette-and-other|title=CPA Sentenced to 6 years in Federal Prison for Embezzling $7.2 Million from Alanis Morissette and Other Celebrities|date=May 4, 2017|website=www.justice.gov}}</ref> In early October of 2017, on her own podcast Conversation with Alanis Morissette, she detailed a new song called \"Diagnosis,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hi8qdTg1nyA |title=Episode 10: Conversation with Alanis Morissette & Karen Kleiman |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> in which she describes [[Postpartum depression]] and how she felt better when she knew what was going on with herself.  Later that month at [[Linkin Park and Friends: Celebrate Life in Honor of Chester Bennington]], Morissette was invited as a guest to perform [[Castle of Glass]] and a new song of hers called \"Rest.\" She detailed that she had been working with [[Michael Farrell (musician)|Mike Farrell]] and writing new demos.\n\nIn March of 2018, Morissette previewed another new song from the album called \"Ablaze,\" dedicated to her children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xOi3uY0XAz0 |title=Alanis Morissette - Ablaze (Acoustic) - New Song - Shawnee OK 3/16/2018 |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2020-04-17}}</ref> In August of 2018 on [[Laura Whitmore]]'s Sunday Session on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], she detailed that the new album would be a \"piano record,\" and that \"Rest\" would make the final cut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p06gcfks|title=BBC Radio 5 live - Laura Whitmore, Alanis Morissette|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\nIn August of 2019, Morissette revealed that she is working with [[Alex Hope (songwriter)|Alex Hope]] and [[Catherine Marks]] on her as-of-then untitled record.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B06R937Hypq/|title=Alanis Morissette\u2019s Instagram photo: \u201cjugular and soul deep into new record. produced by @alexhopemusic and @cjmarks #deepdivingtogether \u2764\ufe0f #notitleyet \u2728\u2728\u2728\u201d|website=Instagram}}</ref> Morissette officially announced the album in December 2019, also debuting \"Reasons I Drink\" and the song \"Smiling\" during a performance at the [[Apollo Theater]] in [[New York City]] on December 2, the latter of which was called \"sanguine\" by Suzy Exposito of ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-live-reviews/alanis-morissette-jagged-little-pill-apollo-theater-920863/|title=A Buoyant Alanis Morissette Performs 'Jagged Little Pill,' Debuts New Songs at Apollo Theater|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Exposito|first=Suzy|date=December 3, 2019|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Promotion==\nMorissette will embark on a world tour for the 25th anniversary of her 1995 album ''[[Jagged Little Pill]]'' in June 2020, during which she will perform songs from the rest of her career, including songs from ''Such Pretty Forks in the Road''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/12/alanis-morissette-jagged-little-pill-tour/|title=Alanis Morissette announces Jagged Little Pill 25th anniversary tour|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|last=Young|first=Alex|date=December 3, 2019|accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|headline = ''Such Pretty Forks in the Road'' track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n\n| title1 = [[Smiling (song)|Smiling]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Alanis Morissette]]|[[Michael Farrell (musician)|Michael Farrell]]}}\n| extra1 = [[Alex Hope (songwriter)|Alex Hope]]\n| length1 = 4:17\n\n| title2 = Ablaze\n| length2 = 3:57\n\n| title3 = [[Reasons I Drink]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Morissette|Farrell}}\n| extra3 = Hope\n| length3 = 3:36\n\n| title4 = Diagnosis\n| length4 = 4:49\n\n| title5 = Missing the Miracle\n| length5 = 3:33\n\n| title6 = Losing the Plot\n| length6 = 3:57\n\n| title7 = Reckoning\n| length7 = 3:30\n\n| title8 = Sandbox Love\n| length8 = 4:12\n\n| title9 = Her\n| length9 = 4:10\n\n| title10 = Nemesis\n| length10 = 5:56\n\n| title11 = Pedestal\n| length11 = 4:08\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Alanis Morissette}}\n\n[[Category:2020 albums]]\n[[Category:Alanis Morissette albums]]\n[[Category:Upcoming albums]]\n[[Category:Thirty Tigers albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Alex Hope (songwriter)]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Catherine Marks]]\n[[Category:RCA Records albums]]\n\n{{2020s-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: morisette->Morissette", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Such_Pretty_Forks_in_the_Road"}
{"title_page": "Nick Groff", "text_new": "{{COI|date=February 2020}}\n{{notability|date=March 2020}}\n'''Nicholas Joshua Groff''' (born April 19, 1980) is an American [[paranormal investigation|paranormal investigator]], musician, and television personality. Groff was the lead investigator for the television series ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]].'' He was a co-investigator, executive producer, editor and cameraman on ''[[Ghost Adventures]]'' from seasons 1\u201310.\n\n==Early life==\nTwo years later, while at home alone, he says he saw a ghostly black figure. In a 2012 interview, Groff questioned, \"Was it my imagination? Or was it something from my accident that made me more open to their world?\"<ref name=\"lex\">{{cite news |url=https://www.kentucky.com/entertainment/movies-news-reviews/article44379003.html |title=Scarefest 2012: 'Ghost Adventures' host fell into his career |last=Copley |first=Rich |date=September 27, 2012 |work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]] |publisher=[[The McClatchy Company]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===''Ghost Adventures''===\n{{Main|Ghost Adventures}}\nIn 2004, Groff teamed up with [[Zak Bagans]] and [[Ghost Adventures#Aaron Goodwin|Aaron Goodwin]] to produce a documentary-style series called ''[[Ghost Adventures (2004)|Ghost Adventures]]''.  On November 24, 2014, Groff announced that he would not be returning to ''Ghost Adventures'' for the upcoming season.<ref name=\"axs\">{{cite web |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161026150640/http://www.axs.com/nick-groff-tells-ghost-adventures-fans-he-is-leaving-the-show-30922 |url=http://www.axs.com/nick-groff-tells-ghost-adventures-fans-he-is-leaving-the-show-30922 |title=Nick Groff tells ''Ghost Adventures'' fans he is leaving the show |date= 1 December 2014 |accessdate=24 June 2015 | archive-date= 26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Other projects===\nGroff has since produced his own series; ''[[Ghost Stalkers]]'' (2014) and ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]]'' (2016\u20132019), where he was the lead investigator and executive producer.<ref name=\"axs\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nGroff married his wife Veronique, in 2004 in Las Vegas. Groff befriended [[Zak Bagans]] during his wedding. <ref name=\"lvrj\">{{cite news |url=http://www.lvrj.com/living/paranormal-encounters-spook--ghost-adventures--trio-104659404.html |title=Life on the Couch: Paranormal encounters spook 'Ghost Adventures' trio |last=Lawrence |first=Christopher |date=October 10, 2010 |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |publisher=[[Stephens Media (newspapers)|Stephens Media]]}}</ref><ref name=\"nashua\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nashuatelegraph.com/livinglifestyles/882559-224/former-nashuan-has-successful-tv-series-hunting.html |title=Former Nashuan has successful TV series hunting ghosts |last=Meighan |first=Patrick |date=October 17, 2010 |work=[[The Telegraph (Nashua)|Nashua Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Publishing Company |accessdate=17 October 2010 |location=[[Nashua, New Hampshire]]}}</ref> Groff and his wife reside outside of [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]<ref name=shock>{{cite web|work=Shock Ya!|url=http://www.shockya.com/news/2016/10/30/new-york-comic-con-2016-interview-nick-groff-katrina-weidman-and-rob-saffi-talk-paranormal-lockdown/|title=New York Comic-Con 2016 Interview: Nick Groff, Katrina Weidman and Rob Saffi Talk Paranormal Lockdown\n|author=Benardello, Karen|date=October 30, 2016|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Film\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Ghost Adventures''\n| Himself, also executive producer\n| \n|-\n| 2008\n| Primo\n| Boris\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Television\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2008\u20132014\n| ''[[Ghost Adventures]]''\n| Himself, also executive producer\n| 138 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Vegas Stripped''\n| Executive producer\n| 9 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Nightline]]''\n| Himself\n| Guest\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Ghost Stalkers]]''\n| Executive producer\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| ''Ghosts of Shepherdstown''\n| Himself\n| 15 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u20132019\n| ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]]''\n| Himself, also executive producer\n| 47 episodes and 10 specials  \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]''\n| Himself\n| Guest\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1530005|name=Nick Groff}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Groff, Nick}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American documentary film directors]]\n[[Category:American documentary film producers]]\n[[Category:American musicians]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American reality television producers]]\n[[Category:American television hosts]]\n[[Category:Male actors from San Jose, California]]\n[[Category:Paranormal investigators]]\n[[Category:People from Nashua, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:University of Nevada, Las Vegas alumni]]\n[[Category:Ghost Adventures]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Television producers from California]]\n[[Category:Film producers from California]]\n", "text_old": "{{COI|date=February 2020}}\n{{notability|date=March 2020}}\n'''Nicholas Joshua Groff''' (born April 19, 1980) is an American [[paranormal investigation|paranormal investigator]], musician, and television personality. Groff was the lead investigator for the television series ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]].'' He was a co-investigator, executive producer, editor and cameraman on ''[[Ghost Adventures]]'' from seasons 1\u201310.\n\n==Early life==\nTwo years later, while at home alone, he says he saw a ghostly black figure. In a 2012 interview, Groff questioned, \"Was it my imagination? Or was it something from my accident that made me more open to [[African-American_culture|their world]]?\"<ref name=\"lex\">{{cite news |url=https://www.kentucky.com/entertainment/movies-news-reviews/article44379003.html |title=Scarefest 2012: 'Ghost Adventures' host fell into his career |last=Copley |first=Rich |date=September 27, 2012 |work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]] |publisher=[[The McClatchy Company]]}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===''Ghost Adventures''===\n{{Main|Ghost Adventures}}\nIn 2004, Groff teamed up with [[Zak Bagans]] and [[Ghost Adventures#Aaron Goodwin|Aaron Goodwin]] to produce a documentary-style series called ''[[Ghost Adventures (2004)|Ghost Adventures]]''.  On November 24, 2014, Groff announced that he would not be returning to ''Ghost Adventures'' for the upcoming season.<ref name=\"axs\">{{cite web |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20161026150640/http://www.axs.com/nick-groff-tells-ghost-adventures-fans-he-is-leaving-the-show-30922 |url=http://www.axs.com/nick-groff-tells-ghost-adventures-fans-he-is-leaving-the-show-30922 |title=Nick Groff tells ''Ghost Adventures'' fans he is leaving the show |date= 1 December 2014 |accessdate=24 June 2015 | archive-date= 26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Other projects===\nGroff has since produced his own series; ''[[Ghost Stalkers]]'' (2014) and ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]]'' (2016\u20132019), where he was the lead investigator and executive producer.<ref name=\"axs\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nGroff married his wife Veronique, in 2004 in Las Vegas. Groff befriended [[Zak Bagans]] during his wedding. <ref name=\"lvrj\">{{cite news |url=http://www.lvrj.com/living/paranormal-encounters-spook--ghost-adventures--trio-104659404.html |title=Life on the Couch: Paranormal encounters spook 'Ghost Adventures' trio |last=Lawrence |first=Christopher |date=October 10, 2010 |work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] |publisher=[[Stephens Media (newspapers)|Stephens Media]]}}</ref><ref name=\"nashua\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nashuatelegraph.com/livinglifestyles/882559-224/former-nashuan-has-successful-tv-series-hunting.html |title=Former Nashuan has successful TV series hunting ghosts |last=Meighan |first=Patrick |date=October 17, 2010 |work=[[The Telegraph (Nashua)|Nashua Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Publishing Company |accessdate=17 October 2010 |location=[[Nashua, New Hampshire]]}}</ref> Groff and his wife reside outside of [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]]<ref name=shock>{{cite web|work=Shock Ya!|url=http://www.shockya.com/news/2016/10/30/new-york-comic-con-2016-interview-nick-groff-katrina-weidman-and-rob-saffi-talk-paranormal-lockdown/|title=New York Comic-Con 2016 Interview: Nick Groff, Katrina Weidman and Rob Saffi Talk Paranormal Lockdown\n|author=Benardello, Karen|date=October 30, 2016|accessdate=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Film\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Ghost Adventures''\n| Himself, also executive producer\n| \n|-\n| 2008\n| Primo\n| Boris\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Television\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2008\u20132014\n| ''[[Ghost Adventures]]''\n| Himself, also executive producer\n| 138 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Vegas Stripped''\n| Executive producer\n| 9 episodes\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Nightline]]''\n| Himself\n| Guest\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Ghost Stalkers]]''\n| Executive producer\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| ''Ghosts of Shepherdstown''\n| Himself\n| 15 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u20132019\n| ''[[Paranormal Lockdown]]''\n| Himself, also executive producer\n| 47 episodes and 10 specials  \n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The View (talk show)|The View]]''\n| Himself\n| Guest\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1530005|name=Nick Groff}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Groff, Nick}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American documentary film directors]]\n[[Category:American documentary film producers]]\n[[Category:American musicians]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American reality television producers]]\n[[Category:American television hosts]]