/ref>\n* Conservative replication would leave the two original template DNA strands together in a [[double helix]] and would produce a copy composed of two new strands containing all of the new DNA base pairs.<ref name=\"Griffiths_1999\" />\n* Dispersive replication would produce two copies of the DNA, both containing distinct regions of DNA composed of either both original strands or both new strands.<ref name=\"Griffiths_1999\" /> The strands of DNA were originally thought to be broken at every tenth base pair to add the new DNA template. Eventually, all new DNA would make up the double helix after many generations of replication.<ref name = \"Watson_2014\" />\n\n== Separation and recombination of double-stranded DNA ==\nFor semiconservative replication to occur, the DNA double-helix needs to be separated so the new template strand can be bound to the complementary base pairs. [[Topoisomerase]] is the enzyme that aids in the unzipping and recombination of the double-helix. Specifically, topoisomerase prevents the double-helix from supercoiling, or becoming too tightly wound. Three topoisomerase enzymes are involved in this process: [[Type I topoisomerase|Type IA Topoisomerase]], [[Type I topoisomerase|Type IB Topoisomerase]], and [[Type II topoisomerase|Type II Topoisomerase]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Brown |first=Terence A. | name-list-format = vanc | chapter-url= https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK21113/ |chapter = Genome Replication | title = Genomes | edition = 2nd|date=2002|publisher=Wiley-Liss }}</ref> Type I Topoisomerase unwinds double stranded DNA while Type II Topoisomerase breaks the [[Hydrogen bond|hydrogen bonds]] linking the complementary base pairs of DNA.<ref name = \"Watson_2014\">{{cite book | first1 = James D | last1 = Watson | first2 = Alexander | last2 = Gann | first3 = Tania A | last3 = Baker | first4 = Michael | last4 = Levine | first5 = Stephen P | last5 = Bell | first6 = Richard | last6 = Losick | name-list-format = vanc | date = 2014 |title=Molecular Biology of the Gene |isbn=978-0-321-76243-6 |edition=Seventh |location=Boston |oclc=824087979}}</ref>\n\n== Rate and accuracy ==\nThe rate of semiconservative DNA replication in a living cell was first measured as the rate of the T4 phage DNA strand elongation in phage-infected ''E. coli''.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = McCarthy D, Minner C, Bernstein H, Bernstein C | title = DNA elongation rates and growing point distributions of wild-type phage T4 and a DNA-delay amber mutant | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 106 | issue = 4 | pages = 963\u201381 | date = October 1976 | pmid = 789903 | doi = 10.1016/0022-2836(76)90346-6 }}</ref>  During the period of exponential DNA increase at 37&nbsp;\u00b0C, the rate of strand elongation was 749 nucleotides per second.  The mutation rate per base pair per round of replication during phage T4 DNA synthesis is {{val|2.4|e=\u22128}}.<ref name=\"pmid9560386\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Drake JW, Charlesworth B, Charlesworth D, Crow JF | title = Rates of spontaneous mutation | journal = Genetics | volume = 148 | issue = 4 | pages = 1667\u201386 | date = April 1998 | pmid = 9560386 | pmc = 1460098 | doi =  }}</ref>  Thus semiconservative DNA replication is both rapid and accurate.\n\n== Applications ==\nSemiconservative replication provides many advantages for DNA. It is not only fast and accurate,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = McCarthy D, Minner C, Bernstein H, Bernstein C | title = DNA elongation rates and growing point distributions of wild-type phage T4 and a DNA-delay amber mutant | journal = Journal of Molecular Biology | volume = 106 | issue = 4 | pages = 963\u201381 | date = October 1976 | pmid = 789903 | doi = 10.1016/0022-2836(76)90346-6 }}</ref> but it has been found to allow DNA to be repaired easily and is responsible for [[Phenotype|phenotypic]] diversity in a few prokaryotic species. The process of creating a newly synthesized strand from the template strand allows for the old strand to be [[Methylation|methylated]] at a separate time from the new strand. This allows repair enzymes to proofread the new strand and correct any [[Mutation|mutations]] or errors.<ref name=\"Norris_2019\" />\n\nDNA could have the ability to activate or deactivate certain areas on the newly synthesized strand that allows the [[phenotype]] of the cell to be changed. This could be advantageous for the cell because DNA could activate a more favorable phenotype to aid in survival. Due to [[natural selection]], the more favorable phenotype would persist throughout the species. This gives rise to the idea of inheritance, or why certain phenotypes are inherited over another,<ref name=\"Norris_2019\" /> \n\n== See also ==\n*[[Molecular Structure of Nucleic Acids: A Structure for Deoxyribose Nucleic Acid]]\n*[[DNA replication]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|32em}}\n\n[[Category:DNA replication]]\n", "name_user": "AMYCREYNOLDS", "label": "safe", "comment": "Made grammatical corrections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semiconservative_replication"}
{"title_page": "St Andrews Castle", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|St Andrew's Castle, Hamble}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n|name=St. Andrews Castle\n|location=[[St. Andrews]], [[Fife]], [[Scotland]]\n|image=[[Image:General view of castle from SE.jpg|250px]]\n|caption=St Andrews castle ruins\n|map_type = UK Scotland\n|map_relief= 1\n|map_caption = Shown within Scotland\n|coordinates = {{coord|56.34|-2.79|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n|map_size=220\n|type=\n|built=c.1200\n|builder=[[Bishop Roger|Roger de Beaumont]]\n|controlledby=Bishops of St Andrews\n|materials=stone\n|height=\n|used=Until c.1689\n|condition=Ruined\n|ownership=[[Historic Environment Scotland]]\n|open_to_public= Yes\n}}\n\n'''St Andrews Castle''' is a [[ruin]] located in the coastal [[Royal Burgh of St Andrews]] in [[Fife]], [[Scotland]]. The castle sits on a rocky [[promontory]] overlooking a small beach called Castle Sands and the adjoining [[North Sea]]. There has been a castle standing at the site since the times of [[Roger de Beaumont (bishop)|Bishop Roger]] (1189-1202), son of the [[Earl of Leicester]]. It housed the [[burgh]]\u2019s wealthy and powerful [[bishop]]s while St Andrews served as the [[ecclesiastical]] centre of Scotland during the years before the [[Protestant Reformation]]. In their [[Latin]] charters, the [[Archdiocese of St Andrews|Archbishops of St Andrews]] wrote of the castle as their palace, signing, \"apud Palatium nostrum.\"<ref>Charles Jobson Lyon, ''History of St Andrews'', vol.2, (1843), p.244</ref>\n\nThe castle's grounds are now maintained by [[Historic Environment Scotland]] as a [[scheduled monument]].<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=SM90259|desc=St Andrews Castle|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref> The site is entered through a visitor centre with displays on its history. Some of the best surviving carved fragments from the castle are displayed in the centre, which also has a shop.\n\n== Wars of Scottish Independence ==\nDuring the [[Wars of Scottish Independence]], the castle was destroyed and rebuilt several times as it changed hands between the Scots and the [[England|English]]. Soon after the [[sack of Berwick]] in 1296 by [[Edward I of England]], the castle was taken and made ready for the [[English king]] in 1303. In 1314, however, after the Scottish victory at [[Battle of Bannockburn|Bannockburn]], the castle was retaken and repaired by [[William de Lamberton|Bishop William Lamberton]], [[Guardian of Scotland]], a loyal supporter of [[Robert I of Scotland|King Robert the Bruce]]. The English had recaptured it again by the 1330s and reinforced its defences in 1336, but were not successful in holding the castle. Sir [[Andrew Moray]], [[Regent of Scotland]] in the absence of [[David II of Scotland|David II]], recaptured it after a siege lasting three weeks. Shortly after this, in 1336-1337, it was destroyed by the Scots to prevent the English from once again using it as a stronghold.\n\nIt remained in this ruined state until Bishop [[Walter Trail]] rebuilt it at the turn of the century. His castle forms the basis of what can be seen today. He completed work on the castle in about 1400 and died within its walls in 1401.\n\n== Home to kings ==\nSeveral notable figures spent time in the castle over the next several years. [[James I of Scotland]] (1406-1437) received part of his education from Bishop [[Henry Wardlaw]], the founder of [[St Andrews University]] in 1410. A later resident, Bishop [[James Kennedy (bishop)|James Kennedy]], was a trusted advisor of [[James II of Scotland]] (1437-1460). In 1445 the castle was the birthplace of [[James III of Scotland]].\n\n== Used as a prison ==\nDuring these years, the castle also served as a notorious [[prison]]. The castle's [[bottle dungeon]] is a dank and airless pit cut out of solid rock below the north-west tower. It housed local miscreants who fell under the Bishop's jurisdiction as well as several more prominent individuals such as [[David Stuart, Duke of Rothesay]] in 1402, [[Murdoch Stewart, 2nd Duke of Albany|Duke Murdoch]] in 1425, and [[Archbishop]] [[Patrick Graham (bishop)|Patrick Graham]], who was judged to be insane and imprisoned in his own castle in 1478.\n\n== Reformation and siege ==\n{{Main|Siege of St Andrews Castle}}\n\nDuring the [[Scottish Reformation]], the castle became a centre of religious persecution and controversy. Referring to the bottle dungeon the Scottish reformer, [[John Knox]], wrote, \"Many of God's Children were imprisoned here.\" In 1521 [[James Beaton]], then [[Archbishop of Glasgow]], won the seat of St Andrews and took up residence in the castle. Beaton altered the defences to enable the castle to withstand a heavy [[artillery]] attack, which was a threat as tensions grew between English [[Protestant]]s and Scottish [[Catholic]]s. In 1538 James Beaton was succeeded by his ambitious and wealthy nephew, Cardinal [[David Beaton]]. His strong opposition to the marriage of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], with Prince Edward (later King [[Edward VI]]), the son and heir of [[Henry VIII of England]], helped to spark renewed fighting in 1544.\n\n[[File:Military mine beneath St. Andrews Castle 2017-05-28.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Mine tunnel dug during the siege in 1546]]\n\nScottish Protestants were increasingly viewed as dangerous turncoats who sided with the English. In 1546 David Beaton imprisoned the Protestant preacher [[George Wishart]] (1513-1546) in the castle's Sea Tower and had him burnt at the stake in front of the castle walls on 1 March. Today, brick lettering with his initials marks the spot where he died. In May the same year, Wishart's friends conspired against the [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]]. On 26 May they gained entry to the castle by disguising themselves as [[stonemason|masons]] when some building work was in progress. After overcoming the [[garrison]], they murdered Cardinal Beaton and hung his body from his window on the front of the castle.\n\nFollowing this murder, the Protestants took refuge in the castle and formed the first Protestant [[Wiktionary:congregation|congregation]] in Scotland. A long [[siege]] was ordered by the Scottish Regent, [[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran]]. In October 1546 a [[Mining (military)|mine]] was begun by the attackers which was successfully counter-mined by the defenders.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/correspondancep00pongoog ''Correspondance Politique de Odet de Selve'', (1888), 54, 10 November 1546]</ref> Both the mine and counter-mine cut through solid rock. They were rediscovered in 1879 and remain open to the public today. Arran heard that an English army was on its way to relieve the Castle and asked Fife Lairds like John Wemyss of that Ilk to come by 4 November 1546, bringing his followers and whatever artillery they had to resist a sea invasion.<ref>Fraser, William, ed., ''Memorials of the family of Wemyss'', vol. 3, Edinburgh (1888), 7, (letter 31 October 1546)</ref> Although Henry VIII made plans to assist the Protestants within the castle,<ref>''State Papers Henry VIII'', vol. 5, part IV part 2, (1836), 572-584.</ref> the invasion never came and his son [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]] did not send aid.\n\nDuring an [[armistice]] in April 1547, [[John Knox]] entered the castle and served as the garrison's preacher for the remainder of the siege. For a time Knox had the freedom to pass to and from the castle to preach in the [[parish]] church. This peaceful interlude came to end, however, when a French fleet arrived bringing an Italian engineer [[Leone Strozzi]] who directed a devastating artillery bombardment to dislodge the Protestant [[laird]]s. The lairds knew an expert was in the field when their own Italian engineer observed cannon being winched into position with ropes rather than exposing the besiegers to their fire.<ref>Lindsay of Pitscottie, ''Chronicles of Scotland'', vol. 2, Edinburgh, (1814), 489-490.</ref> Guns were also placed on St Salvator's and the cathedral towers. One of the largest Scottish cannon was called \"thrawynmouthe.\"<ref>''Accounts of the Lord High Treasurer of Scotland'', vol. 9 (1911), 103.</ref> The castle was quickly rendered indefensible. Within six hours according to [[Robert Lindsay of Pitscottie]].<ref>Lindsay of Pitscottie, ''Chronicles of Scotland'', vol. 2, Edinburgh, (1814), 490.</ref> The defeated Protestants were taken away: some were imprisoned in France while others, including Knox, were condemned to the [[galley]]s.\n\n== Decline and current condition ==\n\n[[File:Carving of Cardinal Beaton's Arms.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Beaton's arms on a panel believed to have been removed from one of his private apartments in the castle]]\n\nFollowing this Protestant defeat, the castle was substantially rebuilt by [[John Hamilton (archbishop)|Archbishop John Hamilton]], the illegitimate brother of [[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran|Regent Arran]], and successor to [[Dr.]] [[David Cardinal Beaton]]. But following his death in 1571 it was mainly occupied by a succession of [[constable]]s. [[Parliament of Scotland|Parliament]] separated the castle from the archbishopric in 1606, and it was granted to the [[Earl of Dunbar]], constable since 1603. In 1612 it was returned to Archbishop [[George Gledstanes]], but further attempts to re-establish the former estates of the Archbishop failed. With the eventual success of the [[Reformation in Scotland]], the office of the bishop was increasingly eroded until it was finally abolished by [[William III of England|William of Orange]] in 1689. Deprived of any function, the castle fell rapidly into ruin. By 1656, it had fallen into such disrepair that the burgh council ordered the use of its materials in repairing the pier. The principal remains are a portion of the south wall enclosing a square tower, the \"bottle dungeon,\" the kitchen tower, and the underground mine and counter-mine.\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Attributed to Robert Adamson (Scottish - St. Andrews Castle from the East) - Google Art Project - top image.jpg|1843-44 photo of St. Andrews Castle by [[Robert Adamson (photographer)|Robert Adamson]]\nFile:The ruins of St Andrews Castle.jpg|The ruins of St Andrews Castle viewed from St Andrews Pier\nFile:St. Andrews Castle 2017-05-28.jpg|The courtyard of St Andrews Castle\n</gallery>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|St Andrews Castle}}\n*Historic Environment Scotland: [https://www.historicenvironment.scot/visit-a-place/places/st-andrews-castle Visitor guide]\n\n{{St Andrews}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Andrews Castle}}\n[[Category:Ruined castles in Fife]]\n[[Category:St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Episcopal palaces in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Defunct prisons in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Ancient Monuments in Fife]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Fife]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|St Andrew's Castle, Hamble}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n|name=St. Andrews Castle\n|location=[[St. Andrews]], [[Fife]], [[Scotland]]\n|image=[[Image:General view of castle from SE.jpg|250px]]\n|caption=St Andrews castle ruins\n|map_type = UK Scotland\n|map_relief= 1\n|map_caption = Shown within Scotland\n|coordinates = {{coord|56.34|-2.79|type:landmark|display=inline}}\n|map_size=220\n|type=\n|built=c.1200\n|builder=[[Bishop Roger|Roger de Beaumont]]\n|controlledby=Bishops of St Andrews\n|materials=stone\n|height=\n|used=Until c.1689\n|condition=Ruined\n|ownership=[[Historic Environment Scotland]]\n|open_to_public= Yes\n}}\n\n'''St Andrew's Castle''' is a [[ruin]] located in the coastal [[Royal Burgh of St Andrews]] in [[Fife]], [[Scotland]]. The castle sits on a rocky [[promontory]] overlooking a small beach called Castle Sands and the adjoining [[North Sea]]. There has been a castle standing at the site since the times of [[Roger de Beaumont (bishop)|Bishop Roger]] (1189-1202), son of the [[Earl of Leicester]]. It housed the [[burgh]]\u2019s wealthy and powerful [[bishop]]s while St Andrews served as the [[ecclesiastical]] centre of Scotland during the years before the [[Protestant Reformation]]. In their [[Latin]] charters, the [[Archdiocese of St Andrews|Archbishops of St Andrews]] wrote of the castle as their palace, signing, \"apud Palatium nostrum.\"<ref>Charles Jobson Lyon, ''History of St Andrews'', vol.2, (1843), p.244</ref>\n\nThe castle's grounds are now maintained by [[Historic Environment Scotland]] as a [[scheduled monument]].<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=SM90259|desc=St Andrews Castle|access-date=24 February 2019}}</ref> The site is entered through a visitor centre with displays on its history. Some of the best surviving carved fragments from the castle are displayed in the centre, which also has a shop.\n\n== Wars of Scottish Independence ==\nDuring the [[Wars of Scottish Independence]], the castle was destroyed and rebuilt several times as it changed hands between the Scots and the [[England|English]]. Soon after the [[sack of Berwick]] in 1296 by [[Edward I of England]], the castle was taken and made ready for the [[English king]] in 1303. In 1314, however, after the Scottish victory at [[Battle of Bannockburn|Bannockburn]], the castle was retaken and repaired by [[William de Lamberton|Bishop William Lamberton]], [[Guardian of Scotland]], a loyal supporter of [[Robert I of Scotland|King Robert the Bruce]]. The English had recaptured it again by the 1330s and reinforced its defences in 1336, but were not successful in holding the castle. Sir [[Andrew Moray]], [[Regent of Scotland]] in the absence of [[David II of Scotland|David II]], recaptured it after a siege lasting three weeks. Shortly after this, in 1336-1337, it was destroyed by the Scots to prevent the English from once again using it as a stronghold.\n\nIt remained in this ruined state until Bishop [[Walter Trail]] rebuilt it at the turn of the century. His castle forms the basis of what can be seen today. He completed work on the castle in about 1400 and died within its walls in 1401.\n\n== Home to kings ==\nSeveral notable figures spent time in the castle over the next several years. [[James I of Scotland]] (1406-1437) received part of his education from Bishop [[Henry Wardlaw]], the founder of [[St Andrews University]] in 1410. A later resident, Bishop [[James Kennedy (bishop)|James Kennedy]], was a trusted advisor of [[James II of Scotland]] (1437-1460). In 1445 the castle was the birthplace of [[James III of Scotland]].\n\n== Used as a prison ==\nDuring these years, the castle also served as a notorious [[prison]]. The castle's [[bottle dungeon]] is a dank and airless pit cut out of solid rock below the north-west tower. It housed local miscreants who fell under the Bishop's jurisdiction as well as several more prominent individuals such as [[David Stuart, Duke of Rothesay]] in 1402, [[Murdoch Stewart, 2nd Duke of Albany|Duke Murdoch]] in 1425, and [[Archbishop]] [[Patrick Graham (bishop)|Patrick Graham]], who was judged to be insane and imprisoned in his own castle in 1478.\n\n== Reformation and siege ==\n{{Main|Siege of St Andrews Castle}}\n\nDuring the [[Scottish Reformation]], the castle became a centre of religious persecution and controversy. Referring to the bottle dungeon the Scottish reformer, [[John Knox]], wrote, \"Many of God's Children were imprisoned here.\" In 1521 [[James Beaton]], then [[Archbishop of Glasgow]], won the seat of St Andrews and took up residence in the castle. Beaton altered the defences to enable the castle to withstand a heavy [[artillery]] attack, which was a threat as tensions grew between English [[Protestant]]s and Scottish [[Catholic]]s. In 1538 James Beaton was succeeded by his ambitious and wealthy nephew, Cardinal [[David Beaton]]. His strong opposition to the marriage of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], with Prince Edward (later King [[Edward VI]]), the son and heir of [[Henry VIII of England]], helped to spark renewed fighting in 1544.\n\n[[File:Military mine beneath St. Andrews Castle 2017-05-28.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Mine tunnel dug during the siege in 1546]]\n\nScottish Protestants were increasingly viewed as dangerous turncoats who sided with the English. In 1546 David Beaton imprisoned the Protestant preacher [[George Wishart]] (1513-1546) in the castle's Sea Tower and had him burnt at the stake in front of the castle walls on 1 March. Today, brick lettering with his initials marks the spot where he died. In May the same year, Wishart's friends conspired against the [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]]. On 26 May they gained entry to the castle by disguising themselves as [[stonemason|masons]] when some building work was in progress. After overcoming the [[garrison]], they murdered Cardinal Beaton and hung his body from his window on the front of the castle.\n\nFollowing this murder, the Protestants took refuge in the castle and formed the first Protestant [[Wiktionary:congregation|congregation]] in Scotland. A long [[siege]] was ordered by the Scottish Regent, [[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran]]. In October 1546 a [[Mining (military)|mine]] was begun by the attackers which was successfully counter-mined by the defenders.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/correspondancep00pongoog ''Correspondance Politique de Odet de Selve'', (1888), 54, 10 November 1546]</ref> Both the mine and counter-mine cut through solid rock. They were rediscovered in 1879 and remain open to the public today. Arran heard that an English army was on its way to relieve the Castle and asked Fife Lairds like John Wemyss of that Ilk to come by 4 November 1546, bringing his followers and whatever artillery they had to resist a sea invasion.<ref>Fraser, William, ed., ''Memorials of the family of Wemyss'', vol. 3, Edinburgh (1888), 7, (letter 31 October 1546)</ref> Although Henry VIII made plans to assist the Protestants within the castle,<ref>''State Papers Henry VIII'', vol. 5, part IV part 2, (1836), 572-584.</ref> the invasion never came and his son [[Edward VI of England|Edward VI]] did not send aid.\n\nDuring an [[armistice]] in April 1547, [[John Knox]] entered the castle and served as the garrison's preacher for the remainder of the siege. For a time Knox had the freedom to pass to and from the castle to preach in the [[parish]] church. This peaceful interlude came to end, however, when a French fleet arrived bringing an Italian engineer [[Leone Strozzi]] who directed a devastating artillery bombardment to dislodge the Protestant [[laird]]s. The lairds knew an expert was in the field when their own Italian engineer observed cannon being winched into position with ropes rather than exposing the besiegers to their fire.<ref>Lindsay of Pitscottie, ''Chronicles of Scotland'', vol. 2, Edinburgh, (1814), 489-490.</ref> Guns were also placed on St Salvator's and the cathedral towers. One of the largest Scottish cannon was called \"thrawynmouthe.\"<ref>''Accounts of the Lord High Treasurer of Scotland'', vol. 9 (1911), 103.</ref> The castle was quickly rendered indefensible. Within six hours according to [[Robert Lindsay of Pitscottie]].<ref>Lindsay of Pitscottie, ''Chronicles of Scotland'', vol. 2, Edinburgh, (1814), 490.</ref> The defeated Protestants were taken away: some were imprisoned in France while others, including Knox, were condemned to the [[galley]]s.\n\n== Decline and current condition ==\n\n[[File:Carving of Cardinal Beaton's Arms.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Beaton's arms on a panel believed to have been removed from one of his private apartments in the castle]]\n\nFollowing this Protestant defeat, the castle was substantially rebuilt by [[John Hamilton (archbishop)|Archbishop John Hamilton]], the illegitimate brother of [[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran|Regent Arran]], and successor to [[Dr.]] [[David Cardinal Beaton]]. But following his death in 1571 it was mainly occupied by a succession of [[constable]]s. [[Parliament of Scotland|Parliament]] separated the castle from the archbishopric in 1606, and it was granted to the [[Earl of Dunbar]], constable since 1603. In 1612 it was returned to Archbishop [[George Gledstanes]], but further attempts to re-establish the former estates of the Archbishop failed. With the eventual success of the [[Reformation in Scotland]], the office of the bishop was increasingly eroded until it was finally abolished by [[William III of England|William of Orange]] in 1689. Deprived of any function, the castle fell rapidly into ruin. By 1656, it had fallen into such disrepair that the burgh council ordered the use of its materials in repairing the pier. The principal remains are a portion of the south wall enclosing a square tower, the \"bottle dungeon,\" the kitchen tower, and the underground mine and counter-mine.\n\n==Gallery==\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Attributed to Robert Adamson (Scottish - St. Andrews Castle from the East) - Google Art Project - top image.jpg|1843-44 photo of St. Andrews Castle by [[Robert Adamson (photographer)|Robert Adamson]]\nFile:The ruins of St Andrews Castle.jpg|The ruins of St Andrews Castle viewed from St Andrews Pier\nFile:St. Andrews Castle 2017-05-28.jpg|The courtyard of St Andrews Castle\n</gallery>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|St Andrews Castle}}\n*Historic Environment Scotland: [https://www.historicenvironment.scot/visit-a-place/places/st-andrews-castle Visitor guide]\n\n{{St Andrews}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Andrews Castle}}\n[[Category:Ruined castles in Fife]]\n[[Category:St Andrews]]\n[[Category:Episcopal palaces in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Defunct prisons in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Ancient Monuments in Fife]]\n[[Category:Historic house museums in Fife]]\n", "name_user": "Zh84", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected \"St Andrew's Castle\" to \"St Andrews Castle\".", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Andrews_Castle"}
{"title_page": "Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox project\n| name = Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi\n| logo =\n| image =\n| mission_statement =\n| type =\n| products =\n| location = All india \n| country = [[India]]\n| key_people = Vivek Aggarwal (IAS)\n| established = {{Start date|2019|02|01|df=y}}\n| funding = {{INRConvert|75000|c|year=2019}}\n| budget = Y\n|website={{url|http://pmkisan.gov.in}}|ministry=Ministry of Agriculture and Farmers Welfare}}\n'''Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi''' is an initiative by the [[government of India]] in which all farmers will get up to {{INRConvert|6000|year=2019}} per year as minimum income support. The initiative was announced by [[Piyush Goyal]] during the [[2019 Interim Union Budget of India]] on 1 February 2019.<ref name=\"Piyush Goyal announces PM Kisaan Samman Nidhi\">{{cite news|title=Piyush Goyal announces PM Kisaan Samman Nidhi|publisher=[[CNBC TV18]]|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://www.cnbctv18.com/economy/union-budget-2019-2020-finance-minister-piyush-goyal-to-present-modi-governments-last-budget-today-focus-on-farm-loan-waiver-income-tax-slabs-2140711.htm}}</ref><ref name=\"12 Crore farmers to get benefit\">{{cite news|title=12 Crore farmers to get benefit|publisher=[[NewsX]]|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://www.newsx.com/national/7th-pay-commission-interim-budget-2019-piyush-goyal-live-updates-will-narendra-modi-government-make-any-announcement-on-salary-hike}}</ref><ref name=\"Interim Budget\">{{cite news|title=Interim Budget|publisher=[[Outlook India]]|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/business-news-budget-2019-live-litmus-test-for-modi-govt-as-piyush-goyal-is-set-to-present-interim-budget-today/324674}}</ref><ref name=\"Interim Budget 2019\">{{cite news|title=Interim Budget 2019|publisher=[[Zee News]]|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://zeenews.india.com/business/live-updates/interim-budget-2019-live-updates-2176100}}</ref> The scheme will cost {{INRConvert|75000|c|year=2019}} per annum and will come in effect from December 2018.<ref name=\"Goyal announces\">{{cite news|title=Goyal announces|publisher=dailyexcelsior.com|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=http://www.dailyexcelsior.com/goyal-announces-a-mega-pension-yojana-hikes-gratuity-limit-sobs-for-farmer/}}</ref> {{INR}}6,000 per year will be paid to each eligible farmer in three instalments and will be deposited directly to their bank accounts.<ref name=\"Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi scheme Approved\">{{cite news|title=Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi scheme Approved|publisher=dailyhunt.in|accessdate=1 February 2019|url=https://m.dailyhunt.in/news/india/english/east+coast+daily+eng-epaper-eeastco/interim+budget+2019+pradhan+mantri+kisan+samman+nidhi+scheme+approved-newsid-107689105}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe scheme was first conceived and implemented by [[Government of Telangana|Govt of Telangana]] as the [[Rythu Bandhu scheme|Rythu Bandhu]] scheme, where a certain amount is given directly to eligible farmers. The scheme has received accolades<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/world-bank-pat-for-rythu-bandhu-implementation/article26413088.ece|title=World Bank pat for Rythu Bandhu implementation|last=Rajeev|first=M.|date=2019-03-02|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-04-03|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> from various organisations for its successful implementation, including [[World Bank]]. Many economist suggest that this type of investment support is better<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/Politics/2719Mq7Dqo8c5xJ6s9xnJP/Telangana-shows-an-alternative-to-farm-loan-waivers.html|title=Telangana shows an alternative to farm loan waivers|last=Lasania|first=Yunus Y.|date=2018-12-26|website=Mint|language=en|access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref> than farm loan waivers. With the positive outcome of this scheme, [[Government of India|Govt of India]] wanted to implement<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/centre-replicates-telanganas-rythu-bandhu-scheme-give-income-support-farmers-96057|website=www.thenewsminute.com|access-date=2019-04-03|title=Centre replicates Telangana's Rythu Bandhu scheme to give income support to farmers|date=February 2019}}</ref> it as nationwide project and it was announced by [[Piyush Goyal]] during the [[2019 Interim Union Budget of India]] on 1 February 2019.<ref name=\"Interim Budget 20192\">{{cite news|url=https://zeenews.india.com/business/live-updates/interim-budget-2019-live-updates-2176100|title=Interim Budget 2019|accessdate=1 February 2019|publisher=[[Zee News]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Interim Budget2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/website/story/business-news-budget-2019-live-litmus-test-for-modi-govt-as-piyush-goyal-is-set-to-present-interim-budget-today/324674|title=Interim Budget|accessdate=1 February 2019|publisher=[[Outlook India]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February 2019, [[Narendra Modi]] launched the scheme in [[Uttar Pradesh]]'s [[Gorakhpur]] by transferring the first instalment of \u20b92,000 each to over one crore farmers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/pm-launches-kisan-scheme-over-1-crore-farmers-get-1st-instalment/article26356409.ece|title=Modi launches PM-Kisan scheme from Gorakhpur|last=Bureau|first=Our|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatvnews.com/video/politics/pm-modi-launches-pradhan-mantri-kisan-samman-nidhi-yojana-other-initiatives-in-gorakhpur-506022|title=VIDEO: PM Modi launches Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi Yojana, other initiatives in Gorakhpur|website=www.indiatvnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/pm-modi-unveils-pradhan-mantri-kisan-samman-nidhi-scheme-in-gorakhpur-119022400232_1.html|title=PM Modi unveils Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi scheme in Gorakhpur|last=ANI|date=2019-02-24|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> \u00a0\n\n== Objectives ==\n\n# With a view to augment the income of the Small and Marginal Farmers (SMFs), the Government has launched a new Central Sector Scheme, namely, \"Pradhan Mantri KIsan SAmman Nidhi (PM-KISAN)\" in the current financial year.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://pmkisan.nic.in/Documents/PMKisanSamanNidhi.PDF|title=Objectives of PM-Kisan|website=pmkisan.nic.in}}</ref>\n# The PM-KISAN scheme aims to supplement the financial needs of the SMFs in procuring various inputs to ensure proper crop health and appropriate yields, commensurate with the anticipated farm income at the end of the each crop cycle.<ref name=\":1\" />\n# This would also protect them from falling in the clutches of moneylenders for meeting such expenses and ensure their continuance in the farming activities.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Finance==\nThis is error {{INR}}75,000 crore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=187932|title=Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi announced to provide assured income support to small and marginal farmers|website=pib.nic.in|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> The complete expenditure for the scheme will borne by the Union Government in 2019-20.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pmkisan.nic.in/|title=pmkisan.nic.in|website=pmkisan.nic.in}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jagranjosh.com/current-affairs/states-urged-for-speedy-implementation-of-pradhan-mantri-kisan-samman-nidhi-yojana-pm-kisan-portal-launched-1549604418-1|title=Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi Yojana: Guidelines launched for States to implement scheme; PM-Kisan Portal launched|date=2019-02-08|website=Jagranjosh.com|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/centre-seeks-to-emulate-telangana-and-odisha-through-annual-rs-6000-each-to-over-12-crore-farmers/articleshow/67796488.cms|title=Farm de-stress yojana to benefit 12 crore - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n==Eligibility criteria==\n\n# In the database, the land owner's name, gender.\n# Social Classification (Scheduled Tribes / Scheduled Tribes).\n# [[Aadhaar]] number, bank account number and mobile number etc.\n# Land record details.\n# Jan Dhan Bank Account Number, Aadhaar and Mobile Number will help in identifying eligible beneficiaries and incompetent claimants.\n#The scheme is sponsored by the Central Government. Therefore, the farmers have to be citizens of the country.\n\n=== Documents required ===\n\n# Citizenship certificate <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiafilings.com/learn/pradhan-mantri-kisan-samman-nidhi-yojana/|title=Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi Yojana - IndiaFilings|date=2019-02-13|website=IndiaFilings - Learning Centre|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n# Landholding papers <ref name=\":0\" />\n# Aadhaar card <ref name=\":0\" />\n# Bank account details <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/faqs/miscellaneous/pradhan-mantri-kisan-samman-nidhi-check-eligibility-dates-and-other-details-here/articleshow/68049751.cms|title=Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi: Check eligibility, dates and other details here - Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Exclusion categories ===\nThe following categories of beneficiaries of higher economic status shall not be eligible for benefit under the scheme.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pmkisan.nic.in|title=Exclusion categories|website=pmkisan.nic.in}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/economy/pm-kisan-samman-nidhi-govt-announces-exclusion-criteria-check-who-wont-get-it/1479544/|title=PM Kisan scheme: Govt announces exclusion criteria \u2013 Check who won't get it|date=2019-02-07|website=The Financial Express|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n(A) All Institutional Land holders.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n(B) Farmer families in which one or more of its members belong to following categories:<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n# Former and present holders of constitutional posts.\n# Former and present Ministers/ State Ministers and former/present Members of [[Lok Sabha|LokSabha]]/ [[Rajya Sabha|RajyaSabha]]/ State Legislative Assemblies/ State Legislative Councils,former and present Mayors of Municipal Corporations, former and present Chairpersons of District Panchayats.\n# All serving or retired officers and employees of Central/ State Government Ministries /Offices/Departments and its field units Central or State PSEs and Attached offices /Autonomous Institutions under Government as well as regular employees of the Local Bodies (Excluding Multi Tasking Staff /Class IV/Group D employees).\n# All superannuated/retired pensioners whose monthly pension is {{INR}}10,000/-or more (Excluding Multi Tasking Staff / Class IV/Group D employees) of above category.\n# All Persons who paid Income Tax in last assessment year.\n# Professionals like Doctors, Engineers, Lawyers, Chartered Accountants, and Architects registered with Professional bodies and carrying out profession by undertaking practices.\n\n== State Governments Schemes ==\n\n===Annadatha Sukhibhava===\n{{Infobox project\n| name       = Annadatha Sukhibhava\n| budget = \u20b95,000 crores for FY 2019-20\n| location       = [[Andhra Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| website      = http://annadathasukhibhava.ap.gov.in/\n}}\n'''Annadatha Sukhibhava''' ({{lang-te|\u0c05\u0c28\u0c4d\u0c28\u0c26\u0c3e\u0c24 \u0c38\u0c41\u0c16\u0c40\u0c2d\u0c35}}) is a welfare program started by [[Government of Andhra Pradesh|Andhra Pradesh Government]] to provide \u20b915,000 investment support to small and marginal farmer's family per annum which includes \u20b96000 Central Government Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi share.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/india/andhra-to-give-all-farmers-rs-10000-merges-pm-kisan-scheme-with-annadatha-sukhibhava-5582088/|title=Andhra merges PM Kisan scheme with Annadatha Sukhibhava, all farmers to get Rs 10,000|date=2019-02-14|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> The government is providing support to nearly 64.1 lakh farmer including [[tenant farmer]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/54-lakh-andhra-farmers-to-get-benefit-of-annadata-sukhibhava-scheme-2019-somireddy-chandramohan-reddy20190216230913/|title=54 lakh Andhra farmers to get benefit of Annadata Sukhibhava scheme 2019: Somireddy Chandramohan Reddy|website=www.aninews.in|language=en|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref> This farmer investment support scheme where the cash is paid directly into the [[Aadhaar]] linked bank accounts will cover all the farmers in the state on Family as unit basis without any conditions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/andhra-pradesh/5000-cr-allocated-for-annadata-sukhibhava/article26187674.ece|title=\u20b95,000 cr. allocated for \u2018Annadata Sukhibhava\u2019|last=Rao|first=G. Venkataramana|date=2019-02-06|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-04-13|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> It was formally started on 19-02-2019 by providing \u20b91000 Initially by [[Real Time Governance Society|Real Time Governance Society center]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/cities/vijayawada/2019/feb/19/annadata-sukhibhava-launched--nearly-50l-get-rs-1000-on-day-one-1940790.html|title=Annadata Sukhibhava launched, nearly 50 lakh get Rs 1,000 on Day One|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-02-21}}</ref>\n\n====Payment disbursal====\n[[Government of Andhra Pradesh|Andhra Pradesh Government]] was displaying the number of families benefiting with this scheme in real time basis on its official website.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+'''Annadatha Sukhibhava Payment Dashboard''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://annadathasukhibhava.ap.gov.in/ADSBAPP/kisan/index|title=:: Annadatha Sukhibhava ::|website=annadathasukhibhava.ap.gov.in|access-date=2019-04-10}}</ref>'''( As on 13-04-2019; 12 PM )'''\n!Term\n!Amount\n!Date of Initiation\n!'''Families Eligible'''\n!'''Payment Initiated'''\n!'''Payment Success'''\n!'''Under Process'''\n!Amount\n|-\n|Phase 1\n|\u20b9 1000\n|17-02-2019\n|50,19,383\n|50,16,443\n|46,21,658\n|3,97,725\n|\u20b9 462.17 Cr\n|-\n|Phase 2\n|\u20b9 3000\n|03-04-2019\n|48,92,682\n|45,03,431\n|44,43,721\n|4,48,961\n|\u20b9 1333.12 Cr\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n\n== Amratvih ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Aspect\n!PM-Kisan\n![[Rythu Bandhu scheme|Rythu Bandhu]]\n![[Annadatha Sukhibhava]]\n!KALIA scheme<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/odisha/2019/jan/05/what-is-kalia-scheme-and-who-is-eligible-to-get-benefit-1921003.html|title=What is Kalia scheme and who is eligible to get its benefits?|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2019-04-13}}</ref>\n|-\n|Started by\n|[[Government of India|Union Government of India]]\n|[[Government of Telangana|Telangana Government]]\n|[[Government of Andhra Pradesh|Andhra Pradesh Government]]\n|[[Government of Odisha|Odisha Government]]\n|-\n|Unit\n|Per Family\n|Per [[Acre]]\n|Per Family\n|Per Family\n|-\n|No Of Beneficiaries\n|Approx. 120 Million\n|Approx. 6 Million\n|Approx. 7 Million ( Inc 2 Million Tenant farmers)\n|6 Million Families\n|-\n|Assistance\n|\u20b9 6,000 per year in 3 installments\n|\u20b9 10,000 per year per Acre in two installments<ref>https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/telangana/2020/jan/21/telangana-government-releases-rythu-bandhu-funds-ahead-of-municipal-polls-2092291.html</ref>\n|\u20b9 9,000 Extra in addition to PM Kisan Benefit,\n\u20b9 15,000 for Non Beneficiaries of PM Kisan\n|Rs.5,000 per farm family over five seasons\n|-\n|Exclusion\n|Last year Income Tax Payers,\n\nCivil Servants with High Income\n|No Exclusion\n|No Exclusion\n|No Exclusion\n|-\n|Cap\n|Small 