ricultural finance in India]]\n[[Category:Government schemes in India]]\n[[Category:Ministry of Agriculture & Farmers Welfare]]\n[[Category:Modi administration initiatives]]\n[[Category:Social security in India]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Rv spamlink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pradhan_Mantri_Kisan_Samman_Nidhi"}
{"title_page": "Jos\u00e9 Bautista", "text_new": "{{For|the pitcher of the same name|Jos\u00e9 Bautista (pitcher)}}\n{{short description|Dominican baseball player}}\n{{Spanish name 2|Bautista|Santos}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name          = Jos\u00e9 Bautista\n| image         = Jose Bautista 9 15 18 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Bautista with the Phillies in 2018\n| position      = [[Right fielder]] / [[Third baseman]]\n| team          =  \n| number        = \n| bats          = Right\n| throws        = Right\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1980|10|19}}\n| birth_place   = [[Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic]]\n| debutleague   = MLB\n| debutdate     = April 4\n| debutyear     = 20008\n| debutteam     = Baltimore Orioles\n| finalleague   = MLB\n| finaldate     = September 30\n| finalyear     = 2018\n| finalteam     = Philadelphia Phillies\n| statleague    = NBA\n| stat1label    = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value    = .247\n| stat2label    = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value    = 344\n| stat3label    = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value    = 975\n| teams         = \n* [[Baltimore Orioles]] ({{mlby|2004}})\n* [[Tampa Bay Rays|Tampa Bay Devil Rays]] ({{mlby|2004}})\n* [[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|2004}})\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|2004}}\u2013{{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2008}}\u2013{{mlby|2017}})\n* [[Atlanta Braves]] ({{mlby|2018}})\n* [[New York Mets]] ({{mlby|2018}})\n* [[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|2018}})\n| awards        = \n* 6\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2010]]\u2013[[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2015]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] (2010, 2011, 2014)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Hank Aaron Award]] (2010, 2011)\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|MLB home run leader]] (2010, 2011)\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Antonio Bautista Santos''' (born October 19, 1980) is a [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominican]] former [[professional baseball]] [[right fielder]] and [[third baseman]]. He has played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[Baltimore Orioles]], [[Tampa Bay Devil Rays]], [[Kansas City Royals]], [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], [[Toronto Blue Jays]], [[Atlanta Braves]], [[New York Mets]], and [[Philadelphia Phillies]].\n\nBautista's professional career began when the Pittsburgh Pirates selected him in the 20th round of the [[2000 Major League Baseball draft]]. In {{by|2010}}, he became the 26th member of the [[50 home run club]], while leading MLB in [[home runs]] for the first of two consecutive seasons. From 2010\u2013{{by|2015}}, Bautista hit more home runs than any player in the major leagues.  An [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|MLB All-Star]] selection six consecutive times, he has won three [[Silver Slugger Awards]] and two [[Hank Aaron Award]]s. In addition, he has received the [[American League]] (AL) [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month|Player of the Month Award]], five times, and the AL [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|Player of the Week]], four times. Before being traded to the Blue Jays, Bautista primarily played [[third base]].\n\nAlthough major league [[Scout (sport)|scouts]] initially took note of Bautista while he was in [[junior college]] for his batting skills \u2013 including [[Power hitter|power hitting]] potential and a strong throwing arm \u2013 his career would take many detours, until Bautista finally realized his potential, in 2010. He made his MLB debut with the Baltimore Orioles in {{by|2004}}, and, that year, became the first player ever to appear on [[#Early career|five MLB rosters in one season]]. The last of those clubs was the Pirates, where he would spend four-plus seasons, seeing time as a [[utility player]], while playing at six different positions, including [[designated hitter]] (DH).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/players/7264/career;_ylt=AluOYHKnUCIIU54UZfxxEc.FCLcF |title=Jos\u00e9 Bautista \u2013 Toronto Blue Jays \u2013 Career Statistics \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBautista was then traded to the Blue Jays, in August {{by|2008}}.<ref>{{cite web |author=Blue Jays Press Release |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20080821&content_id=3344473&vkey=pr_tor&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor&partnerId=rss_tor |title=Blue Jays acquire Bautista |publisher=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 21, 2008 |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> After making adjustments to his swing, he broke through with ten home runs in September {{by|2009}}. Bautista has since been voted in the top ten in the AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] four times, and is a [[List of Toronto Blue Jays team records|leader or among the top ten in numerous offensive single-season and career categories]] in Blue Jays' franchise history.<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/TOR/leaders_bat.shtml |title=Blue Jays top ten batting leaders |website=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |accessdate=January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to {{by|2017}}, Bautista hit at least 20 home runs each year, and in four of those seasons, hit at least 35 home runs, both [[Run (baseball)|scored]] and [[Run batted in|drove in]] at least 100 runs, and drew at least 100 [[bases on balls]], including twice leading the AL. In {{by|2015}}, while playing in the [[Major League Baseball postseason|playoffs]] for the first time, his [[Bat flip#Jos\u00e9 Bautista bat flip|bat flip]] in the [[2015 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] (ALDS) caused a sensation that became a symbol of Toronto's first playoff appearance in 22 years. In {{by|2011}}, Bautista set up a program that assists athletes from the [[Dominican Republic]] to attend universities in the United States.\n\n==Early life==\nComing from a [[middle-class]] family in the [[Dominican Republic]] that placed great importance on education, Bautista began studying English at age eight.  His mother was an accountant and [[financial planner]], and his father, who had earned a [[master's degree]] in [[agricultural engineering]] in Hungary, ran poultry farms.  Bautista attended a private high school, De La Salle High School, in [[Santo Domingo]].  He was aided by the Latin Athletes Education Fund,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/05/sports/baseball/05odermann.html|title=Education fund for latin players quietly changes lives |last=Schwarz|first=Alan|work=nytimes.com|date=May 5, 2008|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref> designed for players from Spanish-speaking countries aspiring to play [[college baseball]] in the United States.  Although he invested much time in pursuing [[professional baseball]], Bautista studied business at [[Pontificia Universidad Cat\u00f3lica Madre y Maestra|Mother and Teacher Pontifical Catholic University]] in the event a career in baseball did not materialize.<ref name=vagabond>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepostgame.com/features/201106/number-crusher-how-blue-jays-slugger-jose-bautista-experimented-his-way-greatness |title=How Jose Bautista went from baseball vagabond to the game's best slugger |last=Passan |first=Jeff |work=thepostgame.com |date=June 14, 2011 |accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter working out with various [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) clubs, he turned down offers of $5,000 from the [[New York Yankees]] and $42,000 from the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]]. The [[Cincinnati Reds]] offered him $300,000, which Bautista accepted; however, before the contract could become official, the team changed [[List of Cincinnati Reds owners and executives|ownership]] and subsequently rescinded the offer.  Bautista then created a highlight tape of himself using a [[camcorder]] and sent it to various colleges in the United States.  There was no response until he received a call from Oscar P\u00e9rez, whom he had known from the Quique Cruz League in the Dominican Republic.  P\u00e9rez informed him of the Latin Athletes Education Fund, designed for players from Spanish-speaking countries aspiring to play [[college baseball]] in the United States.  He connected Bautista with Don Odermann, a businessman in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]].  Odermann, who assisted baseball players from Latin America desiring to play baseball in the US, knew that [[Chipola College]], a [[junior college]] in [[Marianna, Florida]], was seeking an everyday player.  There, Bautista played for two years until being drafted.<ref name=vagabond/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/02/10/jose-bautista-toronto-blue-jays-bautista-family-education-fund |title=Jose Bautista giving back to Latin America by giving kids an education |last=Bradley |first=Jeff |work=si.com|date=February 13, 2015|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Early career===\nThe [[2000 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh Pirates]] drafted Jos\u00e9 Bautista in the 20th round of the [[2000 Major League Baseball draft]]. He signed with the Pirates for a $500,000 signing bonus.<ref name=schoenfield>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/sweetspot/post/_/id/64975/how-jose-bautista-became-jose-bautista|title=How Jose Bautista became Jose Bautista|date=October 19, 2015|work=ESPN|first=David|last=Schoenfield|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Bautista played for the [[Williamsport Crosscutters]] of the [[Class A-Short Season]] [[New York-Penn League]] in 2001 and the [[Hickory Crawdads]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[South Atlantic League]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/more-sports/2010/08/04/jose-bautista|title=Joe Lemire: How the Blue Jays' Jose Bautista pulled himself to prominence|first=Joe|last=Lemire|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=August 4, 2010|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref> In 2003, he played for the [[Lynchburg Hillcats]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Carolina League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milb.com/milb/news/former-hillcat-stuns-majors-with-2010-numbers/c-17047540|title=Former Hillcat Stuns Majors With 2010 Numbers|work=MiLB.com|date=March 21, 2011|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2003 season, the [[2004 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]] selected Bautista in the [[Rule 5 draft]] and carried him on their [[Opening Day]] roster.  He made his MLB debut with Baltimore on April 4, 2004. After playing 16 games with the Orioles, the [[2004 Tampa Bay Devil Rays season|Tampa Bay Devil Rays]] claimed him off [[Major League Baseball transactions#Waivers|waivers]] on June 3. Twenty-five days later, the [[2004 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]] purchased him from Tampa Bay after a 12-game stint with the Devil Rays. He played 13 games for the Royals before they traded him to the [[2004 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] on July 30 for [[Justin Huber]], who then traded him minutes later to [[2004 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh]] with [[Ty Wigginton]] and minor leaguer Matt Peterson for [[Kris Benson]] and [[Jeff Keppinger]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/news/040730benson.html |title=Trade Central |magazine=Baseball America |date=July 30, 2004 |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  This series of transactions made him the first player to appear on five different Major League Baseball rosters in one season, only since matched by [[Oliver Drake (baseball)|Oliver Drake]] in 2018.<ref name=journey>{{cite web |last=Snedden |first=Jeffrey |url=http://www.pittsburghsportingnews.com/the-amazing-journeys-of-chris-davis-and-jose-bautista/ |title=The amazing journeys of Chris Davis and Jose Bautista |publisher=Pittsburgh Sporting News |date=July 2013 |accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref> (Drake, however, actually played for all five teams, while Bautista only played for four; he never actually suited up or played for the Mets.)\n\nBautista played in 11 games for the Pirates in [[2005 Pittsburgh Pirates season|2005]].  In [[2006 Pittsburgh Pirates season|2006]], his first full season in the major leagues, Bautista [[Batting average (baseball)|hit]] .235 with 16 [[home run]]s (HR) and 51 [[runs batted in]] (RBI).  The following season in 2007, he posted similar numbers in 142 games, finishing the season with a batting average of .254, 15 home runs and 63 RBI.  That same year, he became the starting [[third baseman]] for the Pittsburgh Pirates.  He took over for reigning National League [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|batting champion]] [[Freddy Sanchez]], who moved to [[Second baseman|second base]].\n\nBautista was to be the Pirates' starting third baseman and backup outfielder in [[2008 Pittsburgh Pirates season|2008]].  From June 14 to 24, he hit five home runs in a span of nine games against [[interleague]] opponents [[2008 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore]], [[2008 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]], [[2008 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]], and the [[2008 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]].  However, he struggled offensively for most of the year, and after the 2008 trade deadline Bautista lost his starting job to the newly acquired [[Andy LaRoche]].  Bautista was optioned to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Indianapolis Indians]] on August 13.\n\n===Toronto Blue Jays===\n====2008====\nOn August 21, 2008, the Pirates traded Bautista to the Blue Jays for a [[player to be named later]], who eventually was [[Robinzon D\u00edaz]].<ref name=journey/><ref>{{cite news |first=Dejan |last=Kovacevic |title=Pirates trade Bautista to Blue Jays |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08234/906103-100.stm |work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |date=August 21, 2008 |accessdate=August 21, 2008}}</ref> The Blue Jays needed a third baseman due to an injury to [[Scott Rolen]].<ref name=schoenfield/> Bautista batted .214 in 21 games for Toronto after the trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20100605/293419281736841|title=This time, A.J. won't soon forget Bautista|work=Ottawa Citizen|via=[[PressReader]]|date=June 5, 2010|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2009====\n[[File:Jose Bautista in 2009.jpg|left|thumb|Bautista in 2009]]\nStarting the [[2009 Toronto Blue Jays season|2009 season]] on the bench, [[List of Toronto Blue Jays managers|manager]] [[Cito Gaston]] assigned Bautista to back up Rolen and [[outfielder]]s [[Alex R\u00edos]] and [[Adam Lind]]. Bautista started the season with a .317 batting average, .404 [[on-base percentage]] (OBP) and .463 [[slugging percentage]] (SLG) in 49 plate appearances in April.  However, his numbers fell off, as he batted between .167 and .231 each month from May through August with two total home runs. At times he showed marked plate discipline; in the month of May, he walked 14 times for a .403 OBP despite batting just .231.<ref name=\"BR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/bautijo02-bat.shtml |title=Jose Bautista statistics & history |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref>  Eventually, the Chicago White Sox claimed Rios off waivers, the Blue Jays assigned Lind to the role of [[designated hitter]], and an injury to [[Marco Scutaro]] led to an increase in Bautista's playing time and making him the [[leadoff hitter]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Newman |first=Mark |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/5706712/ |title=Fans face tough Final Vote choices |date=July 5, 2009 |accessdate=September 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/news/story?id=4390120 |title=White Sox acquire Rios from Toronto |publisher=ESPN.com |date=August 10, 2009 |accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs the season drew to a close, the Blue Jays made changes to their coaching staff.  One was to move first base coach [[Dwayne Murphy]] to replace the retiring [[Gene Tenace]] as hitting coach.  Formerly a Blue Jays' minor league roving hitting instructor and hitting coach, Murphy had already spent nearly one year working with Bautista, teaching him to leverage his pull power by starting his swing with his now-familiar high leg kick.<ref name=journey/>  In September, he finally broke through, hitting 10 home runs with 21 RBI, a .257 batting average and a .606 [[slugging percentage]] (SLG).<ref name=\"BR\"/>  He hit 13 total HR in 2009 with 40 RBI, a batting average of .235, and 79 [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] in 113 games.  Originally considered to be a non-tender candidate, he re-signed with the Blue Jays on a one-year, $2.4&nbsp;million US contract for the 2010 season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stark |first=Jayson |authorlink=Jayson Stark |title=More free agents coming? |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=December 11, 2008 |url = http://insider.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=3763719&searchName=winter_meetings_2008&campaign=rsssrch&source=jayson_stark |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author =  |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |title=Jays re-sign Bautista, McGowan, Chavez, add Gathright |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=December 13, 2009 |url = http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/story/2009/12/13/sp-baseball-jays-signings.html |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====2010====\nBautista began the [[2010 Toronto Blue Jays season|2010]] campaign as the starting right fielder and leadoff hitter. On May 17, he was named [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|AL Player of the Week]] after hitting .444 (8-for-18) with 20 [[total bases]], four home runs, eight RBI, eight runs scored, a .565 OBP, and an MLB-best 1.111 SLG.<ref>{{cite news |author = |title = Bautista, Prado named Players of the Week |publisher = [[Major League Baseball]] |date =May 17, 2010 |url = http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100517&content_id=10112284&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> Bautista hit his 20th home run as part of a two-home run night against the [[2010 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]] on June 22, setting a new career high for a single season in just two months.<ref name=\"Career High\">{{cite news |last=Zwolinkski |first=Mark |title = Bautista's two homers not enough for Jays against Cardinals |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date =June 22, 2010 |url = https://www.thestar.com/sports/baseball/article/827234--bautista-s-two-homers-not-enough-for-jays-against-cardinals |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBautista was selected as a reserve for the [[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game]].<ref name=2010mlbasg>{{cite news |last=Campbell |first=Morgan |title = Blue Jays\u2019 Vernon Wells, Jose Bautista and John Buck earn All-Star spots |newspaper = Toronto Star |date =July 4, 2010 |url = https://www.thestar.com/sports/baseball/mlb/bluejays/article/831834--wells-bautista-buck-earn-all-star-spots |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> Bautista entered the game as a pinch runner for [[Josh Hamilton]] and finished the game 0\u2013for-1.<ref>{{cite web |title = Boxscore: NL All-Stars vs AL All-Stars |publisher = [[Major League Baseball]] |date =July 13, 2010 |url = http://mlb.mlb.com/news/boxscore.jsp?gid=2010_07_13_nasmlb_aasmlb_1 |accessdate=August 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFor the month of July, Bautista batted .347, with 11 home runs, 29 RBI, and an AL-leading .765 slugging percentage, sharing American League Player of the Month honors with Twins outfielder [[Delmon Young]].<ref>{{cite news |author = |url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/baseball/2010/08/04/14923856.html |title=Jays' Bautista earns AL monthly award |work=[[Toronto Sun]] |date = August 4, 2010 | accessdate = August 4, 2010}}</ref> Bautista was also named Blue Jays' Player of the Month, which is selected through voting by the Toronto chapter of the Baseball Writers' Association of America.<ref name=\"July\">{{cite news |first = Jordan|last = Bastian| url = http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100801&content_id=12888704&notebook_id=12889066&vkey=notebook_tor&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor | title =Bautista named July Player of the Month | publisher = [[Major League Baseball Advanced Media|MLB Advanced Media, L.P.]]| date = August 1, 2010 | accessdate = August 1, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100801&content_id=12888328&vkey=pr_tor&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor |title=Jose Bautista Named Honda Player of the Month |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  With his 12 home runs in May and 11 in July, Bautista became only the third Blue Jay player in [[History of the Toronto Blue Jays|franchise history]] to have two months with at least 10 home runs.<ref name=\"July\"/>\n\nBautista was named co-winner of the American League Player of the Week award for the period ending August 1. Bautista hit .545 with five homers and 13 RBI during that span.<ref>{{cite news |author = | url = https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=329342 | title = Jay's Bautista shares Player of the Week honour | publisher = [[The Sports Network|TSN]]| date = August 2, 2010 | accessdate = August 4, 2010}}</ref> On August 26, Bautista hit his 100th career home run against the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref>{{cite news |author = | url = https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=331753| title = Peralta, Scherzer Lead Tigers Over Blue Jays| publisher = [[The Sports Network|TSN]]| date = August 26, 2010 | accessdate = August 30, 2010}}</ref> Bautista was again named player of the week for the week ending August 29; in seven games that week, Bautista led the American League with a .500 batting average (10-for-20) and hit four home runs.<ref>{{cite news |author = | url = http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/2010/08/30/jays_bautista/| title = Bautista takes top honours| publisher = [[Rogers Sportsnet|Sportsnet]]| date = August 26, 2010 | accessdate = August 30, 2010}}</ref> Bautista became the only Blue Jays player to ever win the award three times in one season.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} Bautista won AL Player of the Month for the month of August, in which he hit he led the AL in home runs (12), RBI (24), slugging percentage (.724) and total bases (72), while tying for the lead in extra-base hits (18). He finished tied for second with 23 runs and was third with 23 walks.<ref name=aug2010pom>{{cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/story/2010/09/02/sp-jose-bautista.html |title=Jays' Bautista wins AL's monthly honour | publisher = [[CBC Sports]]| date = September 2, 2010 | accessdate = September 2, 2010}}</ref> He also won the Honda Player of the Month Award, his second such award in as many months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100901&content_id=14171994&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor&vkey=pr_tor |title=Jose Bautista named Honda player of the month |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn September 17, Bautista set the new Blue Jays single-season home run record with his 48th home run, breaking the record set by [[George Bell (outfielder)|George Bell]].<ref name=tbjhrrecord>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=334138 |title=Bautista hits club record 48th homer as Jays thump Red Sox |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> On September 23, Bautista became the 26th player in Major League Baseball history to reach the [[50 home run club]] in one season, and the first Toronto Blue Jay player to do so.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=334862 |title=Site Map |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  His 52nd home run set a new MLB record for the largest single-season increase in home runs, eclipsing [[Davey Johnson]]'s 38 home run increase from 1972 to 1973.<ref name=hrincrease>{{cite news |last=Bastian |first=Jordan |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100924&content_id=15029508&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Bautista blasts Nos. 51, 52 as Jays drop O's | publisher = [[Major League Baseball Advanced Media|MLB Advanced Media, L.P.]] |date=September 25, 2010 |accessdate=September 25, 2010}}</ref> Bautista finished the 2010 season with an [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|MLB-leading]] 54 home runs, the highest total since [[Alex Rodriguez]] hit 54 in 2007.  Bautista won the AL [[Hank Aaron Award|Hank Aaron]] and a [[Silver Slugger Award|Silver Slugger]] Awards for his offensive performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101031&content_id=15924244&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Big lumber nets Bautista, Votto special hardware |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=October 31, 2010 |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=340753 |title=Jays star Bautista wins Silver Slugger award |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> and finished fourth in the AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] (MVP) voting, behind Hamilton, [[Miguel Cabrera]] and [[Robinson Can\u00f3]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101123&content_id=16182576&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=Bautista's big year good for fourth in MVP race |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date=October 31, 2010 |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  The Toronto chapter of the BBWAA named Bautista the [[Neil MacCarl Award|Blue Jays' Most Valuable Player]], the Blue Jays' Most Improved Player, and presented him the [[John Cerutti|John Cerutti Award]] for displaying \"goodwill, cooperation and character\".<ref name=\"sports.nationalpost.com\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2010/11/25/jays-bautista-adds-to-2010-awards-haul |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130129124910/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2010/11/25/jays-bautista-adds-to-2010-awards-haul |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 29, 2013 |title=Jays\u2019 Bautista adds to 2010 awards haul &#124; Posted Sports &#124; National Post |publisher=nationalpost.com |accessdate=September 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n====2011====\n[[File:Jos\u00e9 Bautista on June 5, 2011.jpg|thumb|left|Bautista at bat in 2011.]]\nBautista agreed to a five-year contract extension worth US$64 million before the [[2011 Toronto Blue Jays season|2011 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=354275 |title=Blue Jays announce five-year, $64M deal with Bautista |publisher=Tsn.ca |date=February 17, 2011 |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  He began the season as the starting right fielder for the Blue Jays, with [[Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n]] playing third base.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110329&content_id=17180068&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=Jose Bautista named Blue Jays' right fielder |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> Bautista walked 28 times in the month of April, breaking a club record that was set when [[Carlos Delgado]] collected 26 bases on balls in April 2001.  Bautista was unanimously selected for the Blue Jays' Player of the Month award, and was also named the AL Player of the Month for the month of April (his third such award in four months, dating back to the 2010 season).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110501&content_id=18486498&notebook_id=18489298&vkey=notebook_tor&c_id=tor |title=Bautista unanimously wins monthly award |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110503&content_id=18577412&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=American League monthly honors go to Jered Weaver, Jose Bautista |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, Bautista hit three home runs against the [[2011 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]], the first three-home run game of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=365820 |title=Bautista belts three homers in matinee win over Twins |publisher=Tsn.ca |date=May 16, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> On May 28, in a home game against the [[2011 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]], Bautista hit his 20th home run, a three-run shot to left field, becoming the first player to reach 20 home runs in 2011 as well as the fastest player to reach 20 home runs (44 games) in Blue Jays franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/recap?gid=310528114 |title=Guillen frustrated as Jays beat White Sox in 14th |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date=May 28, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601031448/https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/recap?gid=310528114 |archive-date=June 1, 2011}}</ref>  Bautista won the AL Player of the Month award for May, his fourth such award in five months.  He also became the first player to have the highest number of home runs in a single month for five consecutive months since [[Jimmie Foxx]] did so from June 1933 to April 1934.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=367678 |title=Blue Jays' Bautista named AL player of the month |publisher=Tsn.ca |date=February 6, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> Bautista also won the Blue Jays' Player of the Month award for the second consecutive month.<ref>{{cite web|last=Oegema |first=Cam |url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2011/6/2/2202914/jose-bautista-voted-blue-jay-player-of-the-month |title=Jose Bautista Voted Blue Jay Player of the Month |publisher=Bluebird Banter |date=June 2, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> On June 23, the Blue Jays shifted Bautista to third base and recalled [[Eric Thames]] to play the outfield.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/2011/06/23/bautista_move/ |title=Jays to move Bautista back to third base |publisher=sportsnet.ca |date=June 23, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBautista was selected for the [[2011 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2011 MLB All-Star Game]], receiving a record 7,454,753 votes.<ref name=2011mlbasg>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110703&content_id=21339402&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=Toronto Blue Jays slugger Jose Bautista tops all to earn starting All-Star nod |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref>  At the time of his selection, he led the MLB in home runs (26), walks (70), OBP (.471), slugging percentage (.679), OPS (1.150), times on base (160) and was also in second place for runs scored (64), total bases (182) and extra base hits (41).  He became the first Blue Jay in history to lead the league in All-Star voting. He was also the first Blue Jay to be voted into the All-Star game as a starter since [[Carlos Delgado]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110703&content_id=21339402&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=Toronto Blue Jays slugger Jose Bautista tops all to earn starting All-Star nod |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>  Bautista participated in the [[2011 Major League Baseball Home Run Derby|Home Run Derby]]; he hit four home runs and was eliminated in the first round.<ref name=hrderby2011>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/events/all_star/y2011/index.jsp?content=hr_derby |title= 2011 All-Star Game \u2013 Home Run Derby |publisher=MLB.com | date=July 21, 2011 | accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, with the debut of prospect [[Brett Lawrie]] to play third base, Bautista returned to right field. In a game against the [[2011 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] on August 20, Bautista walked three times, which brought his season total to 102 walks in 113 games, the fastest a player reached 100 walks since [[Barry Bonds]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/news;_ylt=Am6RaR0nfG_EcHzN8W2baDuFCLcF?slug=ap-bluejays |title=Bautista draws 3 more walks in loss to A's |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date=April 20, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> During a game against the New York Yankees on September 5, Bautista hit his 40th home run of the season, a solo homer off reliever [[Rafael Soriano]]. He became the second player in franchise history with back-to-back 40 home run seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=375152 |title=Jeter homers, drives in five as Yankees sweep Blue Jays |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>  Two games later on September 7, against the [[2011 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]], Bautista stole home plate on a double steal in which Lawrie took second base, becoming the first 40 home run hitter to steal home plate since [[Adam Dunn]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=375348 |title=Encarnacion drives in five, Jays comeback to beat Red Sox |publisher=Tsn.ca |accessdate=September 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013122106/http://tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=375348 |archivedate=October 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter leading the major leagues in home runs for the second consecutive season with 43, Bautista became the first player to do so since [[Mark McGwire]] in 1998 and 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/HR_leagues.shtml |title=Yearly league leaders & records for home runs |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 13, 2016}}</ref>  Baustista also led the majors in slugging percentage (.608), OPS (1.056) and walks (132) and the AL in [[Intentional base on balls|intentional walks]] (24).  He placed second in OBP (.447)<ref name=baustistamlbstats>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/bautijo02.shtml |title=Jos\u00e9 Baustista |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref> behind Cabrera.  He batted .302 and also placed in the top ten in the league in runs scored (105), [[total bases]] (312) and [[times on base]] (293).  Defensively, he led AL right fielders with five [[double play]]s turned and placed fourth in [[Assist (baseball)|assists]] with 13 and fifth with six [[Error (baseball)|errors]].<ref name=baustistamlbstats/>  His walk total was the highest in the league since [[Jason Giambi]] collected 137 in 2000,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/BB_leagues.shtml |title=Yearly league leaders & records for bases on balls |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 13, 2016}}</ref> while setting a new Blue Jays franchise record, which Delgado previously held with 123, also in 2000.  He also set new Blue Jays' single-season records with 8.1 total [[Wins Above Replacement]] (WAR) and 8.3 offensive WAR according to [[Baseball-Reference.com]], edging [[John Olerud]]'s 7.7 total in [[1993 Toronto Blue Jays season|1993]], and Delgado's 8.1 offensive WAR in 2000.  Bautista held the record for total WAR until [[Josh Donaldson]] rated at 8.8 in 2015; however, as of 2015, Bautista still holds the record for offensive WAR.<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders/>  He was the American League winner of the Hank Aaron Award for the second consecutive season,<ref>Davidi, Shi  (October 24, 2011) [https://web.archive.org/web/20111126124251/http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/2011/10/24/bautista_aaron Another Aaron for Bautista]. ''sportsnet.ca''.</ref> becoming just the third player in the award's history, after Rodriguez and [[Barry Bonds]], to win the award in back-to-back years.  Bautista also received his second consecutive Silver Slugger Award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111102&content_id=25873314&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Top boppers earn Silver Slugger Awards |publisher=MLB.com |date=November 2, 2011 |accessdate= November 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\n[[File:Jose Bautista of the Toronto Blue Jays, June 30, 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Bautista with the Toronto Blue Jays, June 30, 2012]] On January 30, Bautista was announced as the cover athlete for the Canadian edition of ''[[MLB 12: The Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/bautista-mlb-12/|title=Bautista to grace \u2018MLB 12 The Show\u2019 cover|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=January 30, 2012|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref> In an interleague game against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] on June 19, [[2012 Toronto Blue Jays season|2012]], Bautista hit the second of three straight solo home runs by the Blue Jays, between [[Colby Rasmus]] and [[Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n]], the first time since 2005 that the Jays went back-to-back-to-back with home runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_06_19_tormlb_milmlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=tor |title=Rasmus, Bautista rally Blue Jays past Crew |publisher=MLB.com | date=June 20, 2012 |accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref>  Bautista also took over the MLB lead in home runs for 2012, hitting his 25th on June 27 against the [[2012 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]], which broke the Blue Jays club record for home runs in a month, with 13. He went on to finish the month with 14 home runs, one short of the American League record for June.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\nBautista was voted an American League starter in the [[2012 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] for the second consecutive year and his third overall All-Star selection.  Hamilton surpassed Bautista's record vote total of the prior year.<ref name=\"Ballot record\">{{cite news |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120701&content_id=34263550&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |first=Jesse|last=Sanchez |publisher=MLB.com |date=July 1, 2012 |accessdate=July 2, 2012 |title=Rosters unveiled for 83rd All-Star Game}}</ref>  On July 2, Bautista was named American League Player of the Month for June.  It was his fifth time receiving the honor in his career. He batted .274 with 14 home runs and 30 RBI in the month of June.  His 14 home runs in June set a new Blue Jays franchise record for home runs in a month.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/Bautista+named+Player+Month/6873161/story.html | title=Bautista Named AL Player of the Month | newspaper=The Province | date=July 2, 2012 | accessdate= July 2, 2012}}</ref> Bautista competed in the [[2012 Major League Baseball Home Run Derby|Home Run Derby]]. At the time of his selection, he led all major league players with 26 home runs.<ref name=2012mlbasg>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120701&content_id=34294412&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=NL, AL Home Run Derby teams unveiled | publisher=MLB.com | date=July 2, 2012 | accessdate= July 2, 2012}}</ref> Bautista finished second to [[Prince Fielder]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/baseball/mlb/07/09/prince-fielder-home-run-derby-2012.ap/index.html?eref=sihp&sct=hp_t11_a0 |title=Fielder outslugs Bautista to capture second Home Run Derby crown |agency=AP|work=SportsIllustrated.CNN.com|date=July 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBautista was placed on the 15-day disabled list on July 17 with inflammation in his wrist.<ref name=\"Wrist\">{{cite news |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/blue-jays-put-bautista-dl-164939305--mlb.html |title=Blue Jays put Bautista on DL, call up OF Gose |agency=AP|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Mike|work=Yahoo! Sports |date=July 17, 2012 |accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref> He had started in all previous 90 games, and the Blue Jays called up prospect [[Anthony Gose]] to take his place after the game.<ref name=\"Wrist\" /> Bautista was activated on August 24, but returned to the disabled list on August 26 after he re-aggravated the injury to his left wrist. On August 28, the Jays announced that he would undergo season-ending surgery on the wrist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=404018 |title=Jays' Bautista to have wrist surgery; done for season|work=TSN.ca|date=August 28, 2012 |accessdate=August 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/2012/08/28/bautista_jose_blue_jays_surgery_wrist/ |title=Bautista needs surgery, done for 2012|work=Sportsnet.ca|last=Cormack |first=Mike|date=August 28, 2012|accessdate=August 28, 2012}}</ref> In 2012, Bautista batted .241 with 27 home runs and 65 RBI in 92 games.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\n====2013====\nOn January 21, [[2013 Toronto Blue Jays season|2013]], it was announced that Bautista would once again be the cover athlete of the Canadian edition of ''[[MLB 13: The Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/MLBTheShow/status/292352514014208000|work=Twitter.com |title=Twitter @MLBTheShow |date=January 18, 2013|access-date=January 21, 2013}}</ref>  Bautista hit his 200th career home run in a game against the [[2013 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]] on June 29.  On July 6, he was elected to his fourth consecutive [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], and his third as the starting right fielder for the American League.  At the time of his selection, he batted .264 with 20 HR and 52 RBI.<ref name=2013mlbasg>{{cite news |last=Koreen |first=Eric |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/sports/mlb/jose-bautista-leads-trio-of-blue-jays-to-all-star-game |title=Jose Bautista leads trio of Blue Jays to All-Star Game |newspaper=National Post |date=July 6, 2013 |access-date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>  In the All-Star Game, he recorded the game-winning RBI on a sacrifice fly in the fourth inning as the American League won 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |last=Elliot |first=Bob |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/07/16/bautista-a-hit-in-mlb-all-star-game |title=Jose Bautista a hit in MLB All-Star Game: Blue Jays slugger sends AL on its way to all-star victory as Rivera goes out in style |newspaper=Toronto Sun |date=July 16, 2013 |access-date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPlaying against the [[2013 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] on July 30, Bautista hit his 25th home run of the season.  In doing so, he became the fourth player in Blue Jays franchise history to hit at least 25 home runs in four consecutive seasons, joining Bell (1984\u20131987), Carter (1991\u20131996), and Delgado (1996\u20132004).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2013-07-31/mlb-trade-rumors-cubs-red-sox-orioles-phillies-deadline |title=Do deadline deals make sense for non-contenders hoping for quick impact? |last=Spector |first=Jesse |work=[[Sporting News]] |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref>  His season ended prematurely for the second consecutive time on September 4, when it was announced that he would be shut down with a left hip bone bruise.  Bautista finished 2013 with a .259 batting average, 28 home runs, and 73 RBI.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130904&content_id=59535132&notebook_id=59535992&vkey=notebook_tor&c_id=tor |title=Bautista to miss rest of season with hip injury |last=Casella |first=Paul |publisher=MLB.com |date=September 4, 2013|access-date=September 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\nBautista opened the [[2014 Toronto Blue Jays season|2014 season]] with a streak of 37 games in which he reached base safely.  His streak, the longest to open a season in Blue Jays franchise history, came to an end on May 11, when he went 0\u20134.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2014/05/11/blue_jays_drop_third_straight_to_angels.html |title=Blue Jays drop third straight to Angels |last=Kennedy |first=Brendan |work=thestar.com|date=May 11, 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>  On June 18, he recorded his 1,000 career hit in a game against the [[2014 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/tor/jose-bautista-notches-1000th-hit-of-career-in-defeat?ymd=20140618&content_id=80490238&vkey=news_tor|title=Bautista notches 1,000th hit of career in defeat|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=June 18, 2014|accessdate=June 18, 2014}}</ref> Bautista was named as the American League Captain for the [[2014 Major League Baseball Home Run Derby]] on June 23.<ref name=hrderby2014>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/jose-bautista-troy-tulowitzki-named-captains-for-home-run-derby?ymd=20140623&content_id=81221760&vkey=news_mlb |title=Bautista, Tulo named captains for reformatted Derby |last=Newman |first=Mark |work=MLB.com |date=June 23, 2014 |accessdate=June 23, 2014}}</ref>  On July 6, it was announced that not only was he elected to his fifth consecutive [[2014 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], but, for the second time, received the highest number of votes in the Majors, with 5,859,019.<ref name=2014mlbasg>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/tor/blue-jays-slugger-jose-bautista-leads-all-voters?ymd=20140706&content_id=83444292&vkey=news_tor|title=Mr. Popular: Bautista leads all voters on ballot |last=Chisholm |first=Gregor |work=MLB.com|date=July 6, 2014|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, Bautista ended the longest game in franchise history by hitting an opposite field single to drive in [[Munenori Kawasaki]] in the 19th inning, and give the Jays the 6\u20135 win over the [[2014 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/jays-beat-tigers-in-longest-game-in-team-history/ |title=Jays beat Tigers in longest game in team history |work=[[Sportsnet]] |date=August 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> On August 26, Bautista hit his 25th home run of the season, and in doing so, joined Carter and Delgado as the only Blue Jays players in franchise history to hit at least 25 in five or more consecutive seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/tor/blue-jays-slugger-jose-bautista-snaps-slump-by-going-deep?ymd=20140827&content_id=91655606&vkey=news_tor |title=Bautista snaps slump by going deep |last=Chisholm |first=Gregor |work=MLB.com |date=August 27, 2014 |accessdate=August 28, 2014}}</ref> Four days later, Bautista hit his 100th career home run at [[Rogers Centre]], a two-run shot off Yankees starter [[Michael Pineda]], and his fourth straight game with a home run which tied a career-high.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thespec.com/sports-story/4806681-jose-bautista-drew-hutchison-lift-toronto-blue-jays-over-new-york-yankees-2-0/ |title=Jose Bautista, Drew Hutchison lift Toronto Blue Jays over New York Yankees 2\u20130|last=Chidley-Hill|first=John|work=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|date=August 30, 2014|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> He would go on to hit a home run on August 31, extending his home run streak to five games and establishing a new career-high.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-hit-three-homers-in-win-over-yankees/ |title=Blue Jays hit three homers in win over Yankees |work=Sportsnet |date=August 31, 2014 |accessdate=August 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a home game against the [[2014 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]] on September 8, Bautista hit his 200th home run as a Blue Jay, joining Bell, Delgado, Carter, and [[Vernon Wells]] as the only players with 200 or more home runs in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=461306 |title=Bautista hits 200th homer as a Blue Jay in rout of Cubs |work=TSN.ca |date=September 8, 2014 |accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref> Bautista finished 2014 with a .286 batting average, 35 home runs, and 103 RBI.  He won his third Silver Slugger Award for his efforts.\n\n====2015====\n[[File:Jose Bautista talking to fans before a Spring Training Game.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Bautista talking to fans during 2015 [[spring training]]]]\nIn early [[2015 Toronto Blue Jays season|2015]], Bautista earned 10-and-5 rights by having at least 10 years of service time in the big-leagues, with the last 5 being on the same team. These rights give Bautista the ability to veto any trade he would be involved in.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/allowing-bautista-encarnacion-to-acquire-veto-rights-shows-blue-jays-have-no-desire-to-trade-them|title=Allowing Bautista, Encarnacion to acquire veto rights shows the Blue Jays have no desire to trade them|work=sports.vice.com|date=June 11, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In a home game against the [[2015 Baltimore Orioles season|Orioles]] on April 21, Bautista hit his 250th career home run.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/red_sox_mlb/mlb_coverage/2015/04/encarnacion_hits_2_home_runs_blue_jays_beat_orioles_13_6 |title=Encarnacion hits 2 home runs, Blue Jays beat Orioles 13\u20136 |work=[[Boston Herald]] |date=April 21, 2015 |accessdate=April 22, 2015}}</ref>  He injured his right shoulder during that game, attempting to throw out [[Delmon Young]] at first base. He was held out of the lineup for several days before returning, exclusively as the designated hitter. Bautista received a cortisone shot on May 24 and returned to the outfield on June 2, against the [[2015 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/mlb/jose-bautista-eases-back-into-right-field-for-blue-jays-1.3097924 |title=Jose Bautista eases back into right field for Blue Jays|last=Harrison|first=Doug|work=cbc.ca|date=June 2, 2015|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref> On July 6, Bautista was named to his sixth-consecutive [[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] team, as a reserve outfielder in [[Cincinnati]].<ref name=2015mlbasg>{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/135055072/full-roster-released-for-2015-all-star-game |title=Youth served on AL, NL ASG rosters |last=Miller |first=Doug |work=MLB.com|date=July 6, 2015|accessdate=July 6, 2015}}</ref> However, on July 11 it was announced that he would sit out the game due to a shoulder injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/twins-dozier-replaces-bautista-in-all-star-game/ |title=Bautista to miss All-Star game with sore shoulder |last=Zwelling |first=Arden |work=Sportsnet |date=July 11, 2015 |accessdate=July 11, 2015}}</ref> Bautista tied Vernon Wells for second place on the Blue Jays' all-time home run list on July 21, when he hit his 223rd home run for Toronto in a 7\u20131 win over the [[2015 Oakland Athletics season|Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-use-power-to-force-the-issue-vs-as/|title=Blue Jays use power to \u2018force the issue\u2019 vs. A's|last=Davidi |first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=July 22, 2015|accessdate=July 22, 2015}}</ref> He surpassed Wells on July 24 in a 5\u20132 loss to the [[2015 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/bautista-hits-224th-career-hr-in-blue-jays-loss/ |title=Bautista hits 224th career HR in Blue Jays\u2019 loss |work=Sportsnet |date=July 25, 2015 |accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, Bautista surpassed the 40 home run mark for the third time in his career, hitting a solo shot in the ninth inning against the Baltimore Orioles to extend the Blue Jays lead to 11\u20131. The Blue Jays would win the game, 15\u20132, and clinch the American League East.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citynews.ca/2015/09/30/blue-jays-clinch-first-al-east-title-in-22-years/|title=Blue Jays clinch first AL East title in 22 years|work=citynews.ca|date=September 30, 2015|accessdate=October 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBautista finished the 2015 regular season with a .250 batting average, 40 home runs, and 114 RBI. He also walked more than he struck out for the second consecutive year, totaling 110 walks to 106 strikeouts. For the season, he had the lowest [[line drive]] percentage of all major league hitters (13.9%).<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2015&month=0&season1=2015&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=5,a Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2015 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Batted Ball Statistics | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> From 2010\u201315, he batted .268 with 153 doubles, 227 home runs, 582 RBI, 574 walks, 576 strikeouts, .390 OBP, .555 SLG, .945 OPS, and 156 OPS+.<ref name=\"BR\"/> In that span, he hit more home runs than any other major leaguer \u2013 28 ahead of second-place [[Miguel Cabrera]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=nomin&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=HR&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015, sorted by greatest home runs |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> \u2013 was second in slugging percentage<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=minpas&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=slugging_perc&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015 (requiring at least 3000 plate appearances), sorted by greatest slugging % |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> and walks,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=nomin&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=BB&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015, sorted by greatest bases on balls |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> third in OPS<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=minpas&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=onbase_plus_slugging&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015 (requiring at least 3000 plate appearances), sorted by greatest adjusted on-base plus slugging |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> and OPS+<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=minpas&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=onbase_plus_slugging_plus&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015 (requiring at least 3000 plate appearances), sorted by greatest adjusted OPS+ |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> and fifth in OBP.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=minpas&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=onbase_perc&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015 (requiring at least 3000 plate appearances), sorted by greatest adjusted on-base% |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Jos\u00e9 Bautista bat flip, 14 October 2015.jpg|thumb|left|Jos\u00e9 Bautista's [[bat flip]] after hitting a home run in the bottom of the seventh inning of game 5 of the [[2015 American League Division Series]].]] Do not re-add image without reaching a further consensus via talk page. -->\nOn October 8, 2015, with just over 1,400 career games played, Bautista made his postseason debut against the [[2015 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]] in the [[2015 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] (ALDS).  In the fifth and final game of the series on October 14, Bautista hit a three-run home run off [[Sam Dyson]] that gave the Jays a 6\u20133 lead that they would not relinquish, sending Toronto to the [[2015 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]] (ALCS).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/154508912/jose-bautistas-blue-jays-legacy-is-secured|title=Touch 'em all, Jose: Legacy secured|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=October 14, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref>  Bautista watched the home run and [[bat flip|flipped his bat]] high into the air before running the bases, a celebratory gesture that was applauded by Jays fans and media outlets,<ref name=\"Joey Bats nickname\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citynews.ca/2015/10/16/trending-torontos-love-affair-with-joey-bats-more-than-skin-deep/|title=Trending: Toronto's love affair with Joey Bats more than skin deep|work=citynews.ca|date=October 16, 2015|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Watch Jos\u00e9 Bautista's famous bat flip in LEGO form |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/jose-bautista-s-bat-flip-in-a-lego-stop-motion-movie |publisher=MLB |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> while drawing the ire of Rangers players as unsportsmanlike, in the midst of a 53-minute seventh inning laden with controversy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs2015/story/_/page/playoffs15_JoeyBatspersona/how-one-bat-flip-made-blue-jays-star-jose-bautista-polarizing-figure |title=Bautista's bat flip made Joey Bats a polarizing name |last=McHenry |first=Britt |publisher=ESPN |date=October 20, 2015 |accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref>  A vital symbol of Toronto's first [[Major League Baseball postseason|postseason]] appearance since 1993,<ref>{{cite news |last=Arthur\n|first=Bruce |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2016/01/12/alex-anthopoulos-has-moved-on-and-so-should-we-arthur.html |title=Alex Anthopoulos has moved on, and so should we |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=January 12, 2016 |accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> the bat flip was voted [[Esurance]]'s MLB Award for Best Play on Offense for 2015.<ref name=esurancebestoffense>{{cite web |url=https://securea.mlb.com/mlb/awards/y2015/mlb-awards/ |title=Esurance MLB.com awards: Best play, offense |publisher=MLB.com |date=2015 |accessdate=January 6, 2016}}</ref>  In the five games of the ALDS, Bautista batted .273 with two home runs and five RBI.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nIn Game 3 of the ALCS against the [[2015 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]], Bautista had one hit and two walks, joining [[Keith Hernandez]] as the only players in MLB postseason history to reach base three times on their birthday. The Blue Jays would win the game, 11\u20138.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/155007470/blue-jays-royals-alcs-game-3-cool-facts |title=DYK? Joey Bats' b-day feat among G3 rarities |last=Cassavell |first=AJ |work=MLB.com |date=October 20, 2015 |accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref>  In Game 6, Bautista hit two home runs, including a two-run game-tying homer at the top of the eighth inning to tie the game at 3\u20133; however Kansas City would win 4\u20133 to take the [[List of American League pennant winners|pennant]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2015/10/23/world-is-watching-as-blue-jays-head-to-kansas-city-for-game-6-of-alcs.html |title=Fans reeling as Blue Jays eliminated in Game 6 heartbreaker |last=Levinson King |first=Robin |work=thestar.com |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2015, Toronto exercised Bautista's $14 million option for [[2016 Toronto Blue Jays season|2016]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-exercise-options-on-bautista-dickey-encarnacion/ |title=Blue Jays exercise options on Bautista, Dickey, Encarnacion |work=Sportsnet |date=November 3, 2015 |accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n[[File:Jose Bautista 2016 spring training.jpg|thumb|right|Bautista with Toronto in 2016]]\nDuring his final regular season plate appearance against the [[2016 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]] on May 15, [[2016 Toronto Blue Jays season|2016]], Bautista was hit by a pitch from [[Matt Bush (baseball)|Matt Bush]], which many believed to be retaliation by the Rangers organization for Bautista's [[Bat flip#Jos\u00e9 Bautista bat flip|bat flip]] in the 2015 ALDS. Two batters later, Bautista, intending to break-up a double play, made a hard, but no longer legal (as of that season), slide into second basemen [[Rougned Odor]]. Although the slide didn't make any contact, Odor pushed Bautista, who shoved back, followed by Odor punching Bautista in the jaw. This ignited a [[bench-clearing brawl]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chisholm |first1=Gregor |title=Tension boils over in Blue Jays-Rangers game |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/178354174/bautista-odor-fight-in-blue-jays-rangers-game |publisher=MLB |date=May 15, 2016 |accessdate=May 15, 2016}}</ref> Bautista was handed a one-game suspension by the league for his part in the melee, which he appealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/178630394/rougned-odor-jose-bautista-suspended|title=Odor, Bautista among 14 disciplined for brawl|last=Hagen|first=Paul|work=MLB.com|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> On May 27, MLB announced that they had upheld the suspension.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/jose-bautistas-suspension-upheld-will-miss-opener-vs-red-sox/|title=Jose Bautista\u2019s suspension upheld, will miss opener vs. Red Sox|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> During the day of his suspension, Bautista served as the public address announcer at Rogers Centre.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perry|first1=Dayn|title=Jose Bautista does some P.A. announcing while on suspension|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/watch-jose-bautista-does-some-p-a-announcing-while-on-suspension/|publisher=CBS Sports|accessdate=May 28, 2016}}</ref> On June 17, 2016, he was placed on the 15-day disabled list due to an injury to his left big toe.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jose Bautista placed on disabled list after collision with outfield wall|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/16289117/toronto-blue-jays-jose-bautista-placed-15-day-dl-outfield-collision|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref> He returned from the disabled list near the end of July. On August 2, Bautista hit his 300th career home run, a solo shot off [[Houston Astros]] starter [[Lance McCullers Jr.]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/193244784/jose-bautista-the-newest-member-of-300-hr-club/|title=Bautista the newest member of 300-HR club|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=August 2, 2016|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, the Blue Jays extended a $17.2 million qualifying offer to Bautista,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-extend-qualifying-offers-encarnacion-bautista/|title=Blue Jays extend qualifying offers to Encarnacion, Bautista|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref> which he declined on November 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/208848218/edwin-encarnacion-jose-bautista-free-agents/|title=Encarnacion, Bautista reject qualifying offers|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=November 14, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\n[[File:Jose Bautista - 2017 (36556471990) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Bautista making a sliding catch at [[Oriole Park at Camden Yards]]]]\nOn January 18, 2017, Bautista signed a one-year, $18 million contract with the Blue Jays. The contract included a $17 million mutual option for the 2018 season, as well as a $20 million vesting option for 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/213596024/jose-bautista-signs-1-year-deal-with-blue-jays/|title=Bautista returns to Blue Jays on 1-year deal|last1=Chisholm|first1=Gregor|last2=Sanchez|first2=Jesse|work=MLB.com|date=January 18, 2017|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> On August 11, Bautista reached the 20 home run mark for the eighth consecutive season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/247818944/bucs-jameson-taillon-outduels-marcus-stroman/|title=Stroman goes 8, but errors undo Blue Jays|last1=Berry|first1=Adam|last2=Matheson|first2=Keegan|work=MLB.com|date=August 11, 2017|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBautista ended the year batting .203 with 23 home runs and 65 RBIs. His .203 batting average was the lowest of all qualified major league batters.<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=13,a Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2017 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Dashboard | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  The Blue Jays declined Bautista's option for 2018 on November 4, 2017 marking the end of his career as a Blue Jay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-formally-decline-jose-bautistas-17-million-mutual-option/ |title=Blue Jays formally decline Jose Bautista\u2019s $17-million mutual option |first=Mike |last=Johnston |work=sportsnet.ca |date=November 4, 2017 |accessdate=November 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n====Atlanta Braves====\nOn April&nbsp;18 2018, Bautista signed a minor league contract with the [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jose Bautista signs minor-league deal with Atlanta Braves|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/baseball/2018/04/18/jose-bautista-signs-minor-league-deal-with-atlanta-braves.html|accessdate=April 18, 2018|date=April 18, 2018 |first=Laura |last=Armstrong}}</ref> After playing a few games for the [[Gwinnett Stripers]], the Braves promoted Bautista to start at third base for the first of a three-game series against the San Francisco Giants on May&nbsp;4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/baseball/bautista-play-third-bat-first-for-gwinnett-open-doubleheader/JMj5OZJUrKBuzG5KebFmGO/|title=Starting third base job awaits promoted Bautista}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/jose-bautista-coming-up-to-join-braves/c-275200970|title=Jose Bautista coming up to join Braves|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 4, 2018|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref> On May&nbsp;12, 2018, Bautista hit his first home run with the Braves.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Mark|title=Joey Bats redeems error with first Braves HR|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/jose-bautista-hits-his-first-braves-homer/c-276477720|accessdate=May 20, 2018|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 13, 2018}}</ref> Bautista batted .143 with two home runs and five RBIs in 35 at bats over 12 games played before being released by the Braves on May&nbsp;20.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Mark|url=https://www.mlb.com/braves/news/braves-release-third-baseman-jose-bautista/c-277528920|title=Braves release scuffling Bautista|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 20, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====New York Mets====\nOn May 22, 2018, Bautista signed a one-year deal with the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/05/22/mets-closing-in-on-deal-with-jose-bautista|title=Mets agree to deal with Jose Bautista|work=New York Post|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Bautista hit a double in his first at bat with the Mets. He later scored on a sacrifice fly. On June 22, 2018 Bautista hit his first home run as a member of the Mets against the Dodgers making it his 3rd of the season (his previous two being with the Braves). On July 6, Bautista hit a [[Walk-off home run|walk off grand slam]] against the Rays, which was the first walk off home run of his career.<ref>[https://www.mlb.com/mets/gameday/rays-vs-mets/2018/07/06/530729#game_state=,game_tab=,game=530729 Rays vs. Mets | 07/06/18 | New York Mets<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2018 he batted .204 with the Mets with a .351 OBP.\n\n====Philadelphia Phillies====\nThe Mets traded Bautista to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] for a player to be named later or cash on August 28, 2018.<ref>[https://twitter.com/MLBRosterMoves/status/1034495695078744064?s=19 MLBRosterMoves on Twitter: \".@Phillies acquire INF/OF Jos\u00e9 Bautista from @Mets for PTBN or cash. #MLBOnTheMove\u2026 \"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He batted .244 for the Phillies with a .404 OBP and .870 OPS. He was the 9th-oldest player in the National League.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/2018-other-leaders.shtml 2018 National League Awards, All-Stars, & More Leaders | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He elected free agency on October 29.\n\nIn November 2019, Bautista expressed desire to continue his career after taking the 2019 season off. In March 2020, announced he was hoping to return as a two-way player.\n\n==Awards and accomplishments==\n===Awards===\n* 5\u00d7 [[American League]] [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month Award|Player of the Month]] (Jul. 2010, Aug. 2010, Apr. 2011, May 2011, Jun. 2012)<ref name=aug2010pom/>\n* 4\u00d7 American League [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|Player of the Week]] (May 16, 2010; August 1, 2010; August 29, 2010; July 3, 2011)\n* [[Esurance]]'s MLB Award for Best Play, Offense (2015)<ref name=esurancebestoffense/>\n* 2\u00d7 [[Hank Aaron Award]] (2010, 2011)\n* [[John Cerutti]] Award (2010)<ref name=\"sports.nationalpost.com\"/>\n* 6\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|Major League Baseball All-Star]] ([[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2010]]\u2013[[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|15]])<ref name=2010mlbasg/><ref name=2011mlbasg/><ref name=\"Ballot record\"/><ref name=2013mlbasg/><ref name=2014mlbasg/><ref name=2015mlbasg/>\n* 2\u00d7 [[Neil MacCarl Award]] (2010, 2011)<ref name=\"sports.nationalpost.com\"/>\n* 3\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] at [[List of Silver Slugger Award winners at outfield|outfield]] (2010, 2011, 2014)\n* Toronto Blue Jays Most Improved Player (2010)<ref name=\"sports.nationalpost.com\"/>\n\n===Accomplishments===\n* 2\u00d7 American League [[bases on balls]] leader (2011, 2015)\n* 2\u00d7 Major League Baseball [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|home run leader]] (2010, 2011)\n* Major League Baseball [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage leader (2011)\n* Major League Baseball [[slugging percentage]] leader (2011)\n* Toronto Blue Jays top-ten in career [[on-base percentage]], [[slugging percentage]], [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage, [[Run (baseball)|runs]] scored, [[total bases]], [[home run]]s, [[runs batted in]], [[bases on balls]] and adjusted on-base plus slugging percentage (through 2015)<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders/>\n\n===Records===\n* Major League Baseball record for largest single-season home run increase (39 from 2009 to 2010)<ref name=hrincrease/>\n* Toronto Blue Jays single-season most bases on balls (132 in 2011)<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders/>\n* Toronto Blue Jays single-season most home runs (54 in 2010)<ref name=tbjhrrecord/>\n* Toronto Blue Jays single-season most offensive WAR (8.3 in 2011)<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders/>\n\n==Personal life==\nBautista's nickname is \"Joey Bats\".<ref name=\"Joey Bats nickname\"/> A species of weevil, ''[[Sicoderus bautistai]]'', was named for Bautista in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canadian scientist names beetle after Jose Bautista |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/canadian-scientist-names-beetle-after-jose-bautista/2018/11/22/1bf405ec-eea2-11e8-8b47-bd0975fd6199_story.html |accessdate=November 23, 2018 |work=Washington Post |agency=Associated Press |date=November 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBautista and his then-girlfriend, Neisha Croyle had their first daughter together, Estela, born April 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=360936 |title=Bautista expected to miss A's series due to personal matter |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/magazine/sportsnet-magazine-stephen-brunt-jose-bautista-feature/|title=SN Magazine: Brunt at home with Bautista|last=Brunt|first=Stephen|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=April 5, 2012|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref> His second daughter, Ava, was born in November 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontolife.com/informer/features/2013/06/20/jose-bautista-back-in-the-game/|title=Back in the Game: Blue Jays slugger Jos\u00e9 Bautista's high-stakes mission to stay on top|last=Cole|first=Trevor|work=torontolife.com|date=June 20, 2013|accessdate=March 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140530005227/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/features/2013/06/20/jose-bautista-back-in-the-game/|archive-date=May 30, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In 2011 Bautista set up a program to aid athletes to have the same opportunity he had to attend American universities. Initially focused on the Dominican Republic, it has expanded to Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bautistafund.org/about|title=Bautista Family Education Fund|work=bautistafund.org|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref> Bautista and his girlfriend Neisha Croyle were married November 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunter|first1=Ian|title=Here\u2019s what we know about Jose Bautista\u2019s wedding|url=https://torontolife.com/city/toronto-sports/heres-know-jose-bautistas-wedding/|accessdate=May 21, 2018|work=Toronto Life|date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBautista's younger brother, Luis played college baseball at [[Florida International University]]. He was drafted by the [[Chicago Cubs]] in the 32nd round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft]] and played in their minor league system through 2008.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Dominican Republic|Baseball}}\n{{div col}}\n* [[50 home run club]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career putouts as a right fielder leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players from the Dominican Republic]]\n* [[List of Toronto Blue Jays home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Toronto Blue Jays team records]]\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays award winners and league leaders]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Jos\u00e9 Bautista}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=430832|espn=5890|br=b/bautijo02|fangraphs=1887|brm=bautis001jos|retro=B/Pbautj001}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/c9f08cf8 Jos\u00e9 Bautista] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[https://www.ultimatemets.com/profile.php?PlayerCode=1054 Jos\u00e9 Bautista] at Ultimate Mets Database\n* {{twitter|name=Jose Bautista}}\n* {{instagram|JoeyBats19|Jose Bautista}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/commentary/2016/12/28/the-flip-side-to-jos-bautista.html|title=The flip side to Jose Bautista|last=Dodds|first=James|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=28 December 2016|accessdate=28 December 2016}}\n\n{{AL home run champions}}\n{{AL Hank Aaron Award Winners}}\n{{AL OF Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{50 home run club|state=collapsed}}\n{{Dominican Republic roster 2009 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Dominican Republic roster 2017 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bautista, Jose}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2009 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:2017 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:Altoona Curve players]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League home run champions]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Braves players]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Chipola Indians baseball players]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Dunedin Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Florida Fire Frogs players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Gwinnett Stripers players]]\n[[Category:Hickory Crawdads players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Indians players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals players]]\n[[Category:Lynchburg Hillcats players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players from the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball right fielders]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third basemen]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Fisher Cats players]]\n[[Category:New York Mets players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:PUCMM alumni]]\n[[Category:Silver Slugger Award winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:Tampa Bay Devil Rays players]]\n[[Category:Tigres del Licey players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Williamsport Crosscutters players]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the pitcher of the same name|Jos\u00e9 Bautista (pitcher)}}\n{{short description|Dominican baseball player}}\n{{Spanish name 2|Bautista|Santos}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name          = Jos\u00e9 Bautista\n| image         = Jose Bautista 9 15 18 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size    = \n| caption       = Bautista with the Phillies in 2018\n| position      = [[Right fielder]] / [[Third baseman]]\n| team          =  \n| number        = \n| bats          = Right\n| throws        = Right\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1980|10|19}}\n| birth_place   = [[Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic]]\n| debutleague   = MLB\n| debutdate     = April 4\n| debutyear     = 2004\n| debutteam     = Baltimore Orioles\n| finalleague   = MLB\n| finaldate     = September 30\n| finalyear     = 2018\n| finalteam     = Philadelphia Phillies\n| statleague    = MLB\n| stat1label    = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value    = .247\n| stat2label    = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value    = 344\n| stat3label    = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value    = 975\n| teams         = \n* [[Baltimore Orioles]] ({{mlby|2004}})\n* [[Tampa Bay Rays|Tampa Bay Devil Rays]] ({{mlby|2004}})\n* [[Kansas City Royals]] ({{mlby|2004}})\n* [[Pittsburgh Pirates]] ({{mlby|2004}}\u2013{{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2008}}\u2013{{mlby|2017}})\n* [[Atlanta Braves]] ({{mlby|2018}})\n* [[New York Mets]] ({{mlby|2018}})\n* [[Philadelphia Phillies]] ({{mlby|2018}})\n| awards        = \n* 6\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2010]]\u2013[[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2015]])\n* 3\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] (2010, 2011, 2014)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Hank Aaron Award]] (2010, 2011)\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|MLB home run leader]] (2010, 2011)\n}}\n'''Jos\u00e9 Antonio Bautista Santos''' (born October 19, 1980) is a [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominican]] former [[professional baseball]] [[right fielder]] and [[third baseman]]. He has played in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) for the [[Baltimore Orioles]], [[Tampa Bay Devil Rays]], [[Kansas City Royals]], [[Pittsburgh Pirates]], [[Toronto Blue Jays]], [[Atlanta Braves]], [[New York Mets]], and [[Philadelphia Phillies]].\n\nBautista's professional career began when the Pittsburgh Pirates selected him in the 20th round of the [[2000 Major League Baseball draft]]. In {{by|2010}}, he became the 26th member of the [[50 home run club]], while leading MLB in [[home runs]] for the first of two consecutive seasons. From 2010\u2013{{by|2015}}, Bautista hit more home runs than any player in the major leagues.  An [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|MLB All-Star]] selection six consecutive times, he has won three [[Silver Slugger Awards]] and two [[Hank Aaron Award]]s. In addition, he has received the [[American League]] (AL) [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month|Player of the Month Award]], five times, and the AL [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|Player of the Week]], four times. Before being traded to the Blue Jays, Bautista primarily played [[third base]].\n\nAlthough major league [[Scout (sport)|scouts]] initially took note of Bautista while he was in [[junior college]] for his batting skills \u2013 including [[Power hitter|power hitting]] potential and a strong throwing arm \u2013 his career would take many detours, until Bautista finally realized his potential, in 2010. He made his MLB debut with the Baltimore Orioles in {{by|2004}}, and, that year, became the first player ever to appear on [[#Early career|five MLB rosters in one season]]. The last of those clubs was the Pirates, where he would spend four-plus seasons, seeing time as a [[utility player]], while playing at six different positions, including [[designated hitter]] (DH).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/players/7264/career;_ylt=AluOYHKnUCIIU54UZfxxEc.FCLcF |title=Jos\u00e9 Bautista \u2013 Toronto Blue Jays \u2013 Career Statistics \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBautista was then traded to the Blue Jays, in August {{by|2008}}.<ref>{{cite web |author=Blue Jays Press Release |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20080821&content_id=3344473&vkey=pr_tor&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor&partnerId=rss_tor |title=Blue Jays acquire Bautista |publisher=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 21, 2008 |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref> After making adjustments to his swing, he broke through with ten home runs in September {{by|2009}}. Bautista has since been voted in the top ten in the AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] four times, and is a [[List of Toronto Blue Jays team records|leader or among the top ten in numerous offensive single-season and career categories]] in Blue Jays' franchise history.<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/TOR/leaders_bat.shtml |title=Blue Jays top ten batting leaders |website=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |accessdate=January 6, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2010 to {{by|2017}}, Bautista hit at least 20 home runs each year, and in four of those seasons, hit at least 35 home runs, both [[Run (baseball)|scored]] and [[Run batted in|drove in]] at least 100 runs, and drew at least 100 [[bases on balls]], including twice leading the AL. In {{by|2015}}, while playing in the [[Major League Baseball postseason|playoffs]] for the first time, his [[Bat flip#Jos\u00e9 Bautista bat flip|bat flip]] in the [[2015 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] (ALDS) caused a sensation that became a symbol of Toronto's first playoff appearance in 22 years. In {{by|2011}}, Bautista set up a program that assists athletes from the [[Dominican Republic]] to attend universities in the United States.\n\n==Early life==\nComing from a [[middle-class]] family in the [[Dominican Republic]] that placed great importance on education, Bautista began studying English at age eight.  His mother was an accountant and [[financial planner]], and his father, who had earned a [[master's degree]] in [[agricultural engineering]] in Hungary, ran poultry farms.  Bautista attended a private high school, De La Salle High School, in [[Santo Domingo]].  He was aided by the Latin Athletes Education Fund,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/05/sports/baseball/05odermann.html|title=Education fund for latin players quietly changes lives |last=Schwarz|first=Alan|work=nytimes.com|date=May 5, 2008|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref> designed for players from Spanish-speaking countries aspiring to play [[college baseball]] in the United States.  Although he invested much time in pursuing [[professional baseball]], Bautista studied business at [[Pontificia Universidad Cat\u00f3lica Madre y Maestra|Mother and Teacher Pontifical Catholic University]] in the event a career in baseball did not materialize.<ref name=vagabond>{{cite web |url=http://www.thepostgame.com/features/201106/number-crusher-how-blue-jays-slugger-jose-bautista-experimented-his-way-greatness |title=How Jose Bautista went from baseball vagabond to the game's best slugger |last=Passan |first=Jeff |work=thepostgame.com |date=June 14, 2011 |accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter working out with various [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) clubs, he turned down offers of $5,000 from the [[New York Yankees]] and $42,000 from the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]]. The [[Cincinnati Reds]] offered him $300,000, which Bautista accepted; however, before the contract could become official, the team changed [[List of Cincinnati Reds owners and executives|ownership]] and subsequently rescinded the offer.  Bautista then created a highlight tape of himself using a [[camcorder]] and sent it to various colleges in the United States.  There was no response until he received a call from Oscar P\u00e9rez, whom he had known from the Quique Cruz League in the Dominican Republic.  P\u00e9rez informed him of the Latin Athletes Education Fund, designed for players from Spanish-speaking countries aspiring to play [[college baseball]] in the United States.  He connected Bautista with Don Odermann, a businessman in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]].  Odermann, who assisted baseball players from Latin America desiring to play baseball in the US, knew that [[Chipola College]], a [[junior college]] in [[Marianna, Florida]], was seeking an everyday player.  There, Bautista played for two years until being drafted.<ref name=vagabond/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/02/10/jose-bautista-toronto-blue-jays-bautista-family-education-fund |title=Jose Bautista giving back to Latin America by giving kids an education |last=Bradley |first=Jeff |work=si.com|date=February 13, 2015|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Early career===\nThe [[2000 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh Pirates]] drafted Jos\u00e9 Bautista in the 20th round of the [[2000 Major League Baseball draft]]. He signed with the Pirates for a $500,000 signing bonus.<ref name=schoenfield>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/sweetspot/post/_/id/64975/how-jose-bautista-became-jose-bautista|title=How Jose Bautista became Jose Bautista|date=October 19, 2015|work=ESPN|first=David|last=Schoenfield|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Bautista played for the [[Williamsport Crosscutters]] of the [[Class A-Short Season]] [[New York-Penn League]] in 2001 and the [[Hickory Crawdads]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[South Atlantic League]] in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/more-sports/2010/08/04/jose-bautista|title=Joe Lemire: How the Blue Jays' Jose Bautista pulled himself to prominence|first=Joe|last=Lemire|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=August 4, 2010|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref> In 2003, he played for the [[Lynchburg Hillcats]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Carolina League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milb.com/milb/news/former-hillcat-stuns-majors-with-2010-numbers/c-17047540|title=Former Hillcat Stuns Majors With 2010 Numbers|work=MiLB.com|date=March 21, 2011|accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter the 2003 season, the [[2004 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore Orioles]] selected Bautista in the [[Rule 5 draft]] and carried him on their [[Opening Day]] roster.  He made his MLB debut with Baltimore on April 4, 2004. After playing 16 games with the Orioles, the [[2004 Tampa Bay Devil Rays season|Tampa Bay Devil Rays]] claimed him off [[Major League Baseball transactions#Waivers|waivers]] on June 3. Twenty-five days later, the [[2004 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]] purchased him from Tampa Bay after a 12-game stint with the Devil Rays. He played 13 games for the Royals before they traded him to the [[2004 New York Mets season|New York Mets]] on July 30 for [[Justin Huber]], who then traded him minutes later to [[2004 Pittsburgh Pirates season|Pittsburgh]] with [[Ty Wigginton]] and minor leaguer Matt Peterson for [[Kris Benson]] and [[Jeff Keppinger]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/news/040730benson.html |title=Trade Central |magazine=Baseball America |date=July 30, 2004 |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  This series of transactions made him the first player to appear on five different Major League Baseball rosters in one season, only since matched by [[Oliver Drake (baseball)|Oliver Drake]] in 2018.<ref name=journey>{{cite web |last=Snedden |first=Jeffrey |url=http://www.pittsburghsportingnews.com/the-amazing-journeys-of-chris-davis-and-jose-bautista/ |title=The amazing journeys of Chris Davis and Jose Bautista |publisher=Pittsburgh Sporting News |date=July 2013 |accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref> (Drake, however, actually played for all five teams, while Bautista only played for four; he never actually suited up or played for the Mets.)\n\nBautista played in 11 games for the Pirates in [[2005 Pittsburgh Pirates season|2005]].  In [[2006 Pittsburgh Pirates season|2006]], his first full season in the major leagues, Bautista [[Batting average (baseball)|hit]] .235 with 16 [[home run]]s (HR) and 51 [[runs batted in]] (RBI).  The following season in 2007, he posted similar numbers in 142 games, finishing the season with a batting average of .254, 15 home runs and 63 RBI.  That same year, he became the starting [[third baseman]] for the Pittsburgh Pirates.  He took over for reigning National League [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|batting champion]] [[Freddy Sanchez]], who moved to [[Second baseman|second base]].\n\nBautista was to be the Pirates' starting third baseman and backup outfielder in [[2008 Pittsburgh Pirates season|2008]].  From June 14 to 24, he hit five home runs in a span of nine games against [[interleague]] opponents [[2008 Baltimore Orioles season|Baltimore]], [[2008 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]], [[2008 Toronto Blue Jays season|Toronto Blue Jays]], and the [[2008 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]].  However, he struggled offensively for most of the year, and after the 2008 trade deadline Bautista lost his starting job to the newly acquired [[Andy LaRoche]].  Bautista was optioned to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Indianapolis Indians]] on August 13.\n\n===Toronto Blue Jays===\n====2008====\nOn August 21, 2008, the Pirates traded Bautista to the Blue Jays for a [[player to be named later]], who eventually was [[Robinzon D\u00edaz]].<ref name=journey/><ref>{{cite news |first=Dejan |last=Kovacevic |title=Pirates trade Bautista to Blue Jays |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08234/906103-100.stm |work=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |date=August 21, 2008 |accessdate=August 21, 2008}}</ref> The Blue Jays needed a third baseman due to an injury to [[Scott Rolen]].<ref name=schoenfield/> Bautista batted .214 in 21 games for Toronto after the trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/ottawa-citizen/20100605/293419281736841|title=This time, A.J. won't soon forget Bautista|work=Ottawa Citizen|via=[[PressReader]]|date=June 5, 2010|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2009====\n[[File:Jose Bautista in 2009.jpg|left|thumb|Bautista in 2009]]\nStarting the [[2009 Toronto Blue Jays season|2009 season]] on the bench, [[List of Toronto Blue Jays managers|manager]] [[Cito Gaston]] assigned Bautista to back up Rolen and [[outfielder]]s [[Alex R\u00edos]] and [[Adam Lind]]. Bautista started the season with a .317 batting average, .404 [[on-base percentage]] (OBP) and .463 [[slugging percentage]] (SLG) in 49 plate appearances in April.  However, his numbers fell off, as he batted between .167 and .231 each month from May through August with two total home runs. At times he showed marked plate discipline; in the month of May, he walked 14 times for a .403 OBP despite batting just .231.<ref name=\"BR\">{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/bautijo02-bat.shtml |title=Jose Bautista statistics & history |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref>  Eventually, the Chicago White Sox claimed Rios off waivers, the Blue Jays assigned Lind to the role of [[designated hitter]], and an injury to [[Marco Scutaro]] led to an increase in Bautista's playing time and making him the [[leadoff hitter]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Newman |first=Mark |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/5706712/ |title=Fans face tough Final Vote choices |date=July 5, 2009 |accessdate=September 21, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/news/story?id=4390120 |title=White Sox acquire Rios from Toronto |publisher=ESPN.com |date=August 10, 2009 |accessdate=September 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAs the season drew to a close, the Blue Jays made changes to their coaching staff.  One was to move first base coach [[Dwayne Murphy]] to replace the retiring [[Gene Tenace]] as hitting coach.  Formerly a Blue Jays' minor league roving hitting instructor and hitting coach, Murphy had already spent nearly one year working with Bautista, teaching him to leverage his pull power by starting his swing with his now-familiar high leg kick.<ref name=journey/>  In September, he finally broke through, hitting 10 home runs with 21 RBI, a .257 batting average and a .606 [[slugging percentage]] (SLG).<ref name=\"BR\"/>  He hit 13 total HR in 2009 with 40 RBI, a batting average of .235, and 79 [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] in 113 games.  Originally considered to be a non-tender candidate, he re-signed with the Blue Jays on a one-year, $2.4&nbsp;million US contract for the 2010 season.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stark |first=Jayson |authorlink=Jayson Stark |title=More free agents coming? |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date=December 11, 2008 |url = http://insider.espn.go.com/espn/blog/index?entryID=3763719&searchName=winter_meetings_2008&campaign=rsssrch&source=jayson_stark |accessdate=January 24, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author =  |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |title=Jays re-sign Bautista, McGowan, Chavez, add Gathright |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=December 13, 2009 |url = http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/story/2009/12/13/sp-baseball-jays-signings.html |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\n====2010====\nBautista began the [[2010 Toronto Blue Jays season|2010]] campaign as the starting right fielder and leadoff hitter. On May 17, he was named [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|AL Player of the Week]] after hitting .444 (8-for-18) with 20 [[total bases]], four home runs, eight RBI, eight runs scored, a .565 OBP, and an MLB-best 1.111 SLG.<ref>{{cite news |author = |title = Bautista, Prado named Players of the Week |publisher = [[Major League Baseball]] |date =May 17, 2010 |url = http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100517&content_id=10112284&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> Bautista hit his 20th home run as part of a two-home run night against the [[2010 St. Louis Cardinals season|St. Louis Cardinals]] on June 22, setting a new career high for a single season in just two months.<ref name=\"Career High\">{{cite news |last=Zwolinkski |first=Mark |title = Bautista's two homers not enough for Jays against Cardinals |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date =June 22, 2010 |url = https://www.thestar.com/sports/baseball/article/827234--bautista-s-two-homers-not-enough-for-jays-against-cardinals |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref>\n\nBautista was selected as a reserve for the [[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game]].<ref name=2010mlbasg>{{cite news |last=Campbell |first=Morgan |title = Blue Jays\u2019 Vernon Wells, Jose Bautista and John Buck earn All-Star spots |newspaper = Toronto Star |date =July 4, 2010 |url = https://www.thestar.com/sports/baseball/mlb/bluejays/article/831834--wells-bautista-buck-earn-all-star-spots |accessdate=July 31, 2010}}</ref> Bautista entered the game as a pinch runner for [[Josh Hamilton]] and finished the game 0\u2013for-1.<ref>{{cite web |title = Boxscore: NL All-Stars vs AL All-Stars |publisher = [[Major League Baseball]] |date =July 13, 2010 |url = http://mlb.mlb.com/news/boxscore.jsp?gid=2010_07_13_nasmlb_aasmlb_1 |accessdate=August 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nFor the month of July, Bautista batted .347, with 11 home runs, 29 RBI, and an AL-leading .765 slugging percentage, sharing American League Player of the Month honors with Twins outfielder [[Delmon Young]].<ref>{{cite news |author = |url=http://www.torontosun.com/sports/baseball/2010/08/04/14923856.html |title=Jays' Bautista earns AL monthly award |work=[[Toronto Sun]] |date = August 4, 2010 | accessdate = August 4, 2010}}</ref> Bautista was also named Blue Jays' Player of the Month, which is selected through voting by the Toronto chapter of the Baseball Writers' Association of America.<ref name=\"July\">{{cite news |first = Jordan|last = Bastian| url = http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100801&content_id=12888704&notebook_id=12889066&vkey=notebook_tor&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor | title =Bautista named July Player of the Month | publisher = [[Major League Baseball Advanced Media|MLB Advanced Media, L.P.]]| date = August 1, 2010 | accessdate = August 1, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100801&content_id=12888328&vkey=pr_tor&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor |title=Jose Bautista Named Honda Player of the Month |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  With his 12 home runs in May and 11 in July, Bautista became only the third Blue Jay player in [[History of the Toronto Blue Jays|franchise history]] to have two months with at least 10 home runs.<ref name=\"July\"/>\n\nBautista was named co-winner of the American League Player of the Week award for the period ending August 1. Bautista hit .545 with five homers and 13 RBI during that span.<ref>{{cite news |author = | url = https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=329342 | title = Jay's Bautista shares Player of the Week honour | publisher = [[The Sports Network|TSN]]| date = August 2, 2010 | accessdate = August 4, 2010}}</ref> On August 26, Bautista hit his 100th career home run against the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref>{{cite news |author = | url = https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=331753| title = Peralta, Scherzer Lead Tigers Over Blue Jays| publisher = [[The Sports Network|TSN]]| date = August 26, 2010 | accessdate = August 30, 2010}}</ref> Bautista was again named player of the week for the week ending August 29; in seven games that week, Bautista led the American League with a .500 batting average (10-for-20) and hit four home runs.<ref>{{cite news |author = | url = http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/2010/08/30/jays_bautista/| title = Bautista takes top honours| publisher = [[Rogers Sportsnet|Sportsnet]]| date = August 26, 2010 | accessdate = August 30, 2010}}</ref> Bautista became the only Blue Jays player to ever win the award three times in one season.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}} Bautista won AL Player of the Month for the month of August, in which he hit he led the AL in home runs (12), RBI (24), slugging percentage (.724) and total bases (72), while tying for the lead in extra-base hits (18). He finished tied for second with 23 runs and was third with 23 walks.<ref name=aug2010pom>{{cite news |last=Molinaro |first=John |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/story/2010/09/02/sp-jose-bautista.html |title=Jays' Bautista wins AL's monthly honour | publisher = [[CBC Sports]]| date = September 2, 2010 | accessdate = September 2, 2010}}</ref> He also won the Honda Player of the Month Award, his second such award in as many months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20100901&content_id=14171994&fext=.jsp&c_id=tor&vkey=pr_tor |title=Jose Bautista named Honda player of the month |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn September 17, Bautista set the new Blue Jays single-season home run record with his 48th home run, breaking the record set by [[George Bell (outfielder)|George Bell]].<ref name=tbjhrrecord>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=334138 |title=Bautista hits club record 48th homer as Jays thump Red Sox |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> On September 23, Bautista became the 26th player in Major League Baseball history to reach the [[50 home run club]] in one season, and the first Toronto Blue Jay player to do so.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=334862 |title=Site Map |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  His 52nd home run set a new MLB record for the largest single-season increase in home runs, eclipsing [[Davey Johnson]]'s 38 home run increase from 1972 to 1973.<ref name=hrincrease>{{cite news |last=Bastian |first=Jordan |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100924&content_id=15029508&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Bautista blasts Nos. 51, 52 as Jays drop O's | publisher = [[Major League Baseball Advanced Media|MLB Advanced Media, L.P.]] |date=September 25, 2010 |accessdate=September 25, 2010}}</ref> Bautista finished the 2010 season with an [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|MLB-leading]] 54 home runs, the highest total since [[Alex Rodriguez]] hit 54 in 2007.  Bautista won the AL [[Hank Aaron Award|Hank Aaron]] and a [[Silver Slugger Award|Silver Slugger]] Awards for his offensive performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101031&content_id=15924244&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Big lumber nets Bautista, Votto special hardware |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=October 31, 2010 |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=340753 |title=Jays star Bautista wins Silver Slugger award |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> and finished fourth in the AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] (MVP) voting, behind Hamilton, [[Miguel Cabrera]] and [[Robinson Can\u00f3]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101123&content_id=16182576&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=Bautista's big year good for fourth in MVP race |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date=October 31, 2010 |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  The Toronto chapter of the BBWAA named Bautista the [[Neil MacCarl Award|Blue Jays' Most Valuable Player]], the Blue Jays' Most Improved Player, and presented him the [[John Cerutti|John Cerutti Award]] for displaying \"goodwill, cooperation and character\".<ref name=\"sports.nationalpost.com\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2010/11/25/jays-bautista-adds-to-2010-awards-haul |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130129124910/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2010/11/25/jays-bautista-adds-to-2010-awards-haul |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 29, 2013 |title=Jays\u2019 Bautista adds to 2010 awards haul &#124; Posted Sports &#124; National Post |publisher=nationalpost.com |accessdate=September 28, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n====2011====\n[[File:Jos\u00e9 Bautista on June 5, 2011.jpg|thumb|left|Bautista at bat in 2011.]]\nBautista agreed to a five-year contract extension worth US$64 million before the [[2011 Toronto Blue Jays season|2011 season]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=354275 |title=Blue Jays announce five-year, $64M deal with Bautista |publisher=Tsn.ca |date=February 17, 2011 |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref>  He began the season as the starting right fielder for the Blue Jays, with [[Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n]] playing third base.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110329&content_id=17180068&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=Jose Bautista named Blue Jays' right fielder |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref> Bautista walked 28 times in the month of April, breaking a club record that was set when [[Carlos Delgado]] collected 26 bases on balls in April 2001.  Bautista was unanimously selected for the Blue Jays' Player of the Month award, and was also named the AL Player of the Month for the month of April (his third such award in four months, dating back to the 2010 season).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110501&content_id=18486498&notebook_id=18489298&vkey=notebook_tor&c_id=tor |title=Bautista unanimously wins monthly award |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110503&content_id=18577412&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=American League monthly honors go to Jered Weaver, Jose Bautista |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, Bautista hit three home runs against the [[2011 Minnesota Twins season|Minnesota Twins]], the first three-home run game of his career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=365820 |title=Bautista belts three homers in matinee win over Twins |publisher=Tsn.ca |date=May 16, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> On May 28, in a home game against the [[2011 Chicago White Sox season|Chicago White Sox]], Bautista hit his 20th home run, a three-run shot to left field, becoming the first player to reach 20 home runs in 2011 as well as the fastest player to reach 20 home runs (44 games) in Blue Jays franchise history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/recap?gid=310528114 |title=Guillen frustrated as Jays beat White Sox in 14th |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date=May 28, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110601031448/https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/recap?gid=310528114 |archive-date=June 1, 2011}}</ref>  Bautista won the AL Player of the Month award for May, his fourth such award in five months.  He also became the first player to have the highest number of home runs in a single month for five consecutive months since [[Jimmie Foxx]] did so from June 1933 to April 1934.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=367678 |title=Blue Jays' Bautista named AL player of the month |publisher=Tsn.ca |date=February 6, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> Bautista also won the Blue Jays' Player of the Month award for the second consecutive month.<ref>{{cite web|last=Oegema |first=Cam |url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2011/6/2/2202914/jose-bautista-voted-blue-jay-player-of-the-month |title=Jose Bautista Voted Blue Jay Player of the Month |publisher=Bluebird Banter |date=June 2, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> On June 23, the Blue Jays shifted Bautista to third base and recalled [[Eric Thames]] to play the outfield.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/2011/06/23/bautista_move/ |title=Jays to move Bautista back to third base |publisher=sportsnet.ca |date=June 23, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBautista was selected for the [[2011 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2011 MLB All-Star Game]], receiving a record 7,454,753 votes.<ref name=2011mlbasg>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110703&content_id=21339402&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=Toronto Blue Jays slugger Jose Bautista tops all to earn starting All-Star nod |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref>  At the time of his selection, he led the MLB in home runs (26), walks (70), OBP (.471), slugging percentage (.679), OPS (1.150), times on base (160) and was also in second place for runs scored (64), total bases (182) and extra base hits (41).  He became the first Blue Jay in history to lead the league in All-Star voting. He was also the first Blue Jay to be voted into the All-Star game as a starter since [[Carlos Delgado]] in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110703&content_id=21339402&vkey=news_tor&c_id=tor |title=Toronto Blue Jays slugger Jose Bautista tops all to earn starting All-Star nod |website=Toronto Blue Jays|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>  Bautista participated in the [[2011 Major League Baseball Home Run Derby|Home Run Derby]]; he hit four home runs and was eliminated in the first round.<ref name=hrderby2011>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/events/all_star/y2011/index.jsp?content=hr_derby |title= 2011 All-Star Game \u2013 Home Run Derby |publisher=MLB.com | date=July 21, 2011 | accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn August 5, with the debut of prospect [[Brett Lawrie]] to play third base, Bautista returned to right field. In a game against the [[2011 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] on August 20, Bautista walked three times, which brought his season total to 102 walks in 113 games, the fastest a player reached 100 walks since [[Barry Bonds]] in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/news;_ylt=Am6RaR0nfG_EcHzN8W2baDuFCLcF?slug=ap-bluejays |title=Bautista draws 3 more walks in loss to A's |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date=April 20, 2011 |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref> During a game against the New York Yankees on September 5, Bautista hit his 40th home run of the season, a solo homer off reliever [[Rafael Soriano]]. He became the second player in franchise history with back-to-back 40 home run seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=375152 |title=Jeter homers, drives in five as Yankees sweep Blue Jays |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>  Two games later on September 7, against the [[2011 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]], Bautista stole home plate on a double steal in which Lawrie took second base, becoming the first 40 home run hitter to steal home plate since [[Adam Dunn]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=375348 |title=Encarnacion drives in five, Jays comeback to beat Red Sox |publisher=Tsn.ca |accessdate=September 29, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013122106/http://tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=375348 |archivedate=October 13, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter leading the major leagues in home runs for the second consecutive season with 43, Bautista became the first player to do so since [[Mark McGwire]] in 1998 and 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/HR_leagues.shtml |title=Yearly league leaders & records for home runs |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 13, 2016}}</ref>  Baustista also led the majors in slugging percentage (.608), OPS (1.056) and walks (132) and the AL in [[Intentional base on balls|intentional walks]] (24).  He placed second in OBP (.447)<ref name=baustistamlbstats>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/bautijo02.shtml |title=Jos\u00e9 Baustista |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 13, 2015}}</ref> behind Cabrera.  He batted .302 and also placed in the top ten in the league in runs scored (105), [[total bases]] (312) and [[times on base]] (293).  Defensively, he led AL right fielders with five [[double play]]s turned and placed fourth in [[Assist (baseball)|assists]] with 13 and fifth with six [[Error (baseball)|errors]].<ref name=baustistamlbstats/>  His walk total was the highest in the league since [[Jason Giambi]] collected 137 in 2000,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/BB_leagues.shtml |title=Yearly league leaders & records for bases on balls |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 13, 2016}}</ref> while setting a new Blue Jays franchise record, which Delgado previously held with 123, also in 2000.  He also set new Blue Jays' single-season records with 8.1 total [[Wins Above Replacement]] (WAR) and 8.3 offensive WAR according to [[Baseball-Reference.com]], edging [[John Olerud]]'s 7.7 total in [[1993 Toronto Blue Jays season|1993]], and Delgado's 8.1 offensive WAR in 2000.  Bautista held the record for total WAR until [[Josh Donaldson]] rated at 8.8 in 2015; however, as of 2015, Bautista still holds the record for offensive WAR.<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders/>  He was the American League winner of the Hank Aaron Award for the second consecutive season,<ref>Davidi, Shi  (October 24, 2011) [https://web.archive.org/web/20111126124251/http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/2011/10/24/bautista_aaron Another Aaron for Bautista]. ''sportsnet.ca''.</ref> becoming just the third player in the award's history, after Rodriguez and [[Barry Bonds]], to win the award in back-to-back years.  Bautista also received his second consecutive Silver Slugger Award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111102&content_id=25873314&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Top boppers earn Silver Slugger Awards |publisher=MLB.com |date=November 2, 2011 |accessdate= November 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====2012====\n[[File:Jose Bautista of the Toronto Blue Jays, June 30, 2012.jpg|thumb|left|Bautista with the Toronto Blue Jays, June 30, 2012]] On January 30, Bautista was announced as the cover athlete for the Canadian edition of ''[[MLB 12: The Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/bautista-mlb-12/|title=Bautista to grace \u2018MLB 12 The Show\u2019 cover|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=January 30, 2012|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref> In an interleague game against the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] on June 19, [[2012 Toronto Blue Jays season|2012]], Bautista hit the second of three straight solo home runs by the Blue Jays, between [[Colby Rasmus]] and [[Edwin Encarnaci\u00f3n]], the first time since 2005 that the Jays went back-to-back-to-back with home runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/mlb/gameday/index.jsp?gid=2012_06_19_tormlb_milmlb_1&mode=recap&c_id=tor |title=Rasmus, Bautista rally Blue Jays past Crew |publisher=MLB.com | date=June 20, 2012 |accessdate=June 20, 2012}}</ref>  Bautista also took over the MLB lead in home runs for 2012, hitting his 25th on June 27 against the [[2012 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]], which broke the Blue Jays club record for home runs in a month, with 13. He went on to finish the month with 14 home runs, one short of the American League record for June.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\nBautista was voted an American League starter in the [[2012 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] for the second consecutive year and his third overall All-Star selection.  Hamilton surpassed Bautista's record vote total of the prior year.<ref name=\"Ballot record\">{{cite news |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120701&content_id=34263550&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |first=Jesse|last=Sanchez |publisher=MLB.com |date=July 1, 2012 |accessdate=July 2, 2012 |title=Rosters unveiled for 83rd All-Star Game}}</ref>  On July 2, Bautista was named American League Player of the Month for June.  It was his fifth time receiving the honor in his career. He batted .274 with 14 home runs and 30 RBI in the month of June.  His 14 home runs in June set a new Blue Jays franchise record for home runs in a month.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/Bautista+named+Player+Month/6873161/story.html | title=Bautista Named AL Player of the Month | newspaper=The Province | date=July 2, 2012 | accessdate= July 2, 2012}}</ref> Bautista competed in the [[2012 Major League Baseball Home Run Derby|Home Run Derby]]. At the time of his selection, he led all major league players with 26 home runs.<ref name=2012mlbasg>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120701&content_id=34294412&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=NL, AL Home Run Derby teams unveiled | publisher=MLB.com | date=July 2, 2012 | accessdate= July 2, 2012}}</ref> Bautista finished second to [[Prince Fielder]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2012/baseball/mlb/07/09/prince-fielder-home-run-derby-2012.ap/index.html?eref=sihp&sct=hp_t11_a0 |title=Fielder outslugs Bautista to capture second Home Run Derby crown |agency=AP|work=SportsIllustrated.CNN.com|date=July 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBautista was placed on the 15-day disabled list on July 17 with inflammation in his wrist.<ref name=\"Wrist\">{{cite news |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/blue-jays-put-bautista-dl-164939305--mlb.html |title=Blue Jays put Bautista on DL, call up OF Gose |agency=AP|last=Fitzpatrick|first=Mike|work=Yahoo! Sports |date=July 17, 2012 |accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref> He had started in all previous 90 games, and the Blue Jays called up prospect [[Anthony Gose]] to take his place after the game.<ref name=\"Wrist\" /> Bautista was activated on August 24, but returned to the disabled list on August 26 after he re-aggravated the injury to his left wrist. On August 28, the Jays announced that he would undergo season-ending surgery on the wrist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=404018 |title=Jays' Bautista to have wrist surgery; done for season|work=TSN.ca|date=August 28, 2012 |accessdate=August 28, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/2012/08/28/bautista_jose_blue_jays_surgery_wrist/ |title=Bautista needs surgery, done for 2012|work=Sportsnet.ca|last=Cormack |first=Mike|date=August 28, 2012|accessdate=August 28, 2012}}</ref> In 2012, Bautista batted .241 with 27 home runs and 65 RBI in 92 games.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\n====2013====\nOn January 21, [[2013 Toronto Blue Jays season|2013]], it was announced that Bautista would once again be the cover athlete of the Canadian edition of ''[[MLB 13: The Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/MLBTheShow/status/292352514014208000|work=Twitter.com |title=Twitter @MLBTheShow |date=January 18, 2013|access-date=January 21, 2013}}</ref>  Bautista hit his 200th career home run in a game against the [[2013 Boston Red Sox season|Boston Red Sox]] on June 29.  On July 6, he was elected to his fourth consecutive [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], and his third as the starting right fielder for the American League.  At the time of his selection, he batted .264 with 20 HR and 52 RBI.<ref name=2013mlbasg>{{cite news |last=Koreen |first=Eric |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/sports/mlb/jose-bautista-leads-trio-of-blue-jays-to-all-star-game |title=Jose Bautista leads trio of Blue Jays to All-Star Game |newspaper=National Post |date=July 6, 2013 |access-date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>  In the All-Star Game, he recorded the game-winning RBI on a sacrifice fly in the fourth inning as the American League won 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite news |last=Elliot |first=Bob |url=http://www.torontosun.com/2013/07/16/bautista-a-hit-in-mlb-all-star-game |title=Jose Bautista a hit in MLB All-Star Game: Blue Jays slugger sends AL on its way to all-star victory as Rivera goes out in style |newspaper=Toronto Sun |date=July 16, 2013 |access-date=January 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPlaying against the [[2013 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]] on July 30, Bautista hit his 25th home run of the season.  In doing so, he became the fourth player in Blue Jays franchise history to hit at least 25 home runs in four consecutive seasons, joining Bell (1984\u20131987), Carter (1991\u20131996), and Delgado (1996\u20132004).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2013-07-31/mlb-trade-rumors-cubs-red-sox-orioles-phillies-deadline |title=Do deadline deals make sense for non-contenders hoping for quick impact? |last=Spector |first=Jesse |work=[[Sporting News]] |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=July 31, 2013}}</ref>  His season ended prematurely for the second consecutive time on September 4, when it was announced that he would be shut down with a left hip bone bruise.  Bautista finished 2013 with a .259 batting average, 28 home runs, and 73 RBI.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130904&content_id=59535132&notebook_id=59535992&vkey=notebook_tor&c_id=tor |title=Bautista to miss rest of season with hip injury |last=Casella |first=Paul |publisher=MLB.com |date=September 4, 2013|access-date=September 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\nBautista opened the [[2014 Toronto Blue Jays season|2014 season]] with a streak of 37 games in which he reached base safely.  His streak, the longest to open a season in Blue Jays franchise history, came to an end on May 11, when he went 0\u20134.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2014/05/11/blue_jays_drop_third_straight_to_angels.html |title=Blue Jays drop third straight to Angels |last=Kennedy |first=Brendan |work=thestar.com|date=May 11, 2014 |accessdate=May 12, 2014}}</ref>  On June 18, he recorded his 1,000 career hit in a game against the [[2014 New York Yankees season|New York Yankees]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/tor/jose-bautista-notches-1000th-hit-of-career-in-defeat?ymd=20140618&content_id=80490238&vkey=news_tor|title=Bautista notches 1,000th hit of career in defeat|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=June 18, 2014|accessdate=June 18, 2014}}</ref> Bautista was named as the American League Captain for the [[2014 Major League Baseball Home Run Derby]] on June 23.<ref name=hrderby2014>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/jose-bautista-troy-tulowitzki-named-captains-for-home-run-derby?ymd=20140623&content_id=81221760&vkey=news_mlb |title=Bautista, Tulo named captains for reformatted Derby |last=Newman |first=Mark |work=MLB.com |date=June 23, 2014 |accessdate=June 23, 2014}}</ref>  On July 6, it was announced that not only was he elected to his fifth consecutive [[2014 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]], but, for the second time, received the highest number of votes in the Majors, with 5,859,019.<ref name=2014mlbasg>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/tor/blue-jays-slugger-jose-bautista-leads-all-voters?ymd=20140706&content_id=83444292&vkey=news_tor|title=Mr. Popular: Bautista leads all voters on ballot |last=Chisholm |first=Gregor |work=MLB.com|date=July 6, 2014|accessdate=July 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn August 10, Bautista ended the longest game in franchise history by hitting an opposite field single to drive in [[Munenori Kawasaki]] in the 19th inning, and give the Jays the 6\u20135 win over the [[2014 Detroit Tigers season|Detroit Tigers]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/jays-beat-tigers-in-longest-game-in-team-history/ |title=Jays beat Tigers in longest game in team history |work=[[Sportsnet]] |date=August 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 1, 2015}}</ref> On August 26, Bautista hit his 25th home run of the season, and in doing so, joined Carter and Delgado as the only Blue Jays players in franchise history to hit at least 25 in five or more consecutive seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://toronto.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/tor/blue-jays-slugger-jose-bautista-snaps-slump-by-going-deep?ymd=20140827&content_id=91655606&vkey=news_tor |title=Bautista snaps slump by going deep |last=Chisholm |first=Gregor |work=MLB.com |date=August 27, 2014 |accessdate=August 28, 2014}}</ref> Four days later, Bautista hit his 100th career home run at [[Rogers Centre]], a two-run shot off Yankees starter [[Michael Pineda]], and his fourth straight game with a home run which tied a career-high.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thespec.com/sports-story/4806681-jose-bautista-drew-hutchison-lift-toronto-blue-jays-over-new-york-yankees-2-0/ |title=Jose Bautista, Drew Hutchison lift Toronto Blue Jays over New York Yankees 2\u20130|last=Chidley-Hill|first=John|work=[[The Hamilton Spectator]]|date=August 30, 2014|accessdate=August 30, 2014}}</ref> He would go on to hit a home run on August 31, extending his home run streak to five games and establishing a new career-high.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-hit-three-homers-in-win-over-yankees/ |title=Blue Jays hit three homers in win over Yankees |work=Sportsnet |date=August 31, 2014 |accessdate=August 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn a home game against the [[2014 Chicago Cubs season|Chicago Cubs]] on September 8, Bautista hit his 200th home run as a Blue Jay, joining Bell, Delgado, Carter, and [[Vernon Wells]] as the only players with 200 or more home runs in franchise history.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=461306 |title=Bautista hits 200th homer as a Blue Jay in rout of Cubs |work=TSN.ca |date=September 8, 2014 |accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref> Bautista finished 2014 with a .286 batting average, 35 home runs, and 103 RBI.  He won his third Silver Slugger Award for his efforts.\n\n====2015====\n[[File:Jose Bautista talking to fans before a Spring Training Game.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Bautista talking to fans during 2015 [[spring training]]]]\nIn early [[2015 Toronto Blue Jays season|2015]], Bautista earned 10-and-5 rights by having at least 10 years of service time in the big-leagues, with the last 5 being on the same team. These rights give Bautista the ability to veto any trade he would be involved in.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.vice.com/en_us/article/allowing-bautista-encarnacion-to-acquire-veto-rights-shows-blue-jays-have-no-desire-to-trade-them|title=Allowing Bautista, Encarnacion to acquire veto rights shows the Blue Jays have no desire to trade them|work=sports.vice.com|date=June 11, 2015|accessdate=July 1, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In a home game against the [[2015 Baltimore Orioles season|Orioles]] on April 21, Bautista hit his 250th career home run.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/red_sox_mlb/mlb_coverage/2015/04/encarnacion_hits_2_home_runs_blue_jays_beat_orioles_13_6 |title=Encarnacion hits 2 home runs, Blue Jays beat Orioles 13\u20136 |work=[[Boston Herald]] |date=April 21, 2015 |accessdate=April 22, 2015}}</ref>  He injured his right shoulder during that game, attempting to throw out [[Delmon Young]] at first base. He was held out of the lineup for several days before returning, exclusively as the designated hitter. Bautista received a cortisone shot on May 24 and returned to the outfield on June 2, against the [[2015 Washington Nationals season|Washington Nationals]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/mlb/jose-bautista-eases-back-into-right-field-for-blue-jays-1.3097924 |title=Jose Bautista eases back into right field for Blue Jays|last=Harrison|first=Doug|work=cbc.ca|date=June 2, 2015|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref> On July 6, Bautista was named to his sixth-consecutive [[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] team, as a reserve outfielder in [[Cincinnati]].<ref name=2015mlbasg>{{cite web |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/135055072/full-roster-released-for-2015-all-star-game |title=Youth served on AL, NL ASG rosters |last=Miller |first=Doug |work=MLB.com|date=July 6, 2015|accessdate=July 6, 2015}}</ref> However, on July 11 it was announced that he would sit out the game due to a shoulder injury.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/twins-dozier-replaces-bautista-in-all-star-game/ |title=Bautista to miss All-Star game with sore shoulder |last=Zwelling |first=Arden |work=Sportsnet |date=July 11, 2015 |accessdate=July 11, 2015}}</ref> Bautista tied Vernon Wells for second place on the Blue Jays' all-time home run list on July 21, when he hit his 223rd home run for Toronto in a 7\u20131 win over the [[2015 Oakland Athletics season|Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-use-power-to-force-the-issue-vs-as/|title=Blue Jays use power to \u2018force the issue\u2019 vs. A's|last=Davidi |first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=July 22, 2015|accessdate=July 22, 2015}}</ref> He surpassed Wells on July 24 in a 5\u20132 loss to the [[2015 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/bautista-hits-224th-career-hr-in-blue-jays-loss/ |title=Bautista hits 224th career HR in Blue Jays\u2019 loss |work=Sportsnet |date=July 25, 2015 |accessdate=July 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn September 30, Bautista surpassed the 40 home run mark for the third time in his career, hitting a solo shot in the ninth inning against the Baltimore Orioles to extend the Blue Jays lead to 11\u20131. The Blue Jays would win the game, 15\u20132, and clinch the American League East.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citynews.ca/2015/09/30/blue-jays-clinch-first-al-east-title-in-22-years/|title=Blue Jays clinch first AL East title in 22 years|work=citynews.ca|date=September 30, 2015|accessdate=October 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBautista finished the 2015 regular season with a .250 batting average, 40 home runs, and 114 RBI. He also walked more than he struck out for the second consecutive year, totaling 110 walks to 106 strikeouts. For the season, he had the lowest [[line drive]] percentage of all major league hitters (13.9%).<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2015&month=0&season1=2015&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=5,a Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2015 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Batted Ball Statistics | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> From 2010\u201315, he batted .268 with 153 doubles, 227 home runs, 582 RBI, 574 walks, 576 strikeouts, .390 OBP, .555 SLG, .945 OPS, and 156 OPS+.<ref name=\"BR\"/> In that span, he hit more home runs than any other major leaguer \u2013 28 ahead of second-place [[Miguel Cabrera]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=nomin&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=HR&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015, sorted by greatest home runs |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> \u2013 was second in slugging percentage<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=minpas&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=slugging_perc&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015 (requiring at least 3000 plate appearances), sorted by greatest slugging % |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> and walks,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=nomin&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=BB&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015, sorted by greatest bases on balls |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> third in OPS<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=minpas&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=onbase_plus_slugging&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015 (requiring at least 3000 plate appearances), sorted by greatest adjusted on-base plus slugging |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> and OPS+<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=minpas&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=onbase_plus_slugging_plus&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015 (requiring at least 3000 plate appearances), sorted by greatest adjusted OPS+ |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref> and fifth in OBP.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/play-index/season_finder.cgi?type=b#gotresults&as=result_batter&offset=0&sum=1&min_year_season=2010&max_year_season=2015&min_season=1&max_season=-1&min_age=0&max_age=99&is_rookie=&lg_ID=lgAny&lgAL_team=tmAny&lgNL_team=tmAny&lgFL_team=tmAny&lgAA_team=tmAny&lgPL_team=tmAny&lgUA_team=tmAny&lgNA_team=tmAny&isActive=either&isHOF=either&isAllstar=either&bats=any&throws=any&exactness=anypos&pos_1=1&pos_2=1&pos_3=1&pos_4=1&pos_5=1&pos_6=1&pos_7=1&pos_8=1&pos_9=1&pos_10=1&pos_11=1&games_min_max=min&games_prop=50&games_tot=&qualifiersSeason=nomin&minpasValS=502&mingamesValS=100&qualifiersCareer=minpas&minpasValC=3000&mingamesValC=1000&number_matched=1&orderby=onbase_perc&c1gtlt=eq&c1val=0&c2gtlt=eq&c2val=0&c3gtlt=eq&c3val=0&c4gtlt=eq&c4val=0&c5gtlt=eq&c5val=1.0&location=pob&locationMatch=is&pob=&pod=&pcanada=&pusa=&ajax=1&submitter=1 |title=Batting season finder: Spanning multiple seasons or entire careers, from 2010 to 2015 (requiring at least 3000 plate appearances), sorted by greatest adjusted on-base% |website=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Jos\u00e9 Bautista bat flip, 14 October 2015.jpg|thumb|left|Jos\u00e9 Bautista's [[bat flip]] after hitting a home run in the bottom of the seventh inning of game 5 of the [[2015 American League Division Series]].]] Do not re-add image without reaching a further consensus via talk page. -->\nOn October 8, 2015, with just over 1,400 career games played, Bautista made his postseason debut against the [[2015 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]] in the [[2015 American League Division Series|American League Division Series]] (ALDS).  In the fifth and final game of the series on October 14, Bautista hit a three-run home run off [[Sam Dyson]] that gave the Jays a 6\u20133 lead that they would not relinquish, sending Toronto to the [[2015 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]] (ALCS).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/154508912/jose-bautistas-blue-jays-legacy-is-secured|title=Touch 'em all, Jose: Legacy secured|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=October 14, 2015|accessdate=October 15, 2015}}</ref>  Bautista watched the home run and [[bat flip|flipped his bat]] high into the air before running the bases, a celebratory gesture that was applauded by Jays fans and media outlets,<ref name=\"Joey Bats nickname\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citynews.ca/2015/10/16/trending-torontos-love-affair-with-joey-bats-more-than-skin-deep/|title=Trending: Toronto's love affair with Joey Bats more than skin deep|work=citynews.ca|date=October 16, 2015|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Watch Jos\u00e9 Bautista's famous bat flip in LEGO form |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/jose-bautista-s-bat-flip-in-a-lego-stop-motion-movie |publisher=MLB |accessdate=March 21, 2020}}</ref> while drawing the ire of Rangers players as unsportsmanlike, in the midst of a 53-minute seventh inning laden with controversy.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/playoffs2015/story/_/page/playoffs15_JoeyBatspersona/how-one-bat-flip-made-blue-jays-star-jose-bautista-polarizing-figure |title=Bautista's bat flip made Joey Bats a polarizing name |last=McHenry |first=Britt |publisher=ESPN |date=October 20, 2015 |accessdate=October 23, 2015}}</ref>  A vital symbol of Toronto's first [[Major League Baseball postseason|postseason]] appearance since 1993,<ref>{{cite news |last=Arthur\n|first=Bruce |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2016/01/12/alex-anthopoulos-has-moved-on-and-so-should-we-arthur.html |title=Alex Anthopoulos has moved on, and so should we |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=January 12, 2016 |accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> the bat flip was voted [[Esurance]]'s MLB Award for Best Play on Offense for 2015.<ref name=esurancebestoffense>{{cite web |url=https://securea.mlb.com/mlb/awards/y2015/mlb-awards/ |title=Esurance MLB.com awards: Best play, offense |publisher=MLB.com |date=2015 |accessdate=January 6, 2016}}</ref>  In the five games of the ALDS, Bautista batted .273 with two home runs and five RBI.<ref name=\"BR\"/>\n\nIn Game 3 of the ALCS against the [[2015 Kansas City Royals season|Kansas City Royals]], Bautista had one hit and two walks, joining [[Keith Hernandez]] as the only players in MLB postseason history to reach base three times on their birthday. The Blue Jays would win the game, 11\u20138.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/155007470/blue-jays-royals-alcs-game-3-cool-facts |title=DYK? Joey Bats' b-day feat among G3 rarities |last=Cassavell |first=AJ |work=MLB.com |date=October 20, 2015 |accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref>  In Game 6, Bautista hit two home runs, including a two-run game-tying homer at the top of the eighth inning to tie the game at 3\u20133; however Kansas City would win 4\u20133 to take the [[List of American League pennant winners|pennant]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/bluejays/2015/10/23/world-is-watching-as-blue-jays-head-to-kansas-city-for-game-6-of-alcs.html |title=Fans reeling as Blue Jays eliminated in Game 6 heartbreaker |last=Levinson King |first=Robin |work=thestar.com |date=October 23, 2015 |accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn November 3, 2015, Toronto exercised Bautista's $14 million option for [[2016 Toronto Blue Jays season|2016]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-exercise-options-on-bautista-dickey-encarnacion/ |title=Blue Jays exercise options on Bautista, Dickey, Encarnacion |work=Sportsnet |date=November 3, 2015 |accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2016====\n[[File:Jose Bautista 2016 spring training.jpg|thumb|right|Bautista with Toronto in 2016]]\nDuring his final regular season plate appearance against the [[2016 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]] on May 15, [[2016 Toronto Blue Jays season|2016]], Bautista was hit by a pitch from [[Matt Bush (baseball)|Matt Bush]], which many believed to be retaliation by the Rangers organization for Bautista's [[Bat flip#Jos\u00e9 Bautista bat flip|bat flip]] in the 2015 ALDS. Two batters later, Bautista, intending to break-up a double play, made a hard, but no longer legal (as of that season), slide into second basemen [[Rougned Odor]]. Although the slide didn't make any contact, Odor pushed Bautista, who shoved back, followed by Odor punching Bautista in the jaw. This ignited a [[bench-clearing brawl]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chisholm |first1=Gregor |title=Tension boils over in Blue Jays-Rangers game |url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/178354174/bautista-odor-fight-in-blue-jays-rangers-game |publisher=MLB |date=May 15, 2016 |accessdate=May 15, 2016}}</ref> Bautista was handed a one-game suspension by the league for his part in the melee, which he appealed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/178630394/rougned-odor-jose-bautista-suspended|title=Odor, Bautista among 14 disciplined for brawl|last=Hagen|first=Paul|work=MLB.com|date=May 18, 2016|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> On May 27, MLB announced that they had upheld the suspension.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/jose-bautistas-suspension-upheld-will-miss-opener-vs-red-sox/|title=Jose Bautista\u2019s suspension upheld, will miss opener vs. Red Sox|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=May 27, 2016}}</ref> During the day of his suspension, Bautista served as the public address announcer at Rogers Centre.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Perry|first1=Dayn|title=Jose Bautista does some P.A. announcing while on suspension|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/watch-jose-bautista-does-some-p-a-announcing-while-on-suspension/|publisher=CBS Sports|accessdate=May 28, 2016}}</ref> On June 17, 2016, he was placed on the 15-day disabled list due to an injury to his left big toe.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jose Bautista placed on disabled list after collision with outfield wall|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/16289117/toronto-blue-jays-jose-bautista-placed-15-day-dl-outfield-collision|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref> He returned from the disabled list near the end of July. On August 2, Bautista hit his 300th career home run, a solo shot off [[Houston Astros]] starter [[Lance McCullers Jr.]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/193244784/jose-bautista-the-newest-member-of-300-hr-club/|title=Bautista the newest member of 300-HR club|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=August 2, 2016|accessdate=August 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn November 7, the Blue Jays extended a $17.2 million qualifying offer to Bautista,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-extend-qualifying-offers-encarnacion-bautista/|title=Blue Jays extend qualifying offers to Encarnacion, Bautista|last=Davidi|first=Shi|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=November 7, 2016|accessdate=November 7, 2016}}</ref> which he declined on November 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/208848218/edwin-encarnacion-jose-bautista-free-agents/|title=Encarnacion, Bautista reject qualifying offers|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=November 14, 2016|accessdate=November 14, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2017====\n[[File:Jose Bautista - 2017 (36556471990) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Bautista making a sliding catch at [[Oriole Park at Camden Yards]]]]\nOn January 18, 2017, Bautista signed a one-year, $18 million contract with the Blue Jays. The contract included a $17 million mutual option for the 2018 season, as well as a $20 million vesting option for 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/213596024/jose-bautista-signs-1-year-deal-with-blue-jays/|title=Bautista returns to Blue Jays on 1-year deal|last1=Chisholm|first1=Gregor|last2=Sanchez|first2=Jesse|work=MLB.com|date=January 18, 2017|accessdate=January 18, 2017}}</ref> On August 11, Bautista reached the 20 home run mark for the eighth consecutive season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/247818944/bucs-jameson-taillon-outduels-marcus-stroman/|title=Stroman goes 8, but errors undo Blue Jays|last1=Berry|first1=Adam|last2=Matheson|first2=Keegan|work=MLB.com|date=August 11, 2017|accessdate=August 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBautista ended the year batting .203 with 23 home runs and 65 RBIs. His .203 batting average was the lowest of all qualified major league batters.<ref>[https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=8&season=2017&month=0&season1=2017&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=13,a Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2017 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Dashboard | FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>  The Blue Jays declined Bautista's option for 2018 on November 4, 2017 marking the end of his career as a Blue Jay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-formally-decline-jose-bautistas-17-million-mutual-option/ |title=Blue Jays formally decline Jose Bautista\u2019s $17-million mutual option |first=Mike |last=Johnston |work=sportsnet.ca |date=November 4, 2017 |accessdate=November 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n====Atlanta Braves====\nOn April&nbsp;18 2018, Bautista signed a minor league contract with the [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jose Bautista signs minor-league deal with Atlanta Braves|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/baseball/2018/04/18/jose-bautista-signs-minor-league-deal-with-atlanta-braves.html|accessdate=April 18, 2018|date=April 18, 2018 |first=Laura |last=Armstrong}}</ref> After playing a few games for the [[Gwinnett Stripers]], the Braves promoted Bautista to start at third base for the first of a three-game series against the San Francisco Giants on May&nbsp;4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/baseball/bautista-play-third-bat-first-for-gwinnett-open-doubleheader/JMj5OZJUrKBuzG5KebFmGO/|title=Starting third base job awaits promoted Bautista}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/jose-bautista-coming-up-to-join-braves/c-275200970|title=Jose Bautista coming up to join Braves|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 4, 2018|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref> On May&nbsp;12, 2018, Bautista hit his first home run with the Braves.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Mark|title=Joey Bats redeems error with first Braves HR|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/jose-bautista-hits-his-first-braves-homer/c-276477720|accessdate=May 20, 2018|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 13, 2018}}</ref> Bautista batted .143 with two home runs and five RBIs in 35 at bats over 12 games played before being released by the Braves on May&nbsp;20.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowman|first1=Mark|url=https://www.mlb.com/braves/news/braves-release-third-baseman-jose-bautista/c-277528920|title=Braves release scuffling Bautista|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 20, 2018|accessdate=May 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====New York Mets====\nOn May 22, 2018, Bautista signed a one-year deal with the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/05/22/mets-closing-in-on-deal-with-jose-bautista|title=Mets agree to deal with Jose Bautista|work=New York Post|accessdate=May 22, 2018|date=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Bautista hit a double in his first at bat with the Mets. He later scored on a sacrifice fly. On June 22, 2018 Bautista hit his first home run as a member of the Mets against the Dodgers making it his 3rd of the season (his previous two being with the Braves). On July 6, Bautista hit a [[Walk-off home run|walk off grand slam]] against the Rays, which was the first walk off home run of his career.<ref>[https://www.mlb.com/mets/gameday/rays-vs-mets/2018/07/06/530729#game_state=,game_tab=,game=530729 Rays vs. Mets | 07/06/18 | New York Mets<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2018 he batted .204 with the Mets with a .351 OBP.\n\n====Philadelphia Phillies====\nThe Mets traded Bautista to the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] for a player to be named later or cash on August 28, 2018.<ref>[https://twitter.com/MLBRosterMoves/status/1034495695078744064?s=19 MLBRosterMoves on Twitter: \".@Phillies acquire INF/OF Jos\u00e9 Bautista from @Mets for PTBN or cash. #MLBOnTheMove\u2026 \"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He batted .244 for the Phillies with a .404 OBP and .870 OPS. He was the 9th-oldest player in the National League.<ref>[https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/2018-other-leaders.shtml 2018 National League Awards, All-Stars, & More Leaders | Baseball-Reference.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He elected free agency on October 29.\n\nIn November 2019, Bautista expressed desire to continue his career after taking the 2019 season off. In March 2020, announced he was hoping to return as a two-way player.\n\n==Awards and accomplishments==\n===Awards===\n* 5\u00d7 [[American League]] [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month Award|Player of the Month]] (Jul. 2010, Aug. 2010, Apr. 2011, May 2011, Jun. 2012)<ref name=aug2010pom/>\n* 4\u00d7 American League [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|Player of the Week]] (May 16, 2010; August 1, 2010; August 29, 2010; July 3, 2011)\n* [[Esurance]]'s MLB Award for Best Play, Offense (2015)<ref name=esurancebestoffense/>\n* 2\u00d7 [[Hank Aaron Award]] (2010, 2011)\n* [[John Cerutti]] Award (2010)<ref name=\"sports.nationalpost.com\"/>\n* 6\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|Major League Baseball All-Star]] ([[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2010]]\u2013[[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|15]])<ref name=2010mlbasg/><ref name=2011mlbasg/><ref name=\"Ballot record\"/><ref name=2013mlbasg/><ref name=2014mlbasg/><ref name=2015mlbasg/>\n* 2\u00d7 [[Neil MacCarl Award]] (2010, 2011)<ref name=\"sports.nationalpost.com\"/>\n* 3\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] at [[List of Silver Slugger Award winners at outfield|outfield]] (2010, 2011, 2014)\n* Toronto Blue Jays Most Improved Player (2010)<ref name=\"sports.nationalpost.com\"/>\n\n===Accomplishments===\n* 2\u00d7 American League [[bases on balls]] leader (2011, 2015)\n* 2\u00d7 Major League Baseball [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders|home run leader]] (2010, 2011)\n* Major League Baseball [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage leader (2011)\n* Major League Baseball [[slugging percentage]] leader (2011)\n* Toronto Blue Jays top-ten in career [[on-base percentage]], [[slugging percentage]], [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage, [[Run (baseball)|runs]] scored, [[total bases]], [[home run]]s, [[runs batted in]], [[bases on balls]] and adjusted on-base plus slugging percentage (through 2015)<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders/>\n\n===Records===\n* Major League Baseball record for largest single-season home run increase (39 from 2009 to 2010)<ref name=hrincrease/>\n* Toronto Blue Jays single-season most bases on balls (132 in 2011)<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders/>\n* Toronto Blue Jays single-season most home runs (54 in 2010)<ref name=tbjhrrecord/>\n* Toronto Blue Jays single-season most offensive WAR (8.3 in 2011)<ref name=tbjfranchiseleaders/>\n\n==Personal life==\nBautista's nickname is \"Joey Bats\".<ref name=\"Joey Bats nickname\"/> A species of weevil, ''[[Sicoderus bautistai]]'', was named for Bautista in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Canadian scientist names beetle after Jose Bautista |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/canadian-scientist-names-beetle-after-jose-bautista/2018/11/22/1bf405ec-eea2-11e8-8b47-bd0975fd6199_story.html |accessdate=November 23, 2018 |work=Washington Post |agency=Associated Press |date=November 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBautista and his then-girlfriend, Neisha Croyle had their first daughter together, Estela, born April 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/story/?id=360936 |title=Bautista expected to miss A's series due to personal matter |publisher=Tsn.ca |date= |accessdate=September 28, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/magazine/sportsnet-magazine-stephen-brunt-jose-bautista-feature/|title=SN Magazine: Brunt at home with Bautista|last=Brunt|first=Stephen|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=April 5, 2012|accessdate=December 10, 2015}}</ref> His second daughter, Ava, was born in November 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torontolife.com/informer/features/2013/06/20/jose-bautista-back-in-the-game/|title=Back in the Game: Blue Jays slugger Jos\u00e9 Bautista's high-stakes mission to stay on top|last=Cole|first=Trevor|work=torontolife.com|date=June 20, 2013|accessdate=March 26, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140530005227/http://www.torontolife.com/informer/features/2013/06/20/jose-bautista-back-in-the-game/|archive-date=May 30, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In 2011 Bautista set up a program to aid athletes to have the same opportunity he had to attend American universities. Initially focused on the Dominican Republic, it has expanded to Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bautistafund.org/about|title=Bautista Family Education Fund|work=bautistafund.org|accessdate=November 17, 2015}}</ref> Bautista and his girlfriend Neisha Croyle were married November 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunter|first1=Ian|title=Here\u2019s what we know about Jose Bautista\u2019s wedding|url=https://torontolife.com/city/toronto-sports/heres-know-jose-bautistas-wedding/|accessdate=May 21, 2018|work=Toronto Life|date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBautista's younger brother, Luis played college baseball at [[Florida International University]]. He was drafted by the [[Chicago Cubs]] in the 32nd round of the [[2007 Major League Baseball draft]] and played in their minor league system through 2008.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Dominican Republic|Baseball}}\n{{div col}}\n* [[50 home run club]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career putouts as a right fielder leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players from the Dominican Republic]]\n* [[List of Toronto Blue Jays home run leaders]]\n* [[List of Toronto Blue Jays team records]]\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays award winners and league leaders]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Jos\u00e9 Bautista}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=430832|espn=5890|br=b/bautijo02|fangraphs=1887|brm=bautis001jos|retro=B/Pbautj001}}\n*[https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/c9f08cf8 Jos\u00e9 Bautista] at SABR (Baseball BioProject)\n*[https://www.ultimatemets.com/profile.php?PlayerCode=1054 Jos\u00e9 Bautista] at Ultimate Mets Database\n* {{twitter|name=Jose Bautista}}\n* {{instagram|JoeyBats19|Jose Bautista}}\n*{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/opinion/commentary/2016/12/28/the-flip-side-to-jos-bautista.html|title=The flip side to Jose Bautista|last=Dodds|first=James|newspaper=[[Toronto Star]]|date=28 December 2016|accessdate=28 December 2016}}\n\n{{AL home run champions}}\n{{AL Hank Aaron Award Winners}}\n{{AL OF Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{50 home run club|state=collapsed}}\n{{Dominican Republic roster 2009 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Dominican Republic roster 2017 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bautista, Jose}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2009 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:2017 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:Altoona Curve players]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League home run champions]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Braves players]]\n[[Category:Baltimore Orioles players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Chipola Indians baseball players]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic expatriate baseball players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Dunedin Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Florida Fire Frogs players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Pirates players]]\n[[Category:Gwinnett Stripers players]]\n[[Category:Hickory Crawdads players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Indians players]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Royals players]]\n[[Category:Lynchburg Hillcats players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball players from the Dominican Republic]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball right fielders]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball third basemen]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Fisher Cats players]]\n[[Category:New York Mets players]]\n[[Category:Philadelphia Phillies players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Pirates players]]\n[[Category:PUCMM alumni]]\n[[Category:Silver Slugger Award winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:Tampa Bay Devil Rays players]]\n[[Category:Tigres del Licey players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:Williamsport Crosscutters players]]\n", "name_user": "64.150.207.80", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_Bautista"}
{"title_page": "Shaw Academy", "text_new": "{{short description|Online education organisation in Dublin, Ireland}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{advert|date=January 2019}}\n{{COI|date=August 2019}}\n{{POV|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Shaw Academy\n| logo = ShawAcademylogo.png\n| type = [[E-learning|Online learning]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| founder = {{ubl|James Egan|Adrian Murphy}}\n| employees = 66 (2019)\n| url = {{url|shawacademy.com}}\n| launch_date = 2013\n}}\n\n'''Shaw Academy''' is a privately owned [[online education]] organisation based in [[Dublin]], Ireland.<ref name=\"financialtimes\">{{cite web | url = https://www.ft.com/content/1f3b2402-cb3b-11e5-a8ef-ea66e967dd44 | title = Edtech providers move from Moocs to social networking | last = Moules | first = Jonathan | date = 7 March 2016 | publisher = [[Financial Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite web | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonha-revesencio/a-look-at-coursera-the-sh_b_7095034.html | title = A Look at Coursera, The Shaw Academy and Lynda.com: Which One Stands Out? | last = Revesencio | first = Jonha | date = 19 June 2015 | website = [[The Huffington Post]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150422001007/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonha-revesencio/a-look-at-coursera-the-sh_b_7095034.html | archivedate = 22 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFounded in 2013, Shaw Academy provides online courses which are audio/video recorded and deliver them to students through scheduled webinar times decided by the student to suit their \"own pace\".<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/> The courses offered cover subjects including photography, health and fitness, financial trading, nutrition, beauty, leadership, web development, mobile app development, graphic design, digital marketing and social media marketing.<ref name=\"irishtimesedu\">{{cite web | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/we-don-t-need-no-free-market-education-1.2539969 | title = We don\u2019t need no free-market education | last = O'Brien | first = Stephen | date = 23 February 2016 | website = [[The Irish Times]] }}</ref><ref name=\"europapress\">{{cite web | url = http://www.europapress.es/campusvivo/cursos-masteres/noticia-shaw-academy-lanza-cursos-gratis-marketing-financial-trading-fotografia-nutricion-20150904135152.html | title = ACCESS THROUGH LIVE CAMPUS | access-date = 22 September 2015 | publisher = [[Europa Press (news agency)|Europa Press]]}}</ref> Shaw Academy uses online tools to answer students' live questions.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\" />\n\n==History==\nShaw Academy was founded by James Egan and Adrian Murphy in 2013.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\">{{cite web | url = https://www.siliconrepublic.com/careers/2016/01/29/40-jobs-dublin-shaw-academy | title = 40 jobs in Dublin at online learning company Shaw Academy | last = Hunt | first = Gordon | date = 29 January 2016 | website = Silicon Republic }}</ref>\n\nBy January 2016, Shaw Academy was teaching about 55,000 new students each month.<ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\">{{cite web | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/shaw-academy-to-create-40-jobs-in-dublin-1.2515720 | title = Shaw Academy to create 40 jobs in Dublin | last = O'Brien | first = Ciara | date = 29 January 2016 | website = [[The Irish Times]] }}</ref> By November of that year, it was teaching 400,000 new students every month and had surpassed teaching over 1.84 million students.<ref name = \"businessworld\">{{cite web | url = http://bwdisrupt.businessworld.in/article/Flipkart-and-Shaw-Academy-Bring-Live-Education-to-the-Indian-Online-Marketplace/21-11-2016-108568/ | title = Flipkart and Shaw Academy Bring Live Education to the Indian Online Marketplace | date = 21 November 2016 | website = [[Businessworld]] }}</ref><ref name = \"inc42\">{{cite web | url = https://inc42.com/flash-feed/flipkart-forays-online-learning/ | title = Flipkart Forays Into Online Learning; Partners With Shaw Academy | last = Agarwal | first = Meha | date = 18 November 2016 | website = Inc42 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, founder Adrian Murphy and Irish Minister for Jobs, Richard Bruton, announced 40 new education positions in the Dublin office.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\" /><ref name = \"enterpriseireland\">{{cite web | url = http://newsletter.enterprise-ireland.com/1xnwjm1a27g?a=1&p=49805714&t=28830144 | title = 40 jobs in Dublin at online learning company Shaw Academy | website = [[Enterprise Ireland]] | access-date = 4 February 2016 }}</ref> The CEO of Irish government agency [[Enterprise Ireland]], Julie Sinnamon, described Shaw Academy at the time as \"an example of an innovative Irish company in the growing online learning market, who are also supporting other Irish SMEs to grow through their extensive suite of online courses.\"<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"enterpriseireland\" />\n\nIn January 2017, Shaw Academy launched an educational platform, called Phoenix, to accommodate growing student numbers. Phoenix is marketed as a tool to enable Shaw Academy to teach more students live online simultaneously whilst also providing an automated yet personalised service to its students.<ref name = \"insightssuccess\">{{cite web | url = http://www.insightssuccess.com/shaw-academy-launches-a-new-education-technology-platform/ | title = Shaw Academy launches a new Education Technology Platform | website = insightssuccess.com | access-date = 31 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, despite having sold courses to 4.5m students and a revenue the previous year of \u20ac7.2m, the organisation ran into financial difficulties with the calling in of a \u20ac5.7m debt resulting in the High Court appointing an insolvency practitioner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/harsh-lesson-for-dublin-online-education-firm-shaw-academy-as-it-falls-from-top-of-class-kbz5wx0tv|title=Harsh lesson for Dublin online education firm Shaw Academy as it falls from top of class|first=Philip|last=Connolly|via=www.thetimes.co.uk|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/examiner-picks-six-bidders-for-shaw-academy-37800012.html|title=Examiner picks six bidders for Shaw Academy|website=independent}}</ref>  In March, the court approved the exit of Shaw Academy from [[examinership]] after the company secured an additional \u20ac7.15 million in funding.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/shaw-academy-to-exit-examinership-with-7m-investment-1.3844655|title=Shaw Academy to exit examinership with \u20ac7m investment|last=Hamilton|first=Peter|date=2019-04-01|website=The Irish Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Courses ==\nShaw Academy offers courses ranging from business related topics such as digital marketing, social media marketing and web development to wellness programmes such as health and fitness and sports nutrition.<ref name = \"inc42\" /> Courses are delivered with recordings of live presentations.<ref name = \"inc42\" /><ref name = \"indiainfoline\" /> Students can log on to an online portal to complete assignments, exams, review modules, replay lectures, and view additional content. Educational and technical support teams are also available to students.<ref name = \"huffingtonpost\" /><ref name = \"inc\">{{cite web | url = http://www.inc.com/aj-agrawal/5-reasons-why-online-learning-is-the-future-of-education.html | title = 5 Benefits That Make Online Learning With Shaw Academy the Future of Education | last = Agrawal | first = AJ | publisher = [[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.com]] | access-date = 30 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Accreditation ==\nThe professional diploma courses of Shaw Academy were accredited with 10 credit units by the [[Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework]] (SCQF) through validation of [[Edinburgh Napier University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scqf.org.uk/the-framework/search-database/|title=Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework|date=2019-01-16|website=www.scqf.org.uk |access-date=2019-01-16}}</ref> They are on the [[European Qualifications Framework]], a reference network for the comparability of national educational standards,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.accreditedqualifications.org.uk/european-qualifications-framework-eqf.html|title=European Qualifications Framework (EQF)|website=www.accreditedqualifications.org.uk|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref> and therefore, amongst others, comparable to 10 credit units achieved through [[Higher National Diploma]], [[foundation degree]], [[Diploma of Higher Education]] or an [[Associate degree|associate degree]] in the US.{{fact|date=February 2020}}\n\nBecause Edinburgh Napier University is not partnering with Shaw Academy as a credit rating body since 24 July 2019, SCQF has archived the records in their database. Certificates awarded before 24 July 2019 will still be valid. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scqf.org.uk/faqs/|title=Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework|date=2020-04-03|website=www.scqf.org.uk |access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> After this time, Shaw Academy provides the certificates without an accompanying credit rating body. Despite continuing to use the claims of recognition by the European Qualification Framework this recognition and credit rating is not found in the European Union official website under Learning Opportunities and Qualifications section. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/ploteus/en/search/site/Shaw%20Academy?autocomplete_keywords=Shaw%20Academy|title=Learning Opportunities and Qualifications in Europe|date=2020-04-03|website=ec.europa.eu |access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Partners==\nShaw Academy has reportedly formed partnerships with companies in e-commerce, telecom and recruitment sector such as [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[GoDaddy]] and [[Naukri.com]].<ref name = \"businessworld\" /><ref name=\"yahoofinancedec16\">{{cite web | url = http://finance.yahoo.com/news/shaw-academy-reaches-another-milestone-130000045.html | title = Shaw Academy Reaches Another Milestone | date = 9 December 2016 | website = [[Yahoo! Finance]] }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Shaw Academy partnered with Indian e-commerce marketplace [[Flipkart]] to provide certified courses on its portal.<ref name = \"businessworld\" /><ref name = \"industryandbusiness\">{{cite web | url = http://www.industryandbusiness.ie/india-trade-mission-sees-partnerships-signed/ | title = India Trade Mission Sees Partnerships Signed | date = 22 November 2016 | website = Industry and Business }}</ref>\n\n== Office locations ==\nThe company's headquarters are in Dublin, Ireland, and it has other offices elsewhere, employing approximately 200 staff globally in 2016.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\" /> In September 2015, Shaw Academy set up an office in [[Bangalore]], India, which employed over 120 staff.<ref name=\"indiainfoline\">{{cite web | url = http://www.indiainfoline.com/article/b-school-news/flipkart-partners-with-shaw-academy-to-bring-live-education-to-indian-online-marketplace-116111800328_1.html | title = Flipkart partners with Shaw Academy to bring live education to Indian online marketplace | date = 18 November 2016 | website = [[India Infoline]] }}</ref> In April 2019, Shaw Academy had 66 employees, distributed across Dublin, Bangalore and Cape Town.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official Website|http://www.shawacademy.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Irish educational websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Online education organisation in Dublin, Ireland}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{advert|date=January 2019}}\n{{COI|date=August 2019}}\n{{POV|date=February 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = Shaw Academy\n| logo = ShawAcademylogo.png\n| type = [[E-learning|Online learning]]\n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| founder = {{ubl|James Egan|Adrian Murphy}}\n| employees = 66 (2019)\n| url = {{url|shawacademy.com}}\n| launch_date = 2013\n}}\n\n'''Shaw Academy''' is a privately owned [[online education]] organisation based in [[Dublin]], Ireland.<ref name=\"financialtimes\">{{cite web | url = https://www.ft.com/content/1f3b2402-cb3b-11e5-a8ef-ea66e967dd44 | title = Edtech providers move from Moocs to social networking | last = Moules | first = Jonathan | date = 7 March 2016 | publisher = [[Financial Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite web | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonha-revesencio/a-look-at-coursera-the-sh_b_7095034.html | title = A Look at Coursera, The Shaw Academy and Lynda.com: Which One Stands Out? | last = Revesencio | first = Jonha | date = 19 June 2015 | website = [[The Huffington Post]] |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150422001007/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonha-revesencio/a-look-at-coursera-the-sh_b_7095034.html | archivedate = 22 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFounded in 2013, Shaw Academy provides online courses which are audio/video recorded and deliver them to students through scheduled webinar times decided by the student to suit their \"own pace\".<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/> The courses offered cover subjects including photography, health and fitness, financial trading, nutrition, web development, mobile app development and digital marketing.<ref name=\"irishtimesedu\">{{cite web | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/we-don-t-need-no-free-market-education-1.2539969 | title = We don\u2019t need no free-market education | last = O'Brien | first = Stephen | date = 23 February 2016 | website = [[The Irish Times]] }}</ref><ref name=\"europapress\">{{cite web | url = http://www.europapress.es/campusvivo/cursos-masteres/noticia-shaw-academy-lanza-cursos-gratis-marketing-financial-trading-fotografia-nutricion-20150904135152.html | title = ACCESS THROUGH LIVE CAMPUS | access-date = 22 September 2015 | publisher = [[Europa Press (news agency)|Europa Press]]}}</ref> Shaw Academy uses online tools to answer students' live questions.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\" />\n\n==History==\nShaw Academy was founded by James Egan and Adrian Murphy in 2013.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\">{{cite web | url = https://www.siliconrepublic.com/careers/2016/01/29/40-jobs-dublin-shaw-academy | title = 40 jobs in Dublin at online learning company Shaw Academy | last = Hunt | first = Gordon | date = 29 January 2016 | website = Silicon Republic }}</ref>\n\nBy January 2016, Shaw Academy was teaching about 55,000 new students each month.<ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\">{{cite web | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/shaw-academy-to-create-40-jobs-in-dublin-1.2515720 | title = Shaw Academy to create 40 jobs in Dublin | last = O'Brien | first = Ciara | date = 29 January 2016 | website = [[The Irish Times]] }}</ref> By November of that year, it was teaching 400,000 new students every month and had surpassed teaching over 1.84 million students.<ref name = \"businessworld\">{{cite web | url = http://bwdisrupt.businessworld.in/article/Flipkart-and-Shaw-Academy-Bring-Live-Education-to-the-Indian-Online-Marketplace/21-11-2016-108568/ | title = Flipkart and Shaw Academy Bring Live Education to the Indian Online Marketplace | date = 21 November 2016 | website = [[Businessworld]] }}</ref><ref name = \"inc42\">{{cite web | url = https://inc42.com/flash-feed/flipkart-forays-online-learning/ | title = Flipkart Forays Into Online Learning; Partners With Shaw Academy | last = Agarwal | first = Meha | date = 18 November 2016 | website = Inc42 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, founder Adrian Murphy and Irish Minister for Jobs, Richard Bruton, announced 40 new education positions in the Dublin office.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\" /><ref name = \"enterpriseireland\">{{cite web | url = http://newsletter.enterprise-ireland.com/1xnwjm1a27g?a=1&p=49805714&t=28830144 | title = 40 jobs in Dublin at online learning company Shaw Academy | website = [[Enterprise Ireland]] | access-date = 4 February 2016 }}</ref> The CEO of Irish government agency [[Enterprise Ireland]], Julie Sinnamon, described Shaw Academy at the time as \"an example of an innovative Irish company in the growing online learning market, who are also supporting other Irish SMEs to grow through their extensive suite of online courses.\"<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"enterpriseireland\" />\n\nIn January 2017, Shaw Academy launched an educational platform, called Phoenix, to accommodate growing student numbers. Phoenix is marketed as a tool to enable Shaw Academy to teach more students live online simultaneously whilst also providing an automated yet personalised service to its students.<ref name = \"insightssuccess\">{{cite web | url = http://www.insightssuccess.com/shaw-academy-launches-a-new-education-technology-platform/ | title = Shaw Academy launches a new Education Technology Platform | website = insightssuccess.com | access-date = 31 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, despite having sold courses to 4.5m students and a revenue the previous year of \u20ac7.2m, the organisation ran into financial difficulties with the calling in of a \u20ac5.7m debt resulting in the High Court appointing an insolvency practitioner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/harsh-lesson-for-dublin-online-education-firm-shaw-academy-as-it-falls-from-top-of-class-kbz5wx0tv|title=Harsh lesson for Dublin online education firm Shaw Academy as it falls from top of class|first=Philip|last=Connolly|via=www.thetimes.co.uk|url-status=live|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/examiner-picks-six-bidders-for-shaw-academy-37800012.html|title=Examiner picks six bidders for Shaw Academy|website=independent}}</ref>  In March, the court approved the exit of Shaw Academy from [[examinership]] after the company secured an additional \u20ac7.15 million in funding.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/shaw-academy-to-exit-examinership-with-7m-investment-1.3844655|title=Shaw Academy to exit examinership with \u20ac7m investment|last=Hamilton|first=Peter|date=2019-04-01|website=The Irish Times|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Courses ==\nShaw Academy offers courses ranging from business related topics such as digital marketing, social media marketing and web development to wellness programmes such as health and fitness and sports nutrition.<ref name = \"inc42\" /> Courses are delivered with recordings of live presentations.<ref name = \"inc42\" /><ref name = \"indiainfoline\" /> Students can log on to an online portal to complete assignments, exams, review modules, replay lectures, and view additional content. Educational and technical support teams are also available to students.<ref name = \"huffingtonpost\" /><ref name = \"inc\">{{cite web | url = http://www.inc.com/aj-agrawal/5-reasons-why-online-learning-is-the-future-of-education.html | title = 5 Benefits That Make Online Learning With Shaw Academy the Future of Education | last = Agrawal | first = AJ | publisher = [[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.com]] | access-date = 30 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Accreditation ==\nThe professional diploma courses of Shaw Academy were accredited with 10 credit units by the [[Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework]] (SCQF) through validation of [[Edinburgh Napier University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scqf.org.uk/the-framework/search-database/|title=Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework|date=2019-01-16|website=www.scqf.org.uk |access-date=2019-01-16}}</ref> They are on the [[European Qualifications Framework]], a reference network for the comparability of national educational standards,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.accreditedqualifications.org.uk/european-qualifications-framework-eqf.html|title=European Qualifications Framework (EQF)|website=www.accreditedqualifications.org.uk|access-date=2019-01-11}}</ref> and therefore, amongst others, comparable to 10 credit units achieved through [[Higher National Diploma]], [[foundation degree]], [[Diploma of Higher Education]] or an [[Associate degree|associate degree]] in the US.{{fact|date=February 2020}}\n\nBecause Edinburgh Napier University is not partnering with Shaw Academy as a credit rating body since 24 July 2019, SCQF has archived the records in their database. Certificates awarded before 24 July 2019 will still be valid. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scqf.org.uk/faqs/|title=Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework|date=2020-04-03|website=www.scqf.org.uk |access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> After this time, Shaw Academy provides the certificates without an accompanying credit rating body. Despite continuing to use the claims of recognition by the European Qualification Framework this recognition and credit rating is not found in the European Union official website under Learning Opportunities and Qualifications section. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/ploteus/en/search/site/Shaw%20Academy?autocomplete_keywords=Shaw%20Academy|title=Learning Opportunities and Qualifications in Europe|date=2020-04-03|website=ec.europa.eu |access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Partners==\nShaw Academy has reportedly formed partnerships with companies in e-commerce, telecom and recruitment sector such as [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[GoDaddy]] and [[Naukri.com]].<ref name = \"businessworld\" /><ref name=\"yahoofinancedec16\">{{cite web | url = http://finance.yahoo.com/news/shaw-academy-reaches-another-milestone-130000045.html | title = Shaw Academy Reaches Another Milestone | date = 9 December 2016 | website = [[Yahoo! Finance]] }}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, Shaw Academy partnered with Indian e-commerce marketplace [[Flipkart]] to provide certified courses on its portal.<ref name = \"businessworld\" /><ref name = \"industryandbusiness\">{{cite web | url = http://www.industryandbusiness.ie/india-trade-mission-sees-partnerships-signed/ | title = India Trade Mission Sees Partnerships Signed | date = 22 November 2016 | website = Industry and Business }}</ref>\n\n== Office locations ==\nThe company's headquarters are in Dublin, Ireland, and it has other offices elsewhere, employing approximately 200 staff globally in 2016.<ref name = \"siliconrepublic\" /><ref name = \"irishtimesjobs\" /> In September 2015, Shaw Academy set up an office in [[Bangalore]], India, which employed over 120 staff.<ref name=\"indiainfoline\">{{cite web | url = http://www.indiainfoline.com/article/b-school-news/flipkart-partners-with-shaw-academy-to-bring-live-education-to-indian-online-marketplace-116111800328_1.html | title = Flipkart partners with Shaw Academy to bring live education to Indian online marketplace | date = 18 November 2016 | website = [[India Infoline]] }}</ref> In April 2019, Shaw Academy had 66 employees, distributed across Dublin, Bangalore and Cape Town.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official Website|http://www.shawacademy.com/}}\n\n[[Category:Irish educational websites]]\n", "name_user": "Afventer", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added courses", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaw_Academy"}
{"title_page": "HC Bosna Visoko", "text_new": "{{Infobox handball club\n| clubname    = '''HC Bosna Visoko'''\n| image       = \n| fullname    = Handball club Bosna\n| short name  = \n| founded     = 1954\n| ground      = Sport Centre Mladost\n| capacity    = \n| chairman    = Adnan Deli\u0107\n| manager     = Senad Skopljak \n| league      = \n| season      = \n| position    = \n| website     = http://www.rkbosna.ba \n| colour1     = green\n| colour2     = white\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1  = _unknown\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_sh1 = \n| leftarm1    = \n| body1       = \n| rightarm1   = \n| shorts1     = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| leftarm2    = \n| body2       = \n| rightarm2   = \n| shorts2     = \n}}\n\n'''RK Bosna Visoko''' (''[[Bosnian language|Bosnian]]: Rukometni klub Bosna'') is a [[team handball|handball]] club from [[Visoko, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Visoko]], founded on 9 February 1954. RK Bosna competes in the [[Handball Championship of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and the [[Handball Cup of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].\n\n== History ==\n<!-- Commented out because image was deleted: [[Image:Igrali\u0161te.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Old asphalted playing-field of RK Bosna]] -->\nAfter Ferid Semi\u0107 brought the first [[Team handball|handball]] ball to [[Visoko, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Visoko]], and when the congress was held on 9 February 1954, sport society Mladost was born. Its founders were Ferid Semi\u0107 and Vladimir Joli\u0107. The first game was held on 9 May 1954 when Visoko was beaten by [[Sarajevo]] by 25:9.\n\n===Handball club Bosna established===\nOn 15 March 1960 club's name Mladost was renamed to Handball Club Bosna. From the autumn of 1962 all games were held at city's asphalted handball playing-field. The most important moment for Visoko's handball team was the arrival of Sr\u0111an Praljak: the first real handball coach, who from 1 August 1960 to 31 July 1971 created the characteristic Visoko handball school. This was second generation of players with Nevzad Sir\u0107o at the helm, who was one of the best players in the history of Visoko's handball.\n\n===First Yugoslav league===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Nevzad Sirco.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Nevzad Sir\u0107o, one of the best players ever from Visoko]] -->\nAfter only four years, Bosna entered the strong First league of [[Yugoslavia]] in 1964, and at same time won the Cup of Bosnia and Herzegovina, and runner-up in Cup of Yugoslavia. On 20 May 1970, club was renamed to RK Vitex, after economic giant Vitex, and continued with that name until 1991. The club remained in the First handball league of Yugoslavia for seven years until it was relegated to second in 1971/72 season. This wasn't for long, and after only one year, the club re-entered the first league and achieved its best place ever: fourth in 1974/75 season in one of the best handball leagues of that time. It stayed for two more seasons when Bosna was relegated in 1976 to Second Yugoslav league, which was last season for club in first league. Altogether, Bosna have played 10 seasons in elite Yugoslav handball league, having won 3 times Cup of Bosnia and Herzegovina. Pioneer selection became champions of Yugoslavia in 1971. Juniors were two times runners-up, in 1973 and 1974. Zdenko Antovi\u0107 became standard player for Yugoslavian national handball team in 1976, 1977 and 1979, other players like Kemal Vra\u017ei\u0107 and Ranko Antovi\u0107 didn't stay for long.\n\n===Decline===\nAt around this time, the game of handball began to be played in halls, and asphalted playing-fields started to be abandoned. Visoko didn't have a hall so it was forced to play in other towns like [[Sarajevo]], [[Vogo\u0161\u0107a]], [[Zavidovi\u0107i]] and [[Had\u017ei\u0107i]]. After only three seasons Bosna was relegated again to the second league in 1975/76 season. From then until 1991, the club couldn't get back into first league. The most significant result was winning the cup of [[SR BiH]] in 1981. Finally, Visoko got its first handball hall, sports centre Mladost, which was finished on 9 April 1986.\n\n===War and recovery===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:RkBosna.jpg|thumb|200px|Handball derby in Visoko between home team Bosna, and Sarajevo]] -->\nAfter the devastating [[Bosnian War]], the hall and clubs offices were damaged, but Bosna started to recover. From 1995 Bosna twice won the First league of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (seasons 1996/97 and 1998/99) and record three times Cup of BiH (1995, 1998 and in 2001). Bosna had involvement in [[European Handball Federation|EHF]] competitions such as [[EHF Cup]] and [[EHF Cup Winner's Cup]]. At the end of 2001. Bosna was far most successful handball team in after war Bosnia and Herzegovina. But that year brought financial breakdown, Bosna lost most of its players and club staff, which resulted in total result crisis which lasted to 2005. From 2001 till today Bosna has not achieved significant honors, only managing to stay in the First league through good home form.\n\nOnly after 2005 club got its financial aid with signing more sponsors. Results were visible after just one season, in 2006 Bosna finished eight out of twelve clubs in the league, which was relief because club was in past season always on edge being relegated. In 2007 club finished second in Premier League and will play in [[EHF Cup]]. This is big success for club, because it is first time since 2002 that Bosna qualified form one European competition. Edhem Sir\u0107o was first scorer for Bosna, being followed by Amir \u010caki\u0107 and Faruk Halilbegovi\u0107.\n\n=== 2007/2008 season ===\nFor the 2007/2008 season Bosna was reinforced by three new players. [[Muhamed Mustafi\u0107]], a right wing, returned to his parent club after playing 3 successful seasons in HC Bosna Sarajevo which competed successfully in the [[EHF Champions League]], and later the [[EHF Cup Winner's Cup]] where they played semi-finals. Kenan Ahi\u0107, on loan to the Sarajevo side last season returned to Visoko. The third player is Aldin Begagi\u0107, a pivot men from Krivaja and later Gora\u017ede. \n \nIn the first round of [[EHF Cup]] Bosna played against handball club Sutjeska from [[Nik\u0161i\u0107]], and passed after playing draw match in Nik\u0161i\u0107, and scored win in Visoko. Result in Nik\u0161i\u0107 was 21-21, but in Visoko home team Bosna defeated Montenegrin side by 38-27. In second round Bosna was defeated by Gold Club from Slovenia. The first game in Slovenia was a draw (37-37), but the Slovenians managed to defeat the Bosnian side at home, and went through.\n\n==Accomplishments==\n\n=== Domestic ===\n'''Yugoslavia'''\n\n*'''[[Socialist Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina|SRBiH]] Cup:''' \n**'''Winners (4)''': 1965, 1968, 1971, 1982\n*'''[[Yugoslav Handball Cup]]'''\n** Runner-up (1): 1965\n*'''[[Yugoslav Handball Championship]]'''\n** 1975 - 4th place\n\n'''Bosnia and Herzegovina \u2013 5'''\n\n*'''[[Handball Cup of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Cup]]:''' \n**'''Winners (3):''' 1995, 1998, 2001\n**Runner-up (1): 2018\n*'''[[Handball Championship of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Championship]]:''' \n**'''Winners (2):''' 1997, 1999\n**Runner-up (1): 2007\n\n=== European  ===\n\n* '''EHF Cup'''\n** 1/8 finalist: 1999/2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurohandball.com/ec/ehfc/men/1999-00/round/2/1/8-finals|title=European Handball Federation - 1999/00 Men's EHF Cup / 1/8-finals|website=www.eurohandball.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former players==\n\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Sr\u0111an Praljak]]\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Ranko Antovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Nevzad Sir\u0107o \n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Kemal Vra\u017ei\u0107\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Zdenko Antovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Adis Had\u017ei\u0107\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Edhem Sir\u0107o\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Mahir D\u017eud\u017eo\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Faruk Vra\u017eali\u0107]]\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Muhamed Mustafi\u0107]]\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Faruk Halilbegovi\u0107]]\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Amir \u010caki\u0107\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Mirza Hurem\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Adnan Harmandi\u0107]]\n\n==Notable former coaches==\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Sr\u0111an Praljak\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Halid Demirovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Zdenko Antovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Nevzad Sir\u0107o\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Senad Skopljak\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://www.rkbosna.ba Official page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070314001447/http://www.rkbosna.ba/ekipa.php Current roster of team]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071230021805/http://www.rkbosna.ba/galerija_seniori.php Photo gallery, 1954-2006]\n\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina handball clubs]]\n[[Category:Visoko]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox handball club\n| clubname    = '''HC Bosna Visoko'''\n| image       = \n| fullname    = Handball club Bosna\n| short name  = \n| founded     = 1954\n| ground      = Sport Centre Mladost\n| capacity    = \n| chairman    = Adnan Deli\u0107\n| manager     = Senad Skopljak \n| league      = \n| season      = \n| position    = \n| website     = http://www.rkbosna.ba \n| colour1     = green\n| colour2     = white\n| pattern_la1 = \n| pattern_b1  = _unknown\n| pattern_ra1 = \n| pattern_sh1 = \n| leftarm1    = \n| body1       = \n| rightarm1   = \n| shorts1     = \n| pattern_la2 = \n| pattern_b2  = \n| pattern_ra2 = \n| pattern_sh2 = \n| leftarm2    = \n| body2       = \n| rightarm2   = \n| shorts2     = \n}}\n\n'''RK Bosna Visoko''' (''[[Bosnian language|Bosnian]]: Rukometni klub Bosna'') is a [[team handball|handball]] club from [[Visoko, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Visoko]], founded on 9 February 1954. RK Bosna competes in the [[Handball Championship of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] and the [[Handball Cup of Bosnia and Herzegovina]].\n\n== History ==\n<!-- Commented out because image was deleted: [[Image:Igrali\u0161te.jpg|thumb|200px|left|Old asphalted playing-field of RK Bosna]] -->\nAfter Ferid Semi\u0107 brought the first [[Team handball|handball]] ball to [[Visoko, Bosnia and Herzegovina|Visoko]], and when the congress was held on 9 February 1954, sport society Mladost was born. Its founders were Ferid Semi\u0107 and Vladimir Joli\u0107. The first game was held on 9 May 1954 when Visoko was beaten by [[Sarajevo]] by 25:9.\n\n===Handball club Bosna established===\nOn 15 March 1960 club's name Mladost was renamed to Handball Club Bosna. From the autumn of 1962 all games were held at city's asphalted handball playing-field. The most important moment for Visoko's handball team was the arrival of Sr\u0111an Praljak: the first real handball coach, who from 1 August 1960 to 31 July 1971 created the characteristic Visoko handball school. This was second generation of players with Nevzad Sir\u0107o at the helm, who was one of the best players in the history of Visoko's handball.\n\n===First Yugoslav league===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:Nevzad Sirco.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Nevzad Sir\u0107o, one of the best players ever from Visoko]] -->\nAfter only four years, Bosna entered the strong First league of [[Yugoslavia]] in 1964, and at same time won the Cup of Bosnia and Herzegovina, and runner-up in Cup of Yugoslavia. On 20 May 1970, club was renamed to RK Vitex, after economic giant Vitex, and continued with that name until 1991. The club remained in the First handball league of Yugoslavia for seven years until it was relegated to second in 1971/72 season. This wasn't for long, and after only one year, the club re-entered the first league and achieved its best place ever: fourth in 1974/75 season in one of the best handball leagues of that time. It stayed for two more seasons when Bosna was relegated in 1976 to Second Yugoslav league, which was last season for club in first league. Altogether, Bosna have played 10 seasons in elite Yugoslav handball league, having won 3 times Cup of Bosnia and Herzegovina. Pioneer selection became champions of Yugoslavia in 1971. Juniors were two times runners-up, in 1973 and 1974. Zdenko Antovi\u0107 became standard player for Yugoslavian national handball team in 1976, 1977 and 1979, other players like Kemal Vra\u017ei\u0107 and Ranko Antovi\u0107 didn't stay for long.\n\n===Decline===\nAt around this time, the game of handball began to be played in halls, and asphalted playing-fields started to be abandoned. Visoko didn't have a hall so it was forced to play in other towns like [[Sarajevo]], [[Vogo\u0161\u0107a]], [[Zavidovi\u0107i]] and [[Had\u017ei\u0107i]]. After only three seasons Bosna was relegated again to the second league in 1975/76 season. From then until 1991, the club couldn't get back into first league. The most significant result was winning the cup of [[SR BiH]] in 1981. Finally, Visoko got its first handball hall, sports centre Mladost, which was finished on 9 April 1986.\n\n===War and recovery===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:RkBosna.jpg|thumb|200px|Handball derby in Visoko between home team Bosna, and Sarajevo]] -->\nAfter the devastating [[Bosnian War]], the hall and clubs offices were damaged, but Bosna started to recover. From 1995 Bosna twice won the First league of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] (seasons 1996/97 and 1998/99) and record three times Cup of BiH (1995, 1998 and in 2001). Bosna had involvement in [[European Handball Federation|EHF]] competitions such as [[EHF Cup]] and [[EHF Cup Winner's Cup]]. At the end of 2001. Bosna was far most successful handball team in after war Bosnia and Herzegovina. But that year brought financial breakdown, Bosna lost most of its players and club staff, which resulted in total result crisis which lasted to 2005. From 2001 till today Bosna has not achieved significant honors, only managing to stay in the First league through good home form.\n\nOnly after 2005 club got its financial aid with signing more sponsors. Results were visible after just one season, in 2006 Bosna finished eight out of twelve clubs in the league, which was relief because club was in past season always on edge being relegated. In 2007 club finished second in Premier League and will play in [[EHF Cup]]. This is big success for club, because it is first time since 2002 that Bosna qualified form one European competition. Edhem Sir\u0107o was first scorer for Bosna, being followed by Amir \u010caki\u0107 and Faruk Halilbegovi\u0107.\n\n=== 2007/2008 season ===\nFor the 2007/2008 season Bosna was reinforced by three new players. [[Muhamed Mustafi\u0107]], a right wing, returned to his parent club after playing 3 successful seasons in HC Bosna Sarajevo which competed successfully in the [[EHF Champions League]], and later the [[EHF Cup Winner's Cup]] where they played semi-finals. Kenan Ahi\u0107, on loan to the Sarajevo side last season returned to Visoko. The third player is Aldin Begagi\u0107, a pivot men from Krivaja and later Gora\u017ede. \n \nIn the first round of [[EHF Cup]] Bosna played against handball club Sutjeska from [[Nik\u0161i\u0107]], and passed after playing draw match in Nik\u0161i\u0107, and scored win in Visoko. Result in Nik\u0161i\u0107 was 21-21, but in Visoko home team Bosna defeated Montenegrin side by 38-27. In second round Bosna was defeated by Gold Club from Slovenia. The first game in Slovenia was a draw (37-37), but the Slovenians managed to defeat the Bosnian side at home, and went through.\n\n==Accomplishments==\n\n=== '''Domestic''' ===\n'''Yugoslavia'''\n\n*'''[[Socialist Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina|SRBiH]] Cup:''' \n**'''Winners (4)''': 1965, 1968, 1971, 1982\n*'''[[Yugoslav Handball Cup]]'''\n** Runner-up (1): 1965\n*'''[[Yugoslav Handball Championship]]'''\n** 1975 - 4th place\n\n'''Bosnia and Herzegovina \u2013 5'''\n\n*'''[[Handball Cup of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Cup]]:''' \n**'''Winners (3):''' 1995, 1998, 2001\n**Runner-up (1): 2018\n\n*'''[[Handball Championship of Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian Championship]]:''' \n**'''Winners (2):''' 1997, 1999\n**Runner-up (1): 2007\n\n=== European  ===\n\n* '''EHF Cup'''\n** 1/8 finalist: 1999/2000<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurohandball.com/ec/ehfc/men/1999-00/round/2/1/8-finals|title=European Handball Federation - 1999/00 Men's EHF Cup / 1/8-finals|website=www.eurohandball.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Notable former players== \n\n\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} [[Sr\u0111an Praljak]]\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Ranko Antovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Nevzad Sir\u0107o \n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Kemal Vra\u017ei\u0107\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Zdenko Antovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Adis Had\u017ei\u0107\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Edhem Sir\u0107o\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Mahir D\u017eud\u017eo\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Faruk Vra\u017eali\u0107]]\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Muhamed Mustafi\u0107]]\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Faruk Halilbegovi\u0107]]\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Amir \u010caki\u0107\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Mirza Hurem\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} [[Adnan Harmandi\u0107]]\n\n==Notable former coaches==\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Sr\u0111an Praljak\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Halid Demirovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Zdenko Antovi\u0107\n*{{flagicon|YUG}} Nevzad Sir\u0107o\n*{{flagicon|BIH}} Senad Skopljak\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n== External links ==\n\n*[http://www.rkbosna.ba Official page]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070314001447/http://www.rkbosna.ba/ekipa.php Current roster of team]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20071230021805/http://www.rkbosna.ba/galerija_seniori.php Photo gallery, 1954-2006]\n\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina handball clubs]]\n[[Category:Visoko]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Heading with bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HC_Bosna_Visoko"}
{"title_page": "United States Air Forces Central Command Band", "text_new": "[[File:'Falcon' Band Shares Musical Talents in Kyrgyzstan DVIDS208367.jpg|thumb|Members of band in [[Kyrgyzstan]]]]\nThe '''[[United States Air Forces Central Command]] Band''' also known as the '''AFCENT Band''' or '''Blue Steel''' is an [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] [[military band]]. It is based at [[Al Udeid Air Base]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]]. Being a [[contemporary music]]al group, its repertoire ranges from genres like [[Pop music|pop]] to [[country music]] and [[rock-n-roll]]. It is composed of active duty airmen as well as reservist and [[Air National Guard]]smen. It is the only deployed musical unit of the USAF. It provides music for official functions, and community relations.<ref name=\"af\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bandofthesouth.ang.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=14185|website=bandofthesouth.ang.af.mil|title=Air National Guard Band of the South|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> These include embassy ceremonies and public engagement with the people of the country in which it is visiting. Its primary area of responsibility consists of the countries in the [[Middle East]] and [[Central Asia]].<ref name=\"lompocrecord\">{{cite web|url=https://lompocrecord.com/news/local/military/vandenberg/afcent-band-builds-relationships-with-a-universal-language/article_07b90139-3b72-56b9-96b5-020272902091.amp.html|website=lompocrecord.com|title=lompocrecord.com/news/local/military/vandenberg/afcent-band-builds-relationships-with-a-universal-language/article_07b90139-3b72-56b9-96b5-020272902091.amp.html|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> It has performed in countries such as [[Djibouti]],<ref name=\"africom\">{{cite web|url=https://www.africom.mil/media-room/Article/30330/u-s-air-forces-central-command-band-builds-cultural-bridge-in-balbala|website=africom.mil|title=United States Africa Command|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> the [[United Arab Emirates]],<ref name=\"usafa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usafa.edu/news/afcent-band-hits-right-notes-adab/|title=AFCENT band hits right notes on ADAB - United States Air Force Academy|website=usafa.edu|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> [[Kuwait]]<ref name=\"dvidshub\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dvidshub.net/image/5926944/afcent-band-rocks-kuwait|title=DVIDS - Images - AFCENT band rocks Kuwait &#91;Image 10 of 13&#93;|website=dvidshub.net|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> and [[Kyrgyzstan]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|1}}\n\n[[Category:Bands of the United States Air Force]]\n[[Category:Military bands located outside their country of origin]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:'Falcon' Band Shares Musical Talents in Kyrgyzstan DVIDS208367.jpg|thumb|Members of band in [[Kyrgyzstan]].]]\nThe '''[[United States Air Forces Central Command]] Band''' also known as the '''AFCENT Band''' or '''Blue Steel''' is an [[United States Air Force|Air Force]] [[military band]]. It is based at [[Al Udeid Air Base]] in [[Doha]], [[Qatar]]. Being a [[contemporary music]]al group, it's repertoire ranges from genres like [[Pop music|pop]] to [[country music]] and [[rock-n-roll]]. It is composed of active duty airmen as well as reservist and [[Air National Guard]]smen. It is the only deployed musical unit of the USAF. It provides music for official functions, and community relations.<ref name=\"af\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bandofthesouth.ang.af.mil/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=14185|website=bandofthesouth.ang.af.mil|title=Air National Guard Band of the South|accessdate=2020-03-13}}</ref> These include embassy ceremonies amd public engagement with the people of the country in which it's visiting. It's primary area of responsibility consists of the countries in the [[Middle East]] and [[Central Asia]].<ref name=\"lompocrecord\">{{cite web|url=https://lompocrecord.com/news/local/military/vandenberg/afcent-band-builds-relationships-with-a-universal-language/article_07b90139-3b72-56b9-96b5-020272902091.amp.html|website=lompocrecord.com|title=lompocrecord.com/